<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Groups Spent $697M Lobbying  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Health insurers, high-tech companies, banks and other
interest groups spent $697 million to lobby Congress and the federal agencies
during the first six months of 1999, a new report says.
</P>
<P>
	   That's $116 million per month spent to influence the federal government,
according to the report being released Thursday by FEC Info, an Internet
consulting firm that specializes in tracking political money.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is an incredible amount,'' said Tony Raymond, a founder of FEC Info.
``These are the moneymakers. They have two groups they work on: the legislators,
the people who write the laws, but they also work on their home offices, saying
'Our competitors are spending this much on lobbying; we need to catch up with
them.'''
</P>
<P>
	   The amount is similar to the $710 million spent on lobbying during the first
six months of 1998, according to figures compiled by researchers at the Center
for Responsive Politics, which also analyzed federal lobbying disclosure
reports. FEC Info is a subsidiary of the Internet public policy and health care
technology company Netivation.com.
</P>
<P>
	   This time around, the health care industry spent more on lobbying than
anyone else, spending $95.5 million as Congress debated whether to impose new
regulations on managed care health plans. Congress didn't pass the new rules.
</P>
<P>
	   In second place were communications and technology companies, which fought
over providing high-speed Internet access and sought approval for several
telecommunications company mergers. Those companies spent $94.6 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The financial services industry, which won approval of a long-sought bill to
drop Depression-era barriers against banks, insurance companies and investment
houses competing against each other, spent $89.8 million on lobbying.
</P>
<P>
	   The two biggest individual spenders were the American Medical Association,
which spent $8.8 million, and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which spent $8.4
million lobbying on health insurance and other issues.
</P>
<P>
	   The food and tobacco giant Philip Morris spent $7.5 million, but the amount
of money the tobacco companies spent on lobbying declined since Congress did not
take up any anti-smoking legislation during the just-concluded session.
</P>
<P>
	   The Associated Press reported in September that five major cigarette
companies, including Philip Morris, spent $11 million from January through June.
That was a big drop from the first half of 1998, when the industry poured $37
million into an extraordinary effort to defeat legislation that would have
raised cigarette taxes by $1.10 per pack and would have given the federal
government new power to regulate nicotine.
</P>
<P>
	   The top lobbying firm was Cassidy &AMP; Associates, which was paid $10 million
during the first half of 1999. Former Reps. Fred Rooney of Pennsylvania and
Marty Russo of Illinois both work for the firm, whose clients have included
Boeing, Exxon, and a number of colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
	   Patton Boggs, which counts former Rep. Greg Laughlin of Texas in its ranks,
was second at $9.2 million. The firm has represented the Association of Trial
Lawyers, MCI Worldcom and US Airways.
</P>
<P>
	   Verner, Liipfert, Bernhard, McPherson and Hand, home to former Senate
majority leaders George Mitchell and Bob Dole and former Texas Gov. Ann
Richards, was paid $7.3 million.
</P>
<P>
	   During the first six months of 1998, the powerhouse firm received $7.1
million from the tobacco companies alone, but the industry paid just $80,000
during the same period this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0002 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
