<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers Sign Olson to 2-Year Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Dodgers, continuing to improve their
bullpen, signed right-handed reliever Gregg Olson to a $3.5 million, two-year
contract Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Olson, 33, had a career-best 9-4 record with 14 saves and a 3.71 ERA in 61
appearances for the Arizona Diamondbacks last year. He gets $1.25 million this
year and $1.75 million in 2001, and the Dodgers have a $2.25 million option for
2002 with a $500,000 buyout.
</P>
<P>
	   Olson began the season as Arizona's closer, and struggled in that role. He
was replaced in midseason when the Diamondbacks acquired Matt Mantei from the
Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
	   After that, Olson was used in a setup role and went 5-0 with a 2.61 ERA.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are excited about the acquisition of Gregg Olson, a talented setup man,"
Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said. "He fits into our offseason plans and
provides the manager with the flexibility to solidify his bullpen. This is a
quality reliever who definitely shortens a game and brings added leadership to
our clubhouse."
</P>
<P>
	   Olson revived his career after joining Arizona as a non-roster invitee to
spring training in the club's inaugural season of 1998, earning 30 saves.
</P>
<P>
	   Olson started his career saving 160 games with the Baltimore Orioles from
1989-93, becoming the first closer in major league history to record 20 or more
saves in each of his first five seasons. He has a 40-37 record with a 3.43 ERA,
and his 217 saves ranks 23rd on the career list.
</P>
<P>
	   "Gregg is an experienced veteran who strengthens our bullpen," Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said. "I am thrilled with the depth of experience we have
in relief."
</P>
<P>
	   The Dodgers, who had problems in middle relief and setup roles last season,
also acquired Terry Adams from the Chicago Cubs; Dan Naulty from the New York
Yankees and signed free agents Orel Hershiser and Mike Fetters in the offseason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
