<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Flu Drugs Selling Briskly  </HEADLINE>
    By PHIL GALEWITZ AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- You're tired and achy. Your throat hurts and you can't get
out of bed. Yes, the flu season has arrived.
</P>
<P>
	   The good news is this year doctors have two new prescription drugs in their
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
	   So far the new medicines are selling briskly, spurred by the early onset of
the flu season across the United States as well as intense advertising
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   But there are doubts whether the drugs -- Relenza and Tamiflu -- can sustain
the momentum: That's because patients need to start taking the medications
within 48 hours after symptoms appear, and some doctors are not convinced the
relatively expensive medicines will dramatically shorten the suffering.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Glaxo Wellcome, maker of Relenza, and Roche Laboratories, maker of
Tamiflu, are betting they can change the way patients and the medical profession
approaches the ailment that affects up to 50 million people each year and causes
up to 40,000 deaths.
</P>
<P>
	   The drugmakers are targeting cities hit hard by the flu with advertising as
they pitch their medication to doctors. Glaxo has hired Wayne Knight, who played
the pesky mailman Newman on "Seinfeld," to personify the flu bug in its ads.
</P>
<P>
	   Relenza has the early lead. More than 51,000 Relenza prescriptions were
written in the week ending Dec. 24, more than four times the level in the first
week of December, according to IMS Health, a market research firm. Tamiflu,
though, is coming on strong. Tamiflu sold nearly 45,000 prescriptions the same
week, or nearly 10 times more than in the first week of December.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're seeing a nice solid start from both products," said Jeff Chafkin, an
analyst with PaineWebber. "They're not blockbusters, but the early trends look
good."
</P>
<P>
	   Lori Schieri, an administrator at the Hospital of the University of
Pennsylvania in Philadelphia, took Tamiflu just hours after she developed the
bad cough, headache and 101 degree fever associated with the flu. That was on
Friday, Dec. 17. By Saturday night her fever broke. And she was back to work on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was great to feel better so quickly," said Schieri, who recalled the
previous time she had the flu, she was in bed for a week.
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike Schieri, most people either try to get through the flu using
over-the-counter medicines that try to control symptoms. And those who decide to
see a doctor, often do so only after being sick for several days. That's a
problem as the new flu drugs are only useful in the first two days after
symptoms appear. The medicines work by blocking the advance of flu through the
body.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a quagmire because people often wait three days or more to come in,"
said Dr. Thomas Weida, a family doctor in Hershey, Pa.
</P>
<P>
	   Flu can typically last five to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
	   Health experts say neither of the flu drugs should replace flu vaccines --
the shots clearly offer people a better chance at staying flu-free all winter.
The new drugs will help those that neglect to get a shot or those that get sick
even with the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a step forward, but not a giant step forward," said Dr. John
Bartlett, chief of infectious diseases at Johns Hopkins University School of
Medicine in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
	   He said because the drug needs to get to patients quickly, some doctors may
be forced to prescribe it over the telephone without seeing the patient.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention confirms this flu season
started earlier than usual, and has been spotted in all regions of the country.
So far, only Type A, the most common type of influenza, has appeared.
</P>
<P>
	   That's not so good news for the makers of the new flu drugs, which trumpet
their ability to treat both the A and B strains.
</P>
<P>
	   Type A can also be treated by older flu medicines such as the generic drug
amantadine. That anti-viral drug typically sells for $10, compared to the
$45-$65 for Relenza and Tamiflu. Not all insurers cover the new drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   Amantadine also helps reduce the length of the flu but has side effects the
can cause users to lose balance or think clearly. Tamiflu's pill has fewer of
those side effects, but can cause nausea. The main side effects from Relenza are
sinus problems and diarrhea. Because Relenza must be inhaled, it also is not
recommended for patients with asthma or other chronic lung diseases.
</P>
<P>
	   Tamiflu should have an advantage over Relenza simply because most people
prefer a pill over an inhaler, said Myron Holubiak, president of Roche
Laboratories. Both drugs are taken twice a day for five days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0024 </TRAILER>
