<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa-Europe Trade Threatened  </HEADLINE>
   By DANIEL J. WAKIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- That icy thimble of spirits called grappa
goes down with a chill and a burn -- and now threatens to bring the roof down on
one of South Africa's great economic projects: a $17 billion free trade
agreement with Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   Italy says it will not ratify the agreement, which was to have gone into
effect on Saturday. The reason: South African distillers make their own version
of the spirit and have the audacity to call it grappa.
</P>
<P>
	   An Italian Foreign Ministry spokesman, speaking Wednesday in Rome, said
Italy would not ratify the deal without a commitment from South Africa that
grappa is a trademark that belongs exclusively to the Italian regions where it
is produced. However, the ministry said later it would be willing to accept a
gradual phasing out of the name by South African distillers.
</P>
<P>
	   Potentially at stake is a far-reaching free trade agreement that cut tariffs
on South Africa's import and export trade with Europe -- a key economic policy
that took four years of lobbying by then-President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
	   For Italy, it is a question of national tradition. Or maybe spirit.
</P>
<P>
	   Italy produces 40 million bottles of grappa a year, compared to about 30,000
in South Africa. Grappa, the distillation of the sediment left after pressing
grapes to make wine, is entrenched in Italian culture. It is drunk as shots on
ski slopes, a digestive drink after dinner, a side car to an espresso in a
coffee bar, a morning jolt for blue collar workers.
</P>
<P>
	   The colorless liquor, usually about 40 percent alcohol, is often kept in the
freezer and is akin to schnapps.
</P>
<P>
	   In South Africa, grappa has grown more fashionable, although production only
began six years ago and consumption remains small. None of the homemade variety
is exported.
</P>
<P>
	   The Italians ``are jealous that our quality is so high,'' said George Dalla
Cia, who runs the grappa operation at the Meerlust Estate winery near Cape Town,
the largest of three South African grappa producers. Three generations of Dalla
Cia's family made grappa in Italy's Friuli region.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's quite silly, actually. Grappa is not a region at all, like champagne
or cognac. It's more a generic name. So where do you really draw the line? Will
they want to protect the name pizza and pasta afterwards?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The matter is anything but silly to Luigi Odello, national secretary of the
National Grappa Institute in Brescia, Italy.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Grappa is only Italian, both by tradition and etymology,'' he said, saying
the word comes from ``krappa,'' used by the medieval Lombard people of northern
Italy. Traditionally, it has been produced from Italian vines, by Italians,
using traditional Italian methods.
</P>
<P>
	   And, he triumphantly concludes, the European Union gave Italy the exclusive
rights to the ``grappa'' name in 1989.
</P>
<P>
	   The grappa grapple is only the latest obstacle to hold up the agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of a separate ``wine and spirits'' pact, South Africa agreed to
phase out the use of ``sherry'' and ``port,'' under pressure from Spain and
Portugal. The Greeks have threatened over Ouzo and the Irish over Irish whiskey.
</P>
<P>
	   All 15 members of the European Union have to ratify the agreement for it to
take permanent effect. Italy's action appears to have flummoxed even the EU,
whose lawyers were studying the legal implications on Wednesday. It was unclear
whether Italy had the power to undermine the entire pact or just the separate
wine and spirits accord.
</P>
<P>
	   Nevertheless, South African grappa makers can read between the lines.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think we will eventually have to change the name, because of what it
could mean to South Africa -- the loss of millions of rands,'' Dalla Cia said.
``It's not very fair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0026 </TRAILER>
