<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Jan. 6, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bradley, Gore Clash in N.H. Debate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DURHAM. N.H. (AP) -- Democratic presidential hopeful Bill Bradley accused Al
Gore Wednesday night of deliberately distorting his proposal to expand health
coverage, but the vice president shot back in the first debate of the election
year that his rival's plan would leave many New Hampshire residents "high and
dry." Prodded by debate moderator Peter Jennings to say whether Gore had ever
taken a quote or vote out of context, Bradley instantly replied, "Yes." The vice
president, Bradley said, "offended me" by claiming he would hurt
African-Americans and Latinos and by saying his health care plan would
shortchange many Americans.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Algerian Held on Immigration Charges
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- An Algerian suspected of having links to a countryman
charged with trying to smuggle explosives into the United States was ordered
held without bond Wednesday. Abdel Hakim Tizegha, 29, is charged with illegally
entering the country and eluding federal officers at the Canadian border. He was
arrested Dec. 24. No link has been made in court between Tizegha and Ahmed
Ressam, who has pleaded innocent to federal charges accusing him of having
bomb-making materials in his rental car as he entered the country on Dec. 14.
But newspaper reports have said that Tizegha is linked to Ressam.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israelis Leave More of West Bank
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel completed one of its last pullbacks from the West
Bank on Wednesday, in a handover that was quick and unemotional. The withdrawal
ended a seven-week deadlock between the two sides over a relatively minor issue
-- whether the Palestinians would have a say in sketching the maps of the
partial troop withdrawals. Israeli and Palestinian officials were mum about how
the dispute was resolved, but both sides said privately the other gave in.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IRA Wants British Army Withdrawal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- The Irish Republican Army, under pressure to disarm,
accused British authorities Wednesday of straining Northern Ireland's peace
agreement by delaying military cutbacks in the province. In its traditional new
year's message, the outlawed IRA said the British government had "no excuse" for
failing to publish a schedule of troop withdrawals and army-base closures in
Northern Ireland. Under the 1998 Good Friday peace accord, the IRA is expected
to completely disarm by May 2000, and the British government pledged to publish
a schedule of its plans for troop withdrawals.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuban-Americans Protest Decision
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Touching off angry protests by hundreds of Cuban-Americans,
the U.S. government decided Wednesday to send 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez back to
Cuba because "this little boy ... belongs with his father." Elian has been in
the middle of an international tug-of-war since he was found Thanksgiving Day
clinging to an inner tube at sea after his mother, stepfather and nine others
died while trying to reach Florida. He has been living with relatives in Miami,
who have insisted they could give Elian a better life than his father could back
in Cuba.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Home Work Safety Rules Withdrawn
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Responding to a firestorm of criticism from lawmakers and
corporate America, the Labor Department withdrew an advisory letter Wednesday
that had said companies have the same safety responsibilities for employees
working at home as in the office. However, angry Republicans in Congress said
they still plan to investigate the circumstances surrounding the department's
actions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gateway Shares Fall After Warning
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Shares of Gateway Inc. fell nearly 10 percent Wednesday
after the computer maker warned that fourth-quarter earnings would miss
expectations, blaming a decline in sales due to Y2K fears and component supply
problems. The company said it expects to show a profit of about 37 cents per
share for the three months ended Dec. 31, about 7 cents less than expectations
of analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Lower at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese share prices fell Thursday morning on hefty selling
of high-technology issues, despite Wall Street's overnight rebound. The Nikkei
Stock Average ended the morning session down 197.36 points to 18,345.19.
Overnight on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 124.72 points to
11,122.65.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
No. 8 Duke Defeats Virginia 109-100, OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Chris Carrawell had 25 points Wednesday night
as No. 8 Duke rallied from a 10-point second-half deficit for a 109-100 overtime
victory over Virginia. It was the 23rd consecutive Atlantic Coast Conference win
for the Blue Devils (10-2, 1-0) and their 10th straight against the Cavaliers
(9-4, 0-1). But Virginia, which lost to Duke three times last season by an
average of 43 points, gave the Blue Devils all they could handle as they opened
defense of their league title.
</P>
