<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blumenthal says Purple Heart Museum money was mismanaged  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - After spending nearly $620,000 of public and
private money, the organizers of the National Purple Heart Museum have nothing
to show but a $33,000 set of blueprints, according to a report by the state's
Attorney General.
<P>
	   Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said Joseph Donahue, the project's
former executive director, squandered donations and mismanaged cash that was
supposed to build the museum in Enfield.
</P>
<P>
	   Blumenthal said bookkeeping records for the National Purple Heart Museum
Committee Inc. were so incomplete that it is nearly impossible to track how and
when money was spent.
</P>
<P>
	   The committee, which was formed in 1986 to build a museum dedicated to
recipients of the Purple Heart service award, received two state grants. In
1992, they received $250,000 for planing and design costs, and $1 million in
1998. Half of the $1 million grant was supposed to be matched with private
donations.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1997, Persian Gulf War commander Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf took a post
on the museum's advisory board.
</P>
<P>
	   But after spending about $500,000 of the state money and another $120,000 of
private donations, the only thing the organization has to show is a $33,000
architectural design plan for the museum, Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
	   The organization has also failed to collect the $18.75 million of private
donations that it promised to raise in its 1997 state grant application,
Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
	   According to Blumenthal's investigation, Donahue took a $6,000 private
donation for the museum, kept $500 and funneled the rest to his wife's bank
account in Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   Blumenthal is referring the case to the chief state's attorney for possible
criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
	   Donahue left his post as executive director last year. A spokesperson for
the attorney general said Donahue has moved out of Connecticut, and Purple Heart
museum officials said he is working in the Washington, D.C. area. Attempts by
The Associated Press to reach Donahue through listings in that area were not
successful.
</P>
<P>
	   Blumenthal's report also criticizes the museum's board of directors for not
keeping closer tabs on Donahue.
</P>
<P>
	   "The board of directors repeatedly failed to address the financial condition
of (the museum project) or exercise proper oversight of its executive director,"
Blumenthal wrote in his report.
</P>
<P>
	   Chuck Alfano, the museum project's current executive director, said the
board has set up more oversight of his office.
</P>
<P>
	   Alfano said public funds have been withheld from the project while
Blumenthal has been investigating the mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think this will have a negative effect initially," Alfano said. "But I'm
confident this museum can be built."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-06-00 0101 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spending caps and public financing top senators' list for reform  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn (AP) - The state Senate's top Democrats want to put a cap
on campaign fund-raising and allow for public financing of some races through
taxpayer donations.
<P>
	   Senate President Pro Tempore Kevin Sullivan and Senate Majority Leader
George Jepsen say spending caps will eliminate an unfair fundraising advantage
enjoyed by incumbents and prevent candidates from building exorbitant campaign
war chests.
</P>
<P>
	   "We believe the caps we have proposed are fair, and we believe they are also
strict and reasonable," Sullivan, D-West Hartford, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Under their proposal, caps would begin in 2002 with gubernatorial candidates
allowed to raise $5 million. Candidates for other statewide offices could
collect $750,000. State senate races would be capped at $105,000 and candidates
in House races could raise $40,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Voluntary public financing would kick in for the 2002 gubernatorial
election, and would start in 2006 for all statewide offices. Money for campaigns
would come via a check-off on the state income tax form that would allow a $5
contribution taken out of any refund.
</P>
<P>
	   The public financing would be a dollar-for-dollar match to the candidate's
private fundraising. That means a gubernatorial candidate could raise $2.5
million from private sources and be eligible for $2.5 million in public
financing to stay within the cap.
</P>
<P>
	   During the last gubernatorial race, Gov. John G. Rowland raised $6.4
million. His opponent, Barbara Kennelly, raised $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
	   In order to receive the public money, candidates would not be allowed to
exceed the spending caps. If a candidate's opponent broke the cap, he would
receive a match of just 50 cents on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
	   Sullivan and Jepsen said legislative candidates should not be eligible for
public financing, largely because it would be too expensive.
</P>
<P>
	   Campaign spending caps have been ruled unconstitutional by the U.S. Supreme
Court, and Republican leaders blasted the proposal as an infringement on the
First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
	   "I find it shocking that they're suggesting the First Amendment be
rewritten," said Rep. Robert Ward, R-North Branford."I call upon them to come
back to their senses."
</P>
<P>
	   Sullivan and Jepsen say they're ready for a court battle to test the
legality of spending caps, and campaign finance reform advocates say it's time
to clamp down on the amount of money in politics.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a very strong step," said Karen Hobert Flynn, executive director of
Common Cause in Connecticut. "This has never been taken up by the Senate, so
this proposal is extraordinarily significant."
</P>
<P>
	   A bill that would have allowed for public financing of any candidate who
agreed to spending limits was debated in the House last year, but never made it
to a final vote.
</P>
<P>
	   But following former state Treasurer Paul Silvester's guilty plea to federal
corruption charges stemming from illegal fund-raising, lawmakers and state
agencies have been refocused on campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Elections Enforcement Commission voted last month to restrict
contributions from political action committees and political party committees
who now can donate as much as they choose. Lobbyists and their PACs would be
able to donate less to candidates for the Legislature and statewide offices as
well as to party committees.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the plan by Jepsen and Sullivan, candidates would be prohibited from
raising money for themselves or others from anyone doing state business that the
candidate may control while in office.
</P>
<P>
	   Sullivan and Jepsen said they may be willing to change the provisions of
their plan and tinker with the spending caps.
</P>
<P>
	   "We don't view this as the final word on public financing," said Jepsen,
D-Stamford. "We view it as a positive step forward in helping to frame the
debate in the coming months."
</P>
<P>
	   Rowland has said he is open to all campaign finance reform ideas, but would
not comment directly on the proposal made by Jepsen and Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
	   Rowland spokesman Dean Pagani said the governor plans to meet with
legislative leaders within the next month to discuss campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
	   "His hope is that they could come to some agreement about a proposal that
could be put forth in the Legislature," Pagani said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
