<HEADLINE> Bradley accuses Gore of deliberately distorting his health care  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   DURHAM. N.H. (AP) - Democratic presidential hopeful Bill Bradley accused
Al Gore Wednesday night of deliberately distorting his proposal to expand health
coverage, but the vice president shot back in the first debate of the election
year that his rival's plan would leave many New Hampshire residents "high and
dry."
<P>
	   Prodded by debate moderator Peter Jennings to say whether Gore had ever
taken a quote or vote out of context, Bradley instantly replied, "Yes."
</P>
<P>
	   The vice president, Bradley said, "offended me" by claiming he would hurt
African-Americans and Latinos and by saying his health care plan would
shortchange many Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   But Gore, standing a few feet away on a University of New Hampshire stage,
paraphrased Harry Truman's famous utterance: "I'm not giving him hell. I'm just
telling the truth and he thinks it's hell."
</P>
<P>
	   Gore held aloft a card that he said characterized Bradley's health plan and
contended the people of New Hampshire "would be left out, left high and dry" by
Bradley's plan.
</P>
<P>
	   "Let me tell you how the private sector works," retorted back Bradley, a
former New Jersey senator, adding that health insurance companies would quickly
try to fashion coverage to meet the new demand.
</P>
<P>
	   The exchange came one-third of the way through the 60-minute debate, the
first in a series of confrontations in which Democrats and Republicans will take
turns debating in the run-up to the first balloting of the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore is the national front-runner by far, but Bradley has mounted a
surprisingly strong challenge for the Democratic nomination, and is even or
ahead in the polling in advance of the first primary set for Feb. 1 in New
Hampshire. That prompted the vice president to allude to his "underdog" status.
</P>
<P>
	   "Your underdog pitch brings tears to my eyes," Bradley said wryly.
</P>
<P>
	   Said Gore: "I hope my upset victory brings tears to your eyes on Feb. 1."
</P>
<P>
	   Predictably, the reaction of voters in the audience was mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   Laura Akeley, a University of New Hampshire art student, said she arrived a
Gore a supporter and was leaving a Gore supporter, although she conceded "I can
see now why a lot of people support Bill Bradley."
</P>
<P>
	   Doug Mayer, 35, a radio talk-show producer from Randolph, said he had been
undecided, but was walking out whole-heartedly behind Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   The two candidates agreed on the need for stricter gun control laws and on
letting gays serve in the military. But Gore went further, saying he would not
appoint anyone to the Joint Chiefs of Staff who disagreed with his position on
homosexuals in the Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley suggested he would not need to resort to any such litmus test. "When
you're president, you are commander-in-chief and you issue orders. And soldiers
are good soldiers. And they follow your orders. ... whatever the policy is."
</P>
<P>
	   The rivals came prepared for battle, clashing on local issues - including
development within the White Mountain National Forest in northern New Hampshire
- as well as national concerns.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, who likes to boast of a candidacy of big ideas, said Gore was "in a
Washington bunker." That's understandable, he said, given the Republican
Congress, the Democratic fund-raising scandals and impeachment. "But the reality
is, the Democratic party shouldn't be in the Washington bunker with you," he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore responded, "I'm proud that I stayed and fought against the Gingrich
Congress."
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley launched a sharp attack on the Clinton-Gore administration's
handling of relations with Russia, saying the United States had not pushed hard
enough in the last eight years to reduce the stockpile of nuclear weapons and
had agreed to send international aid to Russia "knowing that corruption was
rampant."
</P>
<P>
	   Gore issued a defense, saying, "I think that in spite of the problems there
have been some successes, including a new leader committed to reform, a free
press and free elections."
</P>
<P>
	   The two men were given the chance to pose questions to one another, and Gore
used his turn to ask Bradley whether he believed he had made a mistake on any of
three votes he had cast: in favor of Ronald Reagan's budget cuts in 1981,
opposed to authorizing the ground war against Iraq in 1990 and against the
welfare reform law that President Clinton signed into law. Bradley defended each
vote.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said, "I think all three were mistakes." While serving in Congress,
Gore voted against the budget cuts and in favor of using force in Kuwait and as
vice president supported the welfare law.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore said he was worried that Bradley had refused to own up to any mistakes,
and was worried about that quality in a president.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley broke in to cite what he said was an error he had made: his vote in
1987 against confirmation of Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. "Now that
was a mistake," he said to laughter from the audience.
</P>
<P>
	   While Bradley said Gore was guilty of campaign distortions, Gore said he
wouldn't level that charge against his rival.
</P>
<P>
	   "I won't accuse him of that. If you want a no, I'll give you a no," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The opening question referred to Clinton and his sexual relationship with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said that anytime a president or public official lies, he undermines
his authority. But he offered no criticism of Gore's behavior during the
yearlong impeachment struggle.
</P>
<P>
	   The vice president said he thought he had served "the national interest
well" during that period, making plain his disapproval of Clinton's actions, yet
defending him against what he said was an unwarranted Republican attempt to
remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
	   For his part, despite a candidacy that boasts of time spent out of public
life, Bradley said politics is a "noble profession. I don't think it's corrupt
or deceitful ... The only way you are going to achieve something is through
politics," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
