<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> End Nears for Century-Old Okla. Farm  </HEADLINE>
    By RENEE RUBLE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   THOMAS, Okla. (AP) -- Miles from the closest paved road squats a small
A-frame house. Its wooden frame is sunken, as if the home just exhaled another
moment in its century-old life.
</P>
<P>
	   A petite, elderly woman in a flowered cotton smock shuffles in the kitchen.
Dinner time is approaching and the men should be returning from the fields.
</P>
<P>
	   Alice Horton spreads out shortening and flour for a pie crust. The
85-year-old hands press on a wooden rolling pin that is older than the state of
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
	   On this summer day, her 78-year-old brother Ed soon will be driven by hunger
and heat from the wheat fields.
</P>
<P>
	   Their parents started the homestead, and with 10 children -- six boys and
four girls -- it quickly became the community's social spot. It was one of the
first homes in the area to have a radio. Families would travel miles to hear
election results from the big, brown box.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, everyone stays home to watch cable television and eat microwaveable
food, she says.
</P>
<P>
	   At high noon, life erupts in a small, white dog that begins a piercing bark.
A short, pudgy man in overalls and a cap enters the kitchen. Ed Horton washes
his hands then checks the oven.
</P>
<P>
	   The Horton farm has survived the worst of Mother Nature -- the Dust Bowl --
and the worst of humankind -- two world wars. But what threatens the homestead's
future is close at heart.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't know what will happen when Ed and I are gone," Miss Horton says.
Neither one married. They only have each other and the farm.
</P>
<P>
	   No one gathers in town on the weekend anymore. The one-room schoolhouse is
gone. Most of the food has to be purchased. The trendy eats are disappointing.
The pair once substituted their meat and potato supper for a pizza.
</P>
<P>
	   "It wasn't good," she says. "No, no, Ed didn't care for it."
</P>
<P>
	   Over the years, Horton has seen machinery replace horses. Prayers have given
way to pesticides. And their friends' children have been seduced by city lights.
</P>
<P>
	   "Neighbors would help neighbors," he says. "Now you don't even know them.
You don't have to."
</P>
<P>
	   About one in seven Oklahomans was a farmer in 1900. Today, about one in 46
Oklahomans farm, the state Department of Agriculture says. The average size of a
farm has doubled.
</P>
<P>
	   But the profits farmers make are stuck in the past. The latest state figures
show that in 1997 the average net income for a farmer was $6,145.
</P>
<P>
	   Why do some continue to do it? Why do they work 12-hour days, seven-day
weeks, in scorching and freezing conditions without vacations to earn thousands
below the poverty level?
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a good life. This is what we all did, this is home," Horton says. "I'm
on my own and work for myself. I wouldn't change it. I would do it again."
</P>
<P>
	   The clock approaches one. The ice in the tea has melted. Horton shifts in
his chair.
</P>
<P>
	   He works for his brothers and sisters who died. For the farmers who didn't
make it through the droughts and the homesteads that fell to corporate
competition. And he will keep farming in the new century.
</P>
<P>
	   Someday, Horton says, he will retire -- "When I'm six feet under."
</P>
<P>
	   Until then, the wheat awaits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0107 </TRAILER>
