<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Mom Died Saving Son  </HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GUTKIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARMEN DE URIA, Venezuela (AP) -- When Venezuela's killer floods ravaged her
home, Andrea Prada lifted her 7-year-old son high above her head so he could
cling to a wooden beam for his life.
</P>
<P>
	   She didn't let go, even as an avalanche of water, mud and boulders crashed
down a mountain overlooking this seaside town and into the house.
</P>
<P>
	   Then Vangelis Prada felt his mother's hands go cold.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I told her 'wake up, Mommy, wake up!''' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
	   But Mrs. Prada did not wake up. She was among as many as 30,000 victims of
the mudslides unleashed Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
	   Her husband Oscar also died; of those in the house, only Vangelis and his
66-year-old grandmother, Rosario Segarra, survived.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Segarra, who survived in an air pocket inside a bathroom, held her
grandson as he described what happened the morning his parents drowned.
</P>
<P>
	   Their eyes bloodshot, their lips swollen from infection, and their bodies
bruised and stitched, they spoke to The Associated Press on the day last week
when Vangelis was released from Caracas' Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
	   As he gripped the beam begging his mother to respond, a wall collapsed,
giving Vangelis a concussion and a thick gash on his back. But the boy remained
conscious, holding on while the world around him crumbled in a deluge of mud and
water.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Prada -- a schoolteacher in Carmen de Uria -- may have done what most
any mother would do, but to her sister Elizabeth Granados, she was a hero.
</P>
<P>
	   ``She was a person of extraordinary spiritual values. Only someone like that
would give her life to save her child in the way that she did,'' Mrs. Granados
said.
</P>
<P>
	   When the waters subsided, Vangelis' grandmother crawled out of the bathroom
and found him badly hurt but still alive.
</P>
<P>
	   She comforted him for hours until a rescue worker came and pried Vangelis
from beneath the collapsed wall. The boy and his grandmother made their way to a
school where Mrs. Segarra spent a harrowing night trying to stem the child's
bleeding.
</P>
<P>
	   Help arrived by helicopter the next day, but only Vangelis was allowed to
board since helicopter space was reserved only for the most severely injured.
</P>
<P>
	   Vangelis spent two weeks in the hospital, most of it in intensive care.
Today he lives with relatives in the capital, Caracas, where he cries himself to
sleep at night and is getting help from a government psychologist. His
12-year-old sister, who was in Caracas and out of harm's way when the avalanches
hit, is still unable to discuss what happened.
</P>
<P>
	   Their two-story house, which their grandmother and her late husband built 35
years ago, has been reduced to rubble. Truck-sized boulders that tumbled down
the mountain litter the area where the house once stood.
</P>
<P>
	   Two weeks after the mudslides, Vangelis' father's body still lay in a body
bag in front of the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
	   Returning last week to the ruins, Vangelis' aunt, Mrs. Granados, placed a
strip of white tape reading ``Oscar Prada'' on the body bag.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He was always talking about how the world was going to end because people
were destroying the planet,'' said Mrs. Granados, who also lost her home to the
landslides in a nearby town.
</P>
<P>
	   Carmen de Uria is a ghost town now: A handful of national guardsmen fend off
looters and a few residents load belongings into vehicles. Most of the town was
simply washed into the Caribbean Sea.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Granados returned to the schoolhouse where her sister taught and her
nephew studied.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is her handwriting,'' she said of a lively poster describing magic
and fantasy. Mrs. Prada, she said, loved music and painting and passed along
that passion to her children.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Prada, whose body was dug up from the rubble more than a week after the
landslides, was buried Tuesday without ceremony in a numbered coffin along with
14 other mudslide victims at a Caracas cemetery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
