<HEADLINE> Bulls 77, Wizards 66  </HEADLINE>
    By NANCY ARMOUR AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- All the Chicago Bulls needed was Toni Kukoc.
</P>
<P>
	   Playing in his first game in almost two months, Kukoc hit his first four
shots and finished with a team-high 18 points Wednesday night as the Bulls beat
the Washington Wizards 77-66, snapping an 11-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
	   Kukoc, activated a few hours before the game after missing the last 24
because of lingering back spasms, looked pretty good for a guy who's been on an
extended layoff. He had 11 rebounds, five assists, two steals and two blocked
shots in 39 minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   His presence gave the woeful Bulls a desperately needed boost, and they
responded with a night of highs. Despite only dressing nine players, they scored
their most points in a first quarter (29), set a season-high for biggest lead
(19 points) and won for the first time since Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
	   Washington's 66 points were a franchise low, beating the 69 scored against
Houston in 1993. It also was the second-lowest in the NBA this season behind the
63 scored by Chicago on Monday. The Wizards were a dismal 24-of-84 (29 percent)
from the floor.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Bulls being the Bulls, they had to give their fans a late gut-check.
After a goaltending call gave Chicago a 66-52 lead at the end of the
third-quarter, the Wizards suddenly seemed to get interested in the game. They
opened the fourth quarter with an 11-0 run, including five points from Tracy
Murray, to close to 66-63 with 8:16 left to play.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bulls, finally looking worn out, didn't help themselves with four
turnovers in five possessions. They didn't score until Dickey Simpkins made the
first of two free throws with 6:04 left.
</P>
<P>
	   But that was the only enthusiasm Washington could muster. They went almost
nine minutes without a field goal, while Elton Brand then went on his own run,
scoring six points in a 2:20 span to put Chicago back up 73-63 with 1:51 left.
</P>
<P>
	   After that, all that was left was the celebrating.
</P>
<P>
	   Brand finished with 16 points and 16 rebounds for the Bulls. Fellow rookie
Ron Artest had 16 points, and Simpkins had 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
	   Murray led the Wizards with 18 points, including 3-of-6 from 3-point range.
Juwan Howard, who had 12, was the only other Wizard in double figures. Rod
Strickland was 0-of-9 from the floor.
</P>
<P>
	   With Kukoc leading the way, the Bulls actually looked like a real NBA team
for the first 2 1/2 quarters. He nailed a 13-foot jumper about 20 seconds into
the game, made three more shots, two free throws and had an assist as Chicago
jumped out to a 16-6 lead. He didn't miss a shot until there was four minutes
left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   Chicago led 29-18 at the end of the first quarter, but two layups from
Richard Hamilton closed the gap to 36-34 with 5:05 left in the first half. Kukoc
rescued the Bulls again with a layup -- with a goaltending assist from Jahidi
White -- to start an 11-0 run, and Chicago took a 50-36 lead at the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
