<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Waker Alerts Cairo To Pray  </HEADLINE>
   By TANALEE SMITH Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Bundled up against the winter chill, Garia Mohammed
Bayoumi treads a familiar path through the darkened streets of old Cairo,
thumping out a regular rhythm on a small drum and pausing to call sleeping
residents by name.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Wake up, Hassan! Wake up, Ali! Wake up and start your prayers!''
</P>
<P>
	   It is 2:30 a.m., and Bayoumi, wrapped in a long gray overcoat and dark
woolen scarf, is performing an annual ritual that dates back seven generations
in her family. She is a mesaharati, a public waker, who rouses faithful Muslims
for prayers and breakfast in the wee hours of the holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
	   During Ramadan, Muslims abstain from food, drink, smoking and sex from
sunrise to sunset as an act of sacrifice and purification. They break the fast
with a sunset meal, called iftar, and then wake early to eat a pre-dawn meal,
called sohour, before fasting again. Ramadan ends with the first sighting of the
crescent moon, likely today. However, if the moon is not seen, Ramadan ends a
day later, on Friday. The three-day Eid al-Fitr feast begins the following day.
</P>
<P>
	   Mesaharatis were once a common sight -- and sound -- throughout Cairo, but
now many neighborhoods are without a traditional waker. Sometimes young
entrepreneurs fill the void, clanging noisemakers through the streets, hoping to
be paid for their halfhearted services.
</P>
<P>
	   But Bayoumi, 52, is from the old school, trained by her father, whom she
accompanied as a child, learning the names of every head of household in the
neighborhood. Now, 36 years after she became the mesaharati of the Hosh Qadam
section of old Cairo, she is a respected figure.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A lot of people do not feel like Ramadan has started until they hear her
voice,'' said her son, Mohammed, 17. ``I am very proud of my mother.''
</P>
<P>
	   It is unusual for a woman to be a mesaharati, but Bayoumi's father had no
sons and she wanted to keep the family tradition alive. The people of the
neighborhood supported her, even turning away another mesaharati who tried to
take over her area in 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I feel a responsibility to wake the people,'' she said. ``I like them and
they like me.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bayoumi, who cleans lion cages at the National Circus during the day, begins
her night job with a cup of ginseng tea and a few puffs on a water pipe known as
a shisha at a coffee shop near her apartment. The shisha is habit; the tea is to
soothe her throat for hours of calling and singing.
</P>
<P>
	   And then she's ready. The regulars at the cafe bid her good luck as she
heads back out into the narrow, unpaved streets for her two-hour night journey.
</P>
<P>
	   Her loud voice, rising in pitch in the traditional call, rouses most. The
persistent drumming wakes others. And on some nights, Bayoumi also carries a
wooden walking stick and raps on the doors of those sound sleepers who have
requested special attention.
</P>
<P>
	   Children run out to hug the woman, distinctive in the light of her father's
rusted oil lantern, and two toddlers dance to the beat of her drum. Passers-by
press money into her hand, calling her by name and wishing her a happy holiday.
Groups of men in coffee shops squeeze into side streets, calling out their
greetings.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We saw her grandfather and father doing the same job,'' said an elderly
man sipping hot, sweet tea. ``Garia is one of the cornerstones of the area.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The neighborhood would not be the same without her,'' said Nabil el-Mihy
between puffs on a shisha pipe, lamenting that the tradition has been lost in
other areas of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
	   Bayoumi said that while Cairo has changed over the past decades, there is
still a need for her service.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People used to sleep early. TV has changed their lives and they stay up
late into the night,'' she said. ``But a lot of people are still waiting for me
to wake them up.''
</P>
<P>
	   Most residents tip her, paying extra for special services, such as an extra
rap on their door or adding the name of their young son to her repertoire during
his first fast.
</P>
<P>
	   Some people wait until the end of the month to tip, but others show their
appreciation during her moonlit walks. People come to their doors to hand her
small bills; residents on higher floors open their windows and lower baskets
containing money.
</P>
<P>
	   Bayoumi said neither illness nor bad weather can keep her from performing
her duties.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm going to keep my career until the last second of my life,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Catholic Church Defies Vatican  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China's state-controlled Catholic church defied the Vatican
today, ordaining five bishops in a ceremony that underscored the communist
government's nearly half-century rift with the pope.
</P>
<P>
	   Priests in white ceremonial vestments and nuns in black habits gathered with
several dozen believers for the ordination in Beijing's 95-year-old South
Cathedral. Presided over by a senior bishop in the state church, the ceremony
adhered to ritual, absent approval from the pope.
</P>
<P>
	   The timing seemed an intentional snub to the Vatican, something a Chinese
church official denied. Pope John Paul II was scheduled to ordain nine bishops
from seven other countries at St. Peter's Basilica in a ceremony later today
coinciding with the Roman Catholic Church's feast of the Epiphany.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We had no information about'' the Vatican ceremony, said Liu Bainian, vice
secretary of the China Patriotic Catholic Association. ``We do these ceremonies
according to the needs of our dioceses.''
</P>
<P>
	   Liu said the five were being elevated to replace bishops who were old or in
ill-health.
</P>
<P>
	   The Vatican has assailed the ordinations, calling them a disappointing
setback after positive signals in recent months that the two sides were ready to
improve relations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This gesture will raise obstacles that certainly hinder the process,''
Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   China and the Vatican have had no formal relations since 1951. Newly in
power, the Communist Party then kicked out missionaries and forced Catholics to
sever ties with the Vatican to end what the government saw as foreign
domination. The Vatican moved its ties to Taiwan, where many Chinese clerics
fled.
</P>
<P>
	   Now Beijing is interested in wooing rival Taiwan's last remaining diplomatic
allies to increase the island's isolation. While the Vatican has expressed
interest in re-establishing ties, the stumbling block remains papal authority,
which is mainly asserted through the pope's appointment of bishops.
</P>
<P>
	   The five bishops appointed in Beijing today will help minister to Catholics
whose numbers, even the official church admits, are swelling by 60,000 new
believers a year. China has nearly 5 million Catholics by official count but
missionaries say the real number of believers is closer to 12 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Many Catholics move between official and underground churches, where the
pope is openly venerated. The religious resurgence has forced the official
church into an uneasy coexistence with the unofficial church. Priests sometimes
conduct services in both, and state churches offer low-key prayers to the pope.
</P>
<P>
	   At Beijing's South Cathedral, a sign near a side courtyard celebrates the
Jubilee, the Holy Year on the 2000th anniversary of Jesus' birth in which
Catholics can gain pardon for sins. ``Christ: Yesterday, Today and Forever,''
read the sign.
</P>
<P>
	   ``With this new millennium, our church is entering a new golden era,'' Liu
Yuanren, bishop of Nanjing and president of the state-approved Chinese Catholic
Bishops College, told worshippers at the ordination.
</P>
<P>
	   Ordained in the ceremony were: Lu Xingping to bishop of Nanjing, Zhan Silu
to bishop of Mindong in eastern Fujian province, Fang Zhanping to bishop of
Tangshan in northern Hebei province, Jin Daoyuan to bishop of central Shaanxi
province and Su Changshen to bishop of Baoding, also in Hebei.
</P>
<P>
	   Su, a 76-year-old cleric, will run one of China's most active and
controversial parishes. In the mid-1990s, police destroyed a shrine to the
Madonna near Baoding and detained believers. An overseas Catholic monitoring
group reported arrests and, in one case, torture of underground worshippers in
Baoding last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
