<HEADLINE> Germans Feel Cheated by Gas Tax  </HEADLINE>
   By TONY CZUCZKA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- It's never been cheap to speed down the autobahn, but now a
sharp hike in gasoline prices has outraged even usually docile German motorists.
</P>
<P>
	   After back-to-back increases marred the holiday mood in the speed-loving
nation, some Germans are not only griping at the pump but going to court to try
to overturn a new energy tax.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a rip-off, pure and simple,'' taxpayer advocate Karlheinz Daeke
declared Wednesday, adding that his group would challenge the levy as
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
	   For Germany's center-left government, which includes for the first time the
environmentalist Greens, the ``ecology tax'' on energy is one of its proudest
achievements. Critics say the measure, designed to promote conservation, is
backfiring by raising the cost of public transportation -- in addition to
everything from taxi fares to the drive to the shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
	   While Germans like to lecture other Europeans on the environment, the furor
indicates where they draw the line.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Gasoline madness,'' screamed the capital's main tabloid, B.Z.
</P>
<P>
	   Hundreds of drivers lined up Wednesday at a central Berlin gas station to
experience how much cheaper filling the tank would be without the heavy taxes
raked in by the government.
</P>
<P>
	   For an hour, motorists paid about a quarter of the normal price, thanks to a
publicity stunt financed by the Free Democrats, a small anti-tax opposition
party.
</P>
<P>
	   For much of last year, Germans watched as fuel prices crept up along with
the cost of crude oil and the strength of the U.S. dollar. But the pent-up anger
exploded when oil companies announced yet another price hike just before New
Year, swiftly followed by phase two of the new tax on fossil fuels, which went
into effect on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The double punch sent premium unleaded gasoline soaring above the
psychological barrier of $4 per gallon -- up more than 20 percent from the start
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   That included an earlier hit from the energy tax, which was introduced in
April. And the government has already set further increases for each year
through 2003.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What I hear from almost all my customers is: Where does it end?'' said
Berlin gas station operator Jiri Rada. ``I can only shrug my shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
	   Daeke and others hope the end will come in Federal Constitutional Court,
Germany's highest tribunal.
</P>
<P>
	   The taxpayer group says it's preparing to challenge the ``ecology tax'' as
unconstitutional. It charges the government is hiding a simple grab for revenue
behind ecological arguments.
</P>
<P>
	   Trucking firms also plan to file a constitutional complaint. So do cold
storage companies fighting a rise in electricity prices included in the energy
tax. They assert they are being unfairly hit because the government, worried
about adding to unemployment, shielded some heavy industries from the increases.
</P>
<P>
	   Some legal experts say the challenges could succeed, forcing the government
to rework the tax. However, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's spokesman,
Uwe-Karsten Heye, said Wednesday the government would weather the storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
