<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Young Democracy Fumbles  </HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- In the waning days of 1999, a group of activists
in downtown Seoul trampled paper boxes symbolizing corrupt politics and chanted:
``Goodbye, 20th century. Begone, stale politics!''
</P>
<P>
	   The message resonates in South Korea, where the tainted political landscape
has seen it all in recent months: scandals and mudslinging, hasty resignations
and legislative gridlock.
</P>
<P>
	   Industrial South Korea may be an economic powerhouse, but its young
democracy is still fumbling for maturity one decade after its authoritarian era
faded. In the runup to parliamentary elections in April, fatigue has eclipsed
optimism among many voters.
</P>
<P>
	   Grubby politics are hardly a novelty worldwide, but the often rank tone
during the reformist presidency of Kim Dae-jung -- once the champion of a
persecuted democratic movement -- has been particularly hard to bear for many
South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Like many others, I once expected that things would be different under
this new government. But as far as corruption goes, things seem to be the
same,'' said Lee Young-hee, a 45-year-old insurance saleswoman.
</P>
<P>
	   The opposition Grand National Party gleefully seized on the most
embarrassing scandal, dubbed ``Furgate'' by local media. It involved allegations
that the wife of a jailed businessman tried to lobby Cabinet ministers on his
behalf by paying for expensive clothes for their wives.
</P>
<P>
	   Three of the wives, an ex-justice minister and a former presidential legal
adviser have been indicted on perjury and other charges.
</P>
<P>
	   In May, the environment minister, a former actress, quit for accepting an
envelope of cash from South Korean businessmen after she performed in a play in
Moscow that coincided with a state visit there by Kim.
</P>
<P>
	   The opposition, ousted from power by Kim in 1997 elections, says the
president is hardly living up to his campaign pledge of clean government.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet partisan quarreling in the 299-member National Assembly has sidelined
debate on bills and stalled efforts to reform the precinct voting system in time
for the April 13 elections.
</P>
<P>
	   Reluctant to compromise, the rival camps, particularly the opposition, have
filed dozens of lawsuits against each other.
</P>
<P>
	   The antagonism at times overshadows the notable achievements of Kim's
administration: labor reforms, better ties with Japan, recovery from economic
crisis and a policy of engagement with communist North Korea. Tension on the
divided Korean peninsula has eased considerably in recent months.
</P>
<P>
	   One expert calls it ``transitional trauma,'' the turbulent reversal of roles
for the once-dominant, now resentful Grand National Party and Kim's ruling
coalition, which spent years as a political underdog.
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Moon Jung-in, a political science professor at Yonsei University, said
Kim sometimes echoes the style of his authoritarian predecessors, pushing
through policies without seeking consensus.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The ruling party has not mastered the art of governing,'' Moon said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kim recently failed to merge his National Congress for New Politics with its
coalition partner, the United Liberal Democrats, as part of a strategy to
consolidate power ahead of the parliamentary poll. Scandals have sapped his
popularity.
</P>
<P>
	   If the opposition makes big gains in April, Kim's remaining three years in
office will be a grind. His coalition has 160 seats, but the Grand National
Party is the biggest party with 131 seats.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korea shifted toward democracy in 1987 when President Roh Tae Woo, a
former military commander, took office in a fair election.
</P>
<P>
	   Previous political transitions since independence from Japanese colonial
rule in 1945 had been tumultuous: a student uprising, an assassination and two
military coups.
</P>
<P>
	   Another obstacle to the full blooming of South Korean democracy is the
regional loyalty on which South Korea's three main political parties rely for
their support. Kim narrowly won election with the help of voters from his native
Cholla province, a rural southern area.
</P>
<P>
	   On Dec. 19, Kim urged South Koreans to cease emphasizing divisive regional
ties and apologized for government scandals. It will take more than that to
appease voters weary of their squabbling lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't know what they are fighting about. But I can tell you I am really
sick of all that,'' said Kim Sang-soo, a 30-year-old home appliance repairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0113 </TRAILER>
