<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Communist Poised To Lead Croatia  </HEADLINE>
   By SNJEZANA VUKIC Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- The leader poised to become Croatia's prime minister
admitted it right away: He inhaled.
</P>
<P>
	   Ivica Racan's admission to have smoked marijuana once didn't seem to hurt
him at all in the country's first parliamentary elections since the death of
Balkan strongman Franjo Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
	   Racan's coalition crushed Tudjman's party during the Monday balloting,
winning over voters with promises of economic revival and better ties with the
West.
</P>
<P>
	   With that landslide, the 56-year-old former communist leader turned Social
Democrat is ushering in a new era for a nation struggling to gain economic
strength and stability 9 years after declaring its independence from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
	   With his relative youth and low-key style, Racan symbolizes the country's
desire to make the transition to a modern European state.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The whole philosophy should be changed -- how to contribute to the state,
not take from it,'' he said in a pre-election interview to the independent
weekly Globus. ``The one who loves this country and believes in it, must be
ready for sacrifices.''
</P>
<P>
	   Backed by a solid majority of 71 seats, Racan is likely to easily become
prime minister, a job that may be even more important in the post-Tudjman era
than that of president. Though Tudjman assumed near monarchial authority after
leading the country to independence from Yugoslavia in 1991, it is likely many
of those powers will revert back to parliament.
</P>
<P>
	   The two men could not be more different. Racan speaks softly and rarely
lambastes his opponents. That is in sharp contrast to Tudjman, whose bluster
often served to keep people frightened and obedient.
</P>
<P>
	   Racan pledged that the new government would work around-the-clock for lower
salaries, bringing about hard economic reforms which Tudjman's party shunned.
Racan warned he would not tolerate any ``improprieties.''
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike other leaders tainted by corruption, Racan apparently did not use his
old post as Croatian communist party leader to enrich himself. He wears jeans
and spends summer vacations in a small cottage on the island of Brac. He is
married to an American of Croatian origin.
</P>
<P>
	   Even more critical, Racan appears more focused on the future rather than the
past. Unlike Tudjman, who often seemed obsessed by history, Racan rarely
mentions his own family's past: He was born in 1943 in a labor camp in
Ebersbach, Germany, that was run by the Nazis for those opposed to fascism. His
father died there.
</P>
<P>
	   His coalition's television campaign ad showed puppets, representing World
War II antifascists and fascists, fighting fiercely. The voice-over said: ``Have
you had enough of this? We have.''
</P>
<P>
	   He also made an effort to appeal to the country's young people, attending
rock concerts and defending the right of teen-agers to ``live your life the way
you want it.'' That remark was a slam against Tudjman's conservative taste for
folk music, and the former leader's aversion toward modern culture.
</P>
<P>
	   Cameras also caught Racan dancing enthusiastically at the Zagreb concert of
urban rock bands who supported his coalition. Racan shouted: ``Do you feel
good?'' Youngsters responded: ``Yeah!''
</P>
<P>
	   Then there was the marijuana admission, which prompted Tudjman's supporters
to suggest that he would bring ``sex, drugs and rock 'n' roll'' to Croatia.
</P>
<P>
	   Racan took it in stride, together with claims by opponents that he planned
to restore communism to the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
	   He ignored such suspicions. And he entered a coalition with Drazen Budisa, a
prominent dissident jailed by communist authorities in the 1970s. Budisa runs
for president later this month.
</P>
<P>
	   Though a politically odd couple, Racan said they will pull the country
closer to Western institutions like the European Union and NATO, offering ``a
democratic government that will sit at the European table where European affairs
are being discussed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0114 </TRAILER>
