<HEADLINE> Many cabbies observe Ramadan, prepare for Eid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Hanukkah is over, Christmas a memory and the New Year
well underway. But the city is not entirely through the holiday season. At
sunset every evening, cabs are oddly few and far between, parked instead near
mosques or Middle Eastern restaurants.
<P>
	   It is Ramadan in New York, where hundreds of cabbies are observant Muslims
and stop to break their fast every sunset and do not drive at all on Eid
al-Fitr, or feast of the fast-breaking, a major celebration at the end of the
Muslim holy month.
</P>
<P>
	   "When we break our fast at home or at mosques or at halal restaurants," the
Islamic equivalent of kosher, "it is beautiful, beautiful," said Sajid Ayub, a
cabbie from Queens, halfway through his fast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   During the Islamic lunar month of Ramadan, which started Dec. 9, Muslims
abstain from eating, drinking and smoking between sunrise and sunset as an act
of sacrifice and purification, stopping work to break their fast together each
evening.
</P>
<P>
	   "We do get some complaints during Ramadan, especially when we break our
fast," admitted Farooq Bhatti, president of the Pak Brothers Yellow Cab Drivers
Union. "But it's a special time for us. At that time, if you go to Lexington
Avenue between 26th and 30th streets, where there are halal Pakistani
restaurants, you will find many many cabbies."
</P>
<P>
	   At the Chatkhara restaurant, up to 50 cabbies break their fast with dates
and juice every Ramadan evening before praying at the restaurant or at a nearby
mosque and then eating a big meal of kebab and other delicacies, said cashier
Badar Raja. "Out front it's all taxis and limousines," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Other Muslim cabbies break the fast at home or at mosques.
</P>
<P>
	   "At this time, we have very beautiful everything," Ayub, 40, of Queens, said
enthusiastically. "There is hot food and wonderful juice, beautiful!"
</P>
<P>
	   On Eid, which is determined by the sighting of the new moon and is expected
to fall on Friday or Saturday this year, most Muslim drivers take the day off
for communal prayers and time with their families.
</P>
<P>
	   "Oh no way, we could never work on Eid," said Ayub, who has been driving in
the city for 12 years and estimated that 60 percent of cabbies are Muslim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-06-00 0114 </TRAILER>
