<DOCNO> APW20000106.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Race Starts for Tudjman Successor  </HEADLINE>
   By EUGENE BRCIC Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- Candidates scrambled to get into the race for
Croatia's presidency after the party that has ruled the country since
independence suffered a bruising defeat in parliamentary balloting.
</P>
<P>
	   Just days after an opposition coalition trounced the late President Franjo
Tudjman's Croatian Democratic Union in the first elections since his death,
eight candidates raced to meet a deadline at midnight Wednesday to register to
seek the post in the Jan. 24 ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   The coalition's candidate, Drazen Budisa, is likely to enjoy strong support
-- if the group's landslide win in parliamentary races Monday is any guide.
Tudjman's party, known by its Croatian acronym, HDZ, nominated the foreign
minister, Mate Granic.
</P>
<P>
	   Most opinion polls had indicated Granic, a moderate, was an outright
favorite to win the presidency -- though his chances are likely to suffer from
the election drubbing. The party's biggest loss was in the capital, Zagreb,
which had Granic leading the slate.
</P>
<P>
	   Granic was selected only hours before the filing deadline, hinting at
infighting within the HDZ. Tudjman did not groom a successor, and the quarrel
between hard-liners and moderates in the HDZ for control has only been
exacerbated further by the election debacle.
</P>
<P>
	   The coalition won -- by a 2-1 margin in some districts -- on promises to
push reforms to prepare Croatia for integration into Western European
institutions, such as the European Union and NATO.
</P>
<P>
	   Six other candidates are also seeking the post held by Tudjman since he led
Croatia to independence in 1991 until his death on Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
	   Stipe Mesic, a former Croat representative under the old Yugoslav presidency
and a former justice minister, Zvonimir Separovic, also entered the race, as did
sociologist Slaven Letica, and businessman Ante Ledo.
</P>
<P>
	   Rounding out the field were two hard-line conservatives, Ante Djapic and
Tomislav Mercep.
</P>
<P>
	   The victorious coalition is rallying behind Budisa, a former dissident who
served four years in jail for leading a student movement in the 1970s that
demanded greater autonomy for Croatia within Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The presidential elections are the second half of the same match,'' said
Zdravko Tomac, deputy president of the Social Democrats. ``We need to win and
hope to do so without a runoff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
