<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weld: I'd be hard to stop for New York governor in 2006  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   BOSTON (AP) - Former Massachusetts Gov. William Weld began his first day
as a Manhattan resident with a grand claim: If he decided to run for the top job
in New York in 2006, he could well become only the second American elected
governor of two states.
<P>
	   "I'd be hard to stop," Weld said in a telephone interview Wednesday with The
Associated Press from his New York law office.
</P>
<P>
	   Should Weld succeed, he would join Sam Houston as the only two-state
governor in history. Houston was governor of Tennessee from 1827 to 1829 and
Texas from 1859 to 1861.
</P>
<P>
	   Weld's claim to political viability in a new state may not be far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
	   "If anyone can do it, Bill Weld can do it," said Gov. Paul Cellucci, Weld's
running mate and lieutenant governor for six years. "He certainly was the person
who led our state back from some pretty tough times - he'll always be remembered
fondly."
</P>
<P>
	   Before he had even carried his suitcase into his Upper East Side apartment,
Weld was chatting about his roots in Long Island's Smithtown and his vacation
homes in the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
	   The moderate Republican's not-so-subtle message: He's no carpetbagger,
unlike Hillary Rodham Clinton, who also moved to New York state on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton - who became friends with Weld when they were both young
lawyers working on the Watergate hearings - is running for Senate from her new
home in Chappaqua, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
	   Weld, 54, cannot run for governor until he satisfies New York's five-year
residency requirement for the post. And he said he wouldn't challenge his two
New York pals - Gov. George Pataki or New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who hired
him as a federal prosecutor in 1981 - if either one were to run for governor in
2006.
</P>
<P>
	   New York may have a harsh political environment, but Massachusetts is even
harsher, said former New York Mayor Ed Koch.
</P>
<P>
	   "Massachusetts chews you up more than New York, and we do plenty of
chewing," said Koch, who recently encountered Weld in a barbershop.
</P>
<P>
	   "I wouldn't write him off as a kook," said Gerald Doherty, former
Massachusetts state Democratic chairman who worked on Robert F. Kennedy's 1964
Senate race in New York and ran Jimmy Carter's presidential campaign there.
"I've become a great respecter of him and his abilities to relate to people."
</P>
<P>
	   Brainy, funny and unpredictable - he once dived, fully clothed, into the
Charles River after signing an environmental bill - Weld strongly appealed to
suburban voters.
</P>
<P>
	   He also attracted Irish and Italian voters, despite his patrician lineage
that includes his namesake, William Floyd, who signed the Declaration of
Independence from New York.
</P>
<P>
	   "I may be a tightly wound Yankee, but that's not how I feel," Weld said
Wednesday. "I feel much more ethnic. I think I was separated at birth from an
Irish-Italian mother."
</P>
<P>
	   He narrowly won his long-shot campaign for governor in 1990 on a platform of
fighting crime, reforming welfare and cutting taxes. Over the next four years,
heavily Democratic Massachusetts came to like his brand of fiscal conservatism
and social liberalism and re-elected him by a landslide five years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   He has a notoriously short attention span, however, and soon got bored.
</P>
<P>
	   "Governor is the longest I've ever had a job," Weld said.
</P>
<P>
	   He challenged incumbent John Kerry for the Senate in 1996 and lost. The next
year he resigned, and President Clinton nominated him as ambassador to Mexico.
But Sen. Jesse Helms thought Weld too liberal, and blocked the nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   Since then, he has written two suspense novels, "Mackerel by Moonlight" and
"Big Ugly."
</P>
<P>
	   These days, he said, he is fully engaged as managing partner at McDermott,
Will &AMP; Emery's New York office, where he has been busy buying and selling
companies. "I'm enjoying that," he said. "I've got a reasonably steep learning
curve."
</P>
<P>
	   He will not sell his house in Cambridge, where his five children grew up.
His wife, Susan Roosevelt Weld, lectures at Harvard University and Boston
College.
</P>
<P>
	   If he does run in 2006, he will first have to win the hearts and minds of
New York Republicans and Conservative Party members.
</P>
<P>
	   "Bill Weld would face the high prospect of a Republican primary," New York
consultant Jay Severin said. "If he gets beyond that, 'President Weld' is a very
plausible phrase."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
