<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House GOP Marks Takeover Anniversary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans celebrated five years in power by
hailing their legislative victories and promising to continue to battle
President Clinton over such issues as the scale of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 60 GOP House members, many from the combative class of 1994,
gathered in Washington Wednesday to mark their fifth anniversary as the majority
party and discuss how to get their message out in the coming year. Congress
officially returns to work on Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have changed the nation's fiscal landscape,'' said Rep. J.C. Watts of
Oklahoma, chairman of the House Republican Conference. He was one of the 73
House GOP freshmen who championed the ``Contract with America'' when they
arrived in Washington in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
	   Watts and other Republicans listed overhaul of the welfare system, balancing
the budget, providing tax relief, boosting military spending and extending local
controls over education money as among their major accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House insists it deserves much of the credit for some of those
achievements, particularly attaining a budget surplus while winning more money
for schools and fighting crime.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democratic administration has also thwarted some of the more ambitious
GOP goals, such as last year's $792 billion tax cut vetoed by Clinton.
Republicans have gained ``a healthy dose of what can and can't be accomplished
in a legislative body,'' said Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., who is retiring after
three terms at the end of this session.
</P>
<P>
	   Former Speaker Newt Gingrich, who led the GOP takeover and was the chief
voice for change in the way government does business, received little mention at
Wednesday's news conference. Gingrich resigned after Republicans lost seats in
the 1998 election and in the past year was involved in a very public divorce
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
	   Watts said that while Gingrich helped lead the charge in the GOP revolution,
``we want to focus on the future.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Republicans face a tough future, trying to carry out their agenda with a
slim majority in the House of 222-212, with one independent who usually votes
with the Democrats. In addition, 21 House Republicans have announced they are
retiring at the end of this session, against only six Democrats, boosting
Democratic chances of recapturing the House.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican majority in the Senate, 55-45, appears secure.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our vital signs show that we are in very good shape,'' Watts insisted,
saying that Republicans will stay on the offensive in battling the White House
on such issues as tax cuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0137 </TRAILER>
