<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Groups Paid $697M To Lobby  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two major antagonists in the debate over how much to
regulate managed care health organizations spent the most on lobbying during the
first half of 1999, a private analysis found.
</P>
<P>
	   The American Medical Association, which favored new regulations, and the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which opposed them, each spent more than $8 million
from January to June. Both groups lobbied on other issues besides health care.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We've had some very important issues that we've been lobbying on,'' said
Dr. Thomas Reardon, president of the AMA, which spent $8.8 million. ``There was
a lot of emphasis on the Patients' Bill of Rights. We began to do work on health
care coverage for all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
	   The chamber spent $8.4 million.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The chamber is delivering what its members want most: advocacy on Capitol
Hill,'' spokesman Frank Coleman said. ``Our key issues are trade, legal reform,
preserving health care and fighting for reasonable regulation on business.''
</P>
<P>
	   Overall, health insurers, high-tech companies, banks and other interest
groups spent $697 million to lobby Congress and the federal agencies during the
first six months of 1999, according to a report released today by FEC Info, an
Internet consulting firm that specializes in tracking political money.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is an incredible amount,'' said Tony Raymond, a founder of FEC Info.
``These are the moneymakers. They have two groups they work on: the legislators,
the people who write the laws, but they also work on their home offices, saying
'Our competitors are spending this much on lobbying; we need to catch up with
them.'''
</P>
<P>
	   The amount is similar to the $710 million spent on lobbying during the first
six months of 1998, according to figures compiled by researchers at the Center
for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan research group that also analyzes federal
lobbying disclosure reports. FEC Info is a subsidiary of the Internet public
policy and health care technology company Netivation.com.
</P>
<P>
	   This time around, the health care industry spent more on lobbying than
anyone else, shelling out $95.5 million as Congress debated whether to impose
new regulations on managed care health plans. Congress didn't pass the new
rules.
</P>
<P>
	   In second place were communications and technology companies, which fought
over providing high-speed Internet access and sought approval for several
telecommunications mergers. Those companies spent $94.6 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The financial services industry, which won approval of a long-sought bill to
drop Depression-era barriers against banks, insurance companies and investment
houses competing against each other, spent $89.8 million on lobbying.
</P>
<P>
	   The top lobbying firm was Cassidy &AMP; Associates, which was paid $10 million
during the first half of 1999. Former Reps. Fred Rooney of Pennsylvania and
Marty Russo of Illinois both work for the firm, whose clients have included
Boeing, Exxon, and a number of colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
	   Patton Boggs, which counts former Rep. Greg Laughlin of Texas in its ranks,
was second at $9.2 million. The firm has represented the Association of Trial
Lawyers, MCI Worldcom and US Airways.
</P>
<P>
	   Verner, Liipfert, Bernhard, McPherson and Hand, home to former Senate
majority leaders George Mitchell and Bob Dole and former Texas Gov. Ann
Richards, was paid $7.3 million.
</P>
<P>
	   During the first six months of 1998, the powerhouse firm received $7.1
million from the tobacco companies alone, but the industry paid just $80,000
during the same period this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0138 </TRAILER>
