<HEADLINE> Honduran Indian Leader Slain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- Prosecutors have announced they are mounting a
criminal investigation into the Dec. 31 strangling death of a leader of the
country's Lenca Indian group.
</P>
<P>
	   The death of Jose Cosme Reyes, a local secretary of the National Lenca
Indigenous Organization, brings to 54 the number of indigenous leaders killed in
the last 9 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Gilberto Sanchez, the government's special prosecutor for ethnic groups,
said Wednesday that ``we still do not know the circumstances'' of Reyes' death
in the village of La Campa, 120 miles west of Tegucigalpa.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A large number of Indian leaders have been persecuted in Honduras because
of their efforts. Our aim is to find out if this case involves racism or
repression against Honduran Indians,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
	   In May, prosecutors asked courts to issue arrest warrants for 10 landowners
on charges of killing at least 42 of the Indian leaders in land disputes.
</P>
<P>
	   Indian groups have long accused landlords, woodcutters and some soldiers of
killing their leaders in conflicts over lands in central Honduras, where some
12,000 members of the Lenca tribe live.
</P>
<P>
	   About 10 percent of Honduras' 6.3 million people are Indians of seven
tribes. Most live in poverty and many have struggled against encroachments on
their lands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0151 </TRAILER>
