<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki: The future begins in changing New York education  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A new era in New York can only begin after the
state's education system is reformed, despite the state's impressive record of
tax cutting, welfare roll slashing and crime fighting, Gov. George Pataki says.
<P>
	   The New York Republican, still angling for a possible vice presidential
nomination, sought to burnish his conservative credentials Wednesday as he
delivered his sixth State of the State message to open the 223rd session of the
New York Legislature.
</P>
<P>
	   And Pataki used education as his starting point, calling for school children
to adhere to codes of conduct and teachers to undergo background checks and
crisis training.
</P>
<P>
	   "History must say that we were not just marking time, that we were not
content to merely carry the torch of time, but that we did all that could be
done to make it burn as bright as possible before handing it on to the next
generation," Pataki told lawmakers during his one-hour speech.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to a $700 million tax-cut proposal aimed mostly at businesses,
Pataki also called for legislation that would permit those convicted of three
misdemeanors to be tried as felons on subsequent misdemeanor arrests.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki's education plan - called "Schools 2000" - follows last year's
well-publicized rash of school shootings in Colorado, Oklahoma, Georgia and
other states. While his state was spared the violence epitomized by the massacre
at Columbine High, Pataki has stressed that school safety should go hand-in-hand
with the ongoing campaign to bring more accountability to New York's educational
system.
</P>
<P>
	   "Schools 2000 will create safe schools for our children and families, ensure
that all our children have a qualified teacher and insist that failing schools
are held accountable," said Pataki, who admitted he felt "sick as a dog" before
his early afternoon speech was delivered to a joint session of the state
Legislature in the cavernous Assembly chamber of the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
	   Braving freezing temperatures, thousands of state workers demonstrated
outside the Capitol against the governor. They have been without a contract
since April of last year. Concern about the demonstrations had led to unusually
tight security in and around the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
	   To help keep schools safe, Pataki wants all school districts to establish
codes of conduct that would cover everything from appropriate standards for
language and dress to rules for expulsion of students. He again called for
teachers to get the power to banish unruly students from their classrooms for up
to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor said all districts should also be required to teach students
about "civility, character and citizenship" and instruct them on "principles
including honesty, tolerance ... (and) observance of laws and rules, courtesy
and dignity."
</P>
<P>
	   Those proposals were largely taken from the 1999 recommendations of a task
force on school violence appointed by Pataki and chaired by Lt. Gov. Mary
Donohue.
</P>
<P>
	   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver applauded the governor for his concern but
noted that Pataki didn't mention anything about new gun control laws. "Guns in
our schools, guns on our streets ... He didn't touch on that at all," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki also called for creation of a statewide database that would track all
violent crimes in schools and mandatory violence prevention training for
teachers and school administrators.
</P>
<P>
	   To fight crime generally, Pataki called on the Legislature to adopt his
measure that would allow criminals convicted of multiple misdemeanors to be
tried as felons.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor renewed his calls for ending parole for all felons - it was
ended for violent felons last year - and for taking DNA samples from everyone
convicted of a crime. Currently, the state is only authorized to take DNA
samples from those convicted of certain violent felonies.
</P>
<P>
	   New York ran into education problems last year while trying to move to
higher educational standards, as seen in reports of teacher-approved cheating on
standardized tests in New York City and statewide test results showing more than
half of last year's fourth graders failing a standardized English test.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki's plan would battle the problem by getting more teachers into the
schools that would need them.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki called for the creation of 5,000 awards that would cover tuition
costs of up to $3,400 a year - equivalent to tuition at State University of New
York campuses - for prospective teachers agreeing to work in areas of the state
with chronic teacher shortages.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor also called for creation of "alternative credentialing" of
teachers that would allow people who have lived lives of accomplishments to
serve as classroom teachers, even though they don't have traditional teacher
training.
</P>
<P>
	   "Right now, Colin Powell can't teach in the New York schools that he grew up
in," Pataki said. "Billy Joel is not 'qualified' to teach piano to kids on Long
Island."
</P>
<P>
	   Education Commissioner Richard Mills and Regent Chancellor Carl Hayden both
applauded Pataki's speech.
</P>
<P>
	   "You have the governor of the state of New York giving a powerful recruiting
message for teachers," Mills said.
</P>
<P>
	   Not everyone approved, however. Alan Lubin, executive vice president of New
York State United Teachers union, called Pataki's plan unrealistic. He says
there's already a system that would allow non-teachers to get a waiver to teach
for a year.
</P>
<P>
	   "No matter how talented, Billy Joel or any other prospective teacher must
prove they can cut it in the classroom and show mastery of teaching methods," he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-06-00 0157 </TRAILER>
