<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duval Feeling Fit To Catch Tiger  </HEADLINE>
    By DOUG FERGUSON AP Golf Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KAPALUA, Hawaii (AP) -- David Duval had one of the best years no one
remembers. He returns to the Mercedes Championship as a defending champion, and
no one talks about it.
</P>
<P>
	   It was only 12 months ago that Duval overwhelmed the Plantation course at
Kapalua for a 9-stroke victory, the largest winning margin of the year. And that
was only the start.
</P>
<P>
	   He shot a 59 to the win the Bob Hope Classic, had a gutsy performance on a
brutally tough course to win The Players Championship, followed by his fourth
victory in eight starts in Atlanta -- a stretch of golf that elevated him to No.
1 in the world.
</P>
<P>
	   "That was a long time ago," Duval said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   It certainly feels like it.
</P>
<P>
	   The 30 players who won PGA Tour events last year gathered on the west coast
of Maui to start the year, but only one name seems to really matter right now --
Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
	   Woods became the first player in 25 years to win eight times on tour, and
his four-tournament winning streak to close out his sensational season was the
longest since 1953.
</P>
<P>
	   "Whether I raised the bar too high, I don't know," Woods said Wednesday. "I
just know I'm going to continue to try to improve."
</P>
<P>
	   That means everyone else will have to get better, too.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's on top of it right now," Duval said. "He's played super golf for a
long time. He's been on his game and he's playing like he thinks he can. I would
expect nothing less for a while to come."
</P>
<P>
	   Duval was in Woods' shoes two years ago. He won the final three events of
the 1997 season and came to the winners-only Mercedes Championship with a chance
to become the first player since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win four in a row. He tied
for sixth.
</P>
<P>
	   "It didn't feel to me like I was trying for a fourth in a row," Duval said.
"There was no continuity for it. It's the start of a new year."
</P>
<P>
	   Woods played three more events after the tour season ended -- winning two of
them -- then returned to golf last week in his Williams World Challenge in
Arizona. But it's back to business now, and Woods has a chance at more history.
</P>
<P>
	   Hogan was the last player to win five straight, in 1953, although the PGA
Tour didn't recognize his win in the British Open -- the oldest championship in
golf -- as an official event back then.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, matching Hogan is one thing. Another victory by Woods might send a
signal that the new year won't be much different than the old year.
</P>
<P>
	   Or it might not.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think Tiger needs to send any messages," Olin Browne said. "I think
he sent them already. He proved his point. He's out to play his best every
week."
</P>
<P>
	   His best last year was better than anyone could have imagined, especially
with the wealth of talent on tour these days.
</P>
<P>
	   No one since Johnny Miller in 1974 had won eight tour events in one year.
Beyond the victories were the close calls -- Woods only once finished lower than
seventh in his final 14 tournaments of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   "To win eight times with the strength of all the players today is beyond
words," Jesper Parnevik said. "I really can't see it being done again. But with
Tiger, you never know."
</P>
<P>
	   Thanks to Woods and Duval, who together won 12 tournaments last year, the
Mercedes field is limited to 30 players. Just as notable is who's not here --
Davis Love III, Phil Mickelson, Justin Leonard, Nick Price, Tom Lehman and Fred
Couples are among those who failed to win last year.
</P>
<P>
	   In their place are first-time winners Rich Beem, Ted Tryba, Notah Begay,
J.L. Lewis, Brent Geiberger, Mike Weir, Carlos Franco, Glen Day and Brian
Henninger.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is an unbelievable feeling to be here," Beem said. "I'm still coming
to grips with being a winner on the tour."
</P>
<P>
	   Duval, meanwhile, has sent his own message -- not by anything he has said,
but by the toned, chiseled look of a player determined to prove he can be the
best in the world. Over the past couple of months, Duval has stuck to a
disciplined regimen of exercise and diet. He looks as though he has shed 25
pounds, but the weight instead converted to muscle.
</P>
<P>
	   "What it does is it generally makes me feel better," he said. "It makes me
know that I am as fit and as athletic as anybody playing right now."
</P>
<P>
	   The question is how it will translate to scoring. Duval concedes that Woods
has set a new standard for everyone to reach, similar to what Duval did in the
first three months of a year ago. Only he's not ready to concede that Tiger will
be the only target.
</P>
<P>
	   "It might be Ernie Els," he said. "It just so happens that he (Woods) is
leading the pack right now. I guess I was the leader last year, and somebody
before that. It's just the progression."
</P>
<P>
	   Still, it all starts with Woods. The drive for five began today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0204 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Tech Coach Can Only Wonder  </HEADLINE>
    By HANK KURZ Jr. AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The day after Virginia Tech lost its first real chance
to win a national football title, coach Frank Beamer didn't feel as disappointed
as he did the night before.
</P>
<P>
	   "I feel a lot better right now in the fact that we came back," Beamer said
Wednesday of his team's 46-29 loss in Tuesday night's Sugar Bowl. "I think I'd
really be a miserable son of a gun if that score had ended up 55-7."
</P>
<P>
	   Beamer never expected special teams and big plays to be the Hokies' undoing
in the big game, but two punts resulted in touchdowns 5:34 apart for Florida
State, and the Seminoles scored on pass plays covering 64, 63 and 43 yards.
</P>
<P>
	   "When it's all said and done, I think we're going to kick ourselves for some
of the things that took place in that ballgame," Beamer said. "It just wasn't
us. But then maybe it wasn't us because it was them, at least a little bit."
</P>
<P>
	   Virginia Tech has been the best team in the '90s at using special teams to
change games, but it was the Seminoles who turned the tide Tuesday night,
scoring one touchdown on a blocked punt and another on a 59-yard punt return.
</P>
<P>
	   The Seminoles seemed on their way to a rout early on, taking a 28-7 lead
after about 19 minutes. But with freshman phenom quarterback Michael Vick
leading the way, the Hokies rallied to lead 29-28 heading into the final
quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   The comeback ended there and Florida State put the game away, but Beamer
felt the once-maligned Hokies had proved they belonged. Their finish at No. 2 in
The Associated Press poll seemed to offer respect.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's pretty amazing, isn't it?" he said. "That's neat. I think it is some
respect for our program."
</P>
<P>
	   Beamer also gushed about Vick, whose electrifying scrambles and athletic
ability often left the largest Sugar Bowl crowd in history gasping in disbelief.
Vick was sacked seven times, and he still escaped more often than not.
</P>
<P>
	   "Boy did he make some great, just unbelievable plays," Beamer said, shaking
his head like a burned defender. "I've never seen a quarterback like that.
People have him dead to rights and can't get him. Have ya'll ever seen anybody
like that?
</P>
<P>
	   "About three or four times I was going 'Duck, Michael!' I was afraid and
then all of a sudden there he goes. Just unbelievable, just an amazing talent."
</P>
<P>
	   Vick also made some mistakes, including a fumble after a 12-yard run in the
fourth quarter when the Hokies trailed 36-29 and were driving. Another fumble
ended the first series when Beamer went for it on fourth-and-goal from the 1.
</P>
<P>
	   "The bad plays hurt, too, and Michael knows that," Beamer said. "I think his
key in the future -- and he will -- is just to become a very consistent
quarterback."
</P>
<P>
	   Vick promised that his encore in 2000 will be something to behold.
</P>
<P>
	   "I plan to come back an even better player, even better quarterback,
mentally and physically," the 19-year-old Vick said. "Expect a lot from me next
year."
</P>
<P>
	   The Hokies will have to, especially with nine offensive starters coming
back. But the defense and special teams need to be rebuilt almost completely.
</P>
<P>
	   Defensive end Corey Moore was a non-factor in the Sugar Bowl, a first for
the consensus All-American, and he and the other top four defensive lineman will
move on. Gone, too, will be linebackers Jamel Smith and Michael Hawkes,
cornerback Anthony Midget and every member of the Hokies' punting and kicking
teams.
</P>
<P>
	   Ike Charlton, the Hokies' best defensive back, also said after the game he's
likely to forego his final year of eligibility and apply for the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
	   With the images of losing still fresh Wednesday, Beamer was still reliving
crucial plays and second-guessing risky calls that didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
	   "Would you guys have gone for that fourth down the first time?" he asked,
recalling Vick's opening-drive fumble that started the Hokies' trouble.
</P>
<P>
	   Several reporters said they would have gone for it, too.
</P>
<P>
	   "You're just saying that, aren't you, to make me feel better," Beamer
laughed. Then, easing back with a pained groan, he added: "Yeah, I'd do it again
too."
</P>
<P>
	   Beamer has insisted all along that the Hokies have risen to stay, but it
also wasn't lost on him that this may have been their best title opportunity.
</P>
<P>
	   Big underdogs, they led until 12:59 remained in the championship game.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm very disappointed that we didn't get it, because I think when we look
back, we're going to see how close, how we were right there," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0204 </TRAILER>
