<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State workers protest while Pataki delivers State of State  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Unions' leaders representing 130,000 state workers
said their protest Wednesday in frigid temperatures got their message of
frustration across, even though their boss, Gov. George Pataki, wasn't
listening.
<P>
	   Thousands of workers showed their anger over working without a contract and
the little progress between labor unions and the Pataki administration. But
while the protest failed to disrupt Pataki's upbeat State of the State address,
the event made a point, labor leaders said.
</P>
<P>
	   The protest left an impression with Albany city law enforcement, too; one
that officials don't want repeated.
</P>
<P>
	   Some demonstrators taunted and threw objects at state and city police, and
part of the crowd closed a downtown street after breaking through a temporary
fence on the Capitol lawn. But there were no arrests at the demonstration
sponsored by the Civil Service Employees Association and the Public Employees
Federation, said state Criminal Justice Services Director Katherine Lapp.
</P>
<P>
	   "On behalf of everyone, we are greatly disappointed in today's acts," she
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Albany Mayor Gerald Jennings said the activities of some demonstrators could
have warranted arrests, but that police decided to avoid making them.
</P>
<P>
	   Immediately after the event, several troopers at the scene said the crowd
was cooperative and they knew of no serious problems.
</P>
<P>
	   Crowd estimates varied widely.
</P>
<P>
	   State officials said 5,000 to 6,000 members of the two unions protested,
while the unions themselves said the figure was closer to 20,000.
</P>
<P>
	   While Pataki was delivering his State of the State speech in the state
Assembly chamber, union members chanted, blew whistles and beat drums outside
across the street from the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
	   Union members also toted signs for more than an hour in wind chills of
minus-2 degrees calling Pataki a hypocrite for providing double-digit raises to
lawmakers and his staff while offering little to the union members despite
budget surpluses. Some signs compared Pataki to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
	   Forty-five minutes into Pataki's hour-long speech, protesters outside broke
through a temporary fence and streamed closer to the back of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
	   A hundred troopers with wooden clubs held chest-high got between the
protesters and the building, flanked by Albany police in riot helmets with
visors down. They held the line with the help of union leaders as protesters
chanted "Show your face!" and "Georgie! Georgie!"
</P>
<P>
	   Protesters insisted they simply wanted their voices heard.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's all about respect," said Frank Horodysky, 60, from Poughkeepsie. "I
voted for the governor and I have a lot of respect for him, but he shouldn't
shun his people. I don't expect a 33 percent raise, but we should get at least 4
or 5 percent."
</P>
<P>
	   The Pataki administration's latest offer included 11-percent raises over
four years.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's not offering me anything," said Diane Lilly, 43, of Brooklyn. After
nine years as a keyboard specialist while also performing the duties of
timekeeper, purchasing agent and commissary worker at the Queens Borough
Correctional Facility, she said she and her three children live on her salary of
$23,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
	   "The state is dealing with us like a public assistance project," said George
Gergis, 57, who with 18 other PEF members left on a 5:30 a.m. bus from Long
Island. The pharmacist has worked at the Pilgrim Psychiatric Center for 23 years
and makes $43,000 a year. He said the private-sector equivalent would be
$65,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The 11 percent, four-year package offered to the unions is similar to deals
already approved by CSEA members at the state Thruway Authority and by United
University Professions, Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've tried to talk to the union in recent weeks, but they said they can't
go," McKeon said. "CSEA has made it clear to us they don't have time to
negotiate."
</P>
<P>
	   "This was the Y2K of union protests," McKeon added. "A whole lot of hype
that didn't hold up."
</P>
<P>
	   McKeon said union leaders are too busy getting re-elected to negotiate and
he called Wednesday's protest nothing more than a campaign rally for CSEA
President Danny Donohue.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pataki administration said it has made a "solid offer" to the unions
that represent 130,000 workers and treated the members as the best public
workers in the nation.
</P>
<P>
	   State police refused to say how many additional officers were assigned to
the Capitol Wednesday or the cost, but uniformed state police could be seen at
doorways in the Capitol and throughout the adjoining Empire State Plaza in
numbers rarely seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
