<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawrence Taylor Drug Charge Dropped  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TEANECK, N.J. (AP) -- A municipal court judge agreed to drop a minor drug
charge against former New York Giants linebacker Lawrence Taylor if he stays out
of trouble for six months.
</P>
<P>
	   Taylor, 40, of Saddle River, asked for and received the conditional
discharge in the case, stemming from discovery of drug paraphernalia in a room
rented under his name in a Teaneck hotel in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Taylor attended Wednesday's proceeding, but did not speak. He left hurriedly
afterward and refused to answer reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
	   Teaneck police, acting on a tip, searched the hotel room and found crack
cocaine and a pipe. Taylor was not in the room. The Bergen County Prosecutor's
Office declined to pursue the drug possession charge and in May 1999 downgraded
the paraphernalia case to a disorderly person's offense.
</P>
<P>
	   Municipal Court Judge James E. Young Jr. accepted Taylor's request for a
conditional discharge.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was treated the same as someone who's never before been convicted of a
drug offense," said Taylor's lawyer, Mark A. Berman.
</P>
<P>
	   Taylor has no prior drug convictions, despite highly publicized drug arrests
in Florida and South Carolina. He is an admitted drug abuser who has undergone
extensive rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
	   On Nov. 30, Taylor pleaded no contest to purchasing crack cocaine from an
undercover police officer in St. Pete Beach, Fla. In that case, the judge said
she will likely hand down an 18-month probationary term when Taylor faces
sentencing on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   In May 1996, Taylor was arrested in South Carolina on charges he tried to
buy crack cocaine. But he cleared his record by performing 60 hours of community
service and agreeing to undergo drug counseling and random drug testing.
</P>
<P>
	   Taylor pleaded guilty in June 1997 to a federal tax fraud charge and is
awaiting sentencing in that case.
</P>
<P>
	   Considered the dominant defensive player of his time, Taylor played 13
seasons with the Giants, leading them to two Super Bowl wins. He was inducted
into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0213 </TRAILER>
