<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colts' Berry Ready To Step In  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Third-year linebacker Bertrand Berry likely will start
for Indianapolis in place of the injured Cornelius Bennett in the Colts' first
playoff game Jan. 16.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a great opportunity for me. It's one that I've waited on my whole
career," said Berry, a third-round draft pick in 1997 out of Notre Dame. "To
start in a playoff game, that's what every guy who ever played football dreamed
about, from a little kid, up to an adult."
</P>
<P>
	   Until Sunday, Berry was mainly a special teams player for the AFC East
champions. He saw limited action on defense -- two solo tackles, three assisted
tackles and one sack -- until Bennett suffered a season-ending knee injury in
the 31-6 loss at Buffalo on the Bills' first play of the game.
</P>
<P>
	   The 6-foot-3, 250-pound Berry started 12 games at defensive end last year,
but moved to linebacker this season.
</P>
<P>
	   "He went into the game (Sunday) and did a pretty good job," coach Jim Mora
said. "Whoever it is, it is still going to be a loss, not having Cornelius."
</P>
<P>
	   The Colts (13-3) had Tuesday and Wednesday off, but planned to return to the
practice field today and Friday while waiting to learn whether they will meet
Seattle, Buffalo or Tennessee in the RCA Dome on Jan. 16.
</P>
<P>
	   Berry realizes the difficulty of stepping in to fill the hole left by
Bennett, who led the Colts with 114 tackles in his 13th NFL season.
</P>
<P>
	   "All I can say is I'm going to go out and make sure that the level of play
doesn't decrease because Cornelius isn't in there," Berry said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bennett, the Colts' oldest player at 34, also had been an inspirational
leader on the team. He was hoping to play in his sixth Super Bowl and earn the
winners' ring that eluded him in five previous appearances.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're going to miss his leadership, and his ability to make a lot of
plays," Berry said. "He's going to be in the Hall of Fame one of these days.
He's been playing great for us all season.
</P>
<P>
	   "At the same time, I'm a very capable linebacker and I can go in and make
plays. This is my opportunity to go in and show that."
</P>
<P>
	   Mora said he'll be watching Berry in practice this week and next before
deciding if he will start.
</P>
<P>
	   The Colts had their worst performance of the season Sunday as Buffalo
dominated offensively and defensively while ending the Colts' 11-game winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
	   "The score indicated how ugly it was. We watched the film and that pretty
much confirmed it," Berry said. "We just have to put this behind us and totally
get it out of our system. It's over with."
</P>
<P>
	   The Colts recorded the biggest single-season turnaround in league history
this season after finishing 3-13 in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0214 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
