<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Randy Moss's Game Is Maturing  </HEADLINE>
    By ARNIE STAPLETON AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- Randy Moss admittedly got bored with being a
superstar this season.
</P>
<P>
	   But he also became a better receiver in his second year with the Minnesota
Vikings, even though his touchdown catches dropped from 17 to 11.
</P>
<P>
	   Although he's still not a student of the game like teammate Cris Carter,
Moss added plenty to his repertoire.
</P>
<P>
	   "Now you have to cover me all over the field," said Moss, who caught 80
passes for an NFC-best 1,413 yards, a year after taking the league by storm.
</P>
<P>
	   Carter and Moss combined for 2,654 yards receiving this season, 41 yards shy
of the league record set by Mark Clayton and Mark Duper of the Miami Dolphins in
1984.
</P>
<P>
	   Carter had 90 catches for 1,241 yards and 13 touchdowns -- a typical year
for the perennial Pro Bowl receiver.
</P>
<P>
	   What makes Moss's stats more impressive is that his game no longer consists
of just going deep along the sideline like the best kid on the playground.
</P>
<P>
	   Moss lines up in the slot, runs crossing routes underneath, goes in motion.
He even throws touchdown passes off fake reverses.
</P>
<P>
	   "Randy is primarily a big-play receiver," said coach Dennis Green, who has
forgiven Moss transgressions such as dropped touchdown passes, simply because he
has the talent to make up for it on the next play.
</P>
<P>
	   Moss can still slip a cornerback like a cheap coat and scoot past the safety
for a quick-strike touchdown like last year, when he had a record-tying 10 TDs
for 40-plus yards.
</P>
<P>
	   "He can make a big play with a 5-yard catch and a 55-yard run or he can make
a big play with a 60-yard bomb," Green said.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, it seemed it was all bombs.
</P>
<P>
	   "Last year was basic," Moss said. "When I came to camp, they told me, 'Moss,
you learn and that's it.' This year, with me being able to read the coverages,
they give me a little more leisure to go out there and make plays in the slot,
across the middle."
</P>
<P>
	   That's part maturation and part necessity. Teams successfully double- and
triple-covered Moss early on, so he had to adapt.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's kind of hard to cover me that way if you're used to me going down the
sideline," Moss said. "Me catching slants, me catching hitches, stops, whatever.
Now, you've got to cover me all over the field ... and you don't know what I'm
going to do."
</P>
<P>
	   Moss still has work to do, however.
</P>
<P>
	   He was publicly chastised by team owner Red McCombs last month after
dropping several routine passes and walking away from a defender who had caught
an interception.
</P>
<P>
	   McCombs' criticisms were the first public gripes from the organization about
the moody Moss, who sulked on the sideline, nonchalantly cut off routes when the
plays weren't designed for him and dropped at least four potential touchdown
passes.
</P>
<P>
	   Moss responded by saying the boss had every right to say what he did and
admitted that he did get bored sometimes when he wasn't directly involved in the
action. He also replied by playing better.
</P>
<P>
	   A week later, Moss' five catches for 131 yards and two touchdowns lifted
Minnesota over Green Bay, 24-20. His five-catch, 155-yard performance Sunday
against Detroit included a 67-yard TD and helped the Vikings (10-6) earn a home
wild-card game against Dallas (8-8).
</P>
<P>
	   "I like big games, that's how I'm made," Moss said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0214 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Titans' Gambling Defense Is Working  </HEADLINE>
    By TERESA M. WALKER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Tennessee Titans have a simple philosophy on
defense: Attack the quarterback and get the football.
</P>
<P>
	   They did both as well as anybody in the NFL this season, coming up with 54
sacks and a league-high 24 fumbles. Only Jacksonville and St. Louis, with 57
each, got more sacks.
</P>
<P>
	   Linebacker Barron Wortham said the defense loves handing the ball back to
the offense.
</P>
<P>
	   "We know if we get them the ball again, they'll score again. That's
motivation," said Wortham, who has recovered three fumbles this season.
</P>
<P>
	   This from a defense that got only 19 turnovers in 1998. But the Titans
(13-3), who play host to Buffalo (11-5) on Saturday in an AFC wild-card game --
their first playoff game since 1993 -- had 16 interceptions. They are plus-18 in
turnover margin, which is the best of any team in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
	   It's the team's best turnover margin since 1979, when the former Oilers were
plus-18. They reached the AFC Championship game that season.
</P>
<P>
	   "Turnovers are key," Fisher said. "I think that's a major reason why we are
where we are right now because we've been able to get the ball back for the
offense."
</P>
<P>
	   The Titans ranked 17th overall on defense. Only Detroit (18), Minnesota
(27), Seattle (23) and Washington, which was better than only expansion
Cleveland, ranked worse among playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
	   "This defense will never be ranked high in statistics, but we'll be ranked
high in turnover ratio because this is a hit-or-miss defense," safety Blaine
Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We gamble. We take risks. We're either going to make a big play or we're
going to get a big play against us. That's how we live in this defense, and we
like it that way."
</P>
<P>
	   Fisher also pointed out that the Titans pressured the quarterback 125 times
during the season.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've made a lot of plays off pressures where we haven't gotten to the
quarterback," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense wasn't supposed to be a strength of the Titans this season. They
simply wanted to get better after getting only 30 sacks last season.
</P>
<P>
	   They hired Jim Washburn to coach the defensive line and signed veteran
tackles Mike Jones and Jason Fisk. The trio has provided much needed guidance
and motivation to a young line.
</P>
<P>
	   But the biggest improvement came from drafting Jevon Kearse.
</P>
<P>
	   He became the first rookie to lead a conference in sacks with 14 1/2, one
more than the entire Tennessee defensive line had in 1998. He also forced a
team-high 10 fumbles and was the first rookie end voted to the AFC Pro Bowl
team.
</P>
<P>
	   Bills veteran Bruce Smith has been impressed with Kearse.
</P>
<P>
	   "He has my vote for being defensive player of the year," Smith said
Wednesday. "I usually don't give my vote away very easily or quickly, but he
deserves it. He had one hell of a year."
</P>
<P>
	   The defense wants to make sure the season doesn't end with one game in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're going to try to build on that momentum and keep it going," Wortham
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0214 </TRAILER>
