<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deadline looms in land claim, parties want intensive talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   VERONA, N.Y. (AP) - Oneida County leaders are hoping that a series of
"around-the-clock" meetings with the Oneida Indian Nation could spark a
breakthrough between the groups and thus avoid sending the two sides back to
court.
<P>
	   Court-appointed mediator Ron Riccio has scheduled the meetings for Jan.
24-26 and has said he would decide after that whether it is possible to reach an
out-of-court settlement in the 30-year-old land claim.
</P>
<P>
	   All parties involved in the talks need to commit to a "very intensive"
negotiation schedule, Oneida County Executive Ralph Eannace and Rocco
DiVeronica, chairman of the Madison County Board of Supervisors, said in a
written statement issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   County leaders said they would like to see talks resume sooner.
</P>
<P>
	   "The lack of a more aggressive schedule on the part of all parties would
mean taking this claim to court, which could take years, and lead to a great
deal more expense to all," DiVeronica said.
</P>
<P>
	   "But more importantly, it would mean increased tensions and instability to
Central New York, where relations and civility among formerly friendly neighbors
have already deteriorated dramatically," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month, Oneida Nation Representative Ray Halbritter accused the counties
of jeopardizing negotiations by taking steps to foreclose on tax-delinquent
Oneida-owned land. The state and counties then accused Halbritter of ruining
negotiations by seeking the federal government's approval to serve liquor at the
Turning Stone casino.
</P>
<P>
	   The Oneidas have always been willing to negotiate aggressively, said Mark
Emery, a spokesman for the Oneida Indian Nation of New York, which is joined in
the claim by Oneida tribes from Wisconsin and Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   The Oneidas, with the support of the U.S. Justice Department, are seeking
the return of 250,000 acres of ancestral land in Oneida and Madison counties.
The U.S. Supreme Court found in 1985 that the land was seized in questionable
transactions with the state and private individuals and ruled the Oneidas were
entitled to compensation.
</P>
<P>
	   After 13 years of failed negotiations, Riccio entered the case in February
as a court-appointed settlement master. Talks have been held regularly.
</P>
<P>
	   The two sides have been unable to agree on three main issues: land
ownership, money and sovereign Indian jurisdiction. They have come together on
some minor issues such as hunting and fishing rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Arlinda Locklear, a lawyer for the Oneida Indian Nation of Wisconsin, was
not optimistic that a settlement could be reached.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're at a stage where we know what the possibilities are. I think it is
more of a question of whether each side is willing to make the compromises
needed for a settlement," Locklear said.
</P>
<P>
	   If Riccio declares an impasse, the case would return to U.S. District Judge
Neal McCurn. McCurn's first task would be to rule on the Oneida's outstanding
request to expand the case to sue the state and 20,000 landowners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-06-00 0215 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ewing, Hastert Clash Over Primary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Retiring Rep. Tom Ewing says Speaker Dennis Hastert has
betrayed their nearly two-decade-old friendship and alienated other members of
Congress by endorsing another Republican over Ewing's son in the race to succeed
him.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It sends kind of cold chills down the backs of other members,'' Ewing,
R-Ill., said Wednesday. ``If he'll do it to a friend, what will he do to someone
else? I think he has confused his responsibility to his party with his desire to
keep himself in office.''
</P>
<P>
	   Hastert announced his support for Republican state Rep. Bill Brady at an
appearance Tuesday in Ewing's mostly rural eastern Illinois district. Three
other Republicans also are running, including Sam Ewing, whom his father's
supports as his replacement.
</P>
<P>
	   Ewing said his longtime confidant and fellow Illinois Republican broke an
earlier promise to stay out of the race. He also said Hastert was unwise to
exert his influence in a safely GOP district unlikely to fall out of Republican
hands. President Clinton barely won the district in 1996, but Ewing always won
re-election by wide margins.
</P>
<P>
	   ``To me, it's going to hurt the speaker,'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hastert spokesman John Feehery said the speaker was convinced Ewing's
retirement left the seat vulnerable to a Democratic takeover and felt it
necessary to act to protect House Republicans' narrow majority. Two Democrats
are competing for their party's nomination in the March primary.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's certainly not a given'' that Republicans will keep the seat, Feehery
said. ``With our slim majority, there really is no margin for error.''
</P>
<P>
	   Party leaders generally avoid openly taking positions in primary races, but
often support a candidate behind the scenes to ensure the strongest goes on to
the general election. For instance, even before Hastert's public endorsement, he
and his staff provided fund-raising help to Brady.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0215 </TRAILER>
