<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB Probes Fatal Greyhound Case  </HEADLINE>
   By CLAUDE R. MARX Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lax safety procedures, a sleepy driver who was impaired
by an antihistamine and a policy that allowed trucks to park on the side of the
Pennsylvania Turnpike caused a June 1998 crash that killed seven people and
injured 18, federal investigators say.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Transportation Safety Board said Wednesday that Milton Wisner's
alertness was adversely impacted by an antihistamine and Greyhound Lines Inc.'s
scheduling of irregular work periods for its drivers. The board also said the
Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission's practice of allowing non-emergency parking in
pull-off areas contributed to the accident's severity.
</P>
<P>
	   Greyhound Executive Vice President Jack W. Haugsland disputed the findings
and said fatigue was ``not a major factor'' in causing the accident. He said
studies by the company's pathologists indicated Wisner had suffered a heart
attack, a claim the board specifically rejected.
</P>
<P>
	   Haugsland also said the company's scheduling was sound and that it had a
good safety record.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission would not comment on the board's
findings, said spokeswoman Kathy Liebler.
</P>
<P>
	   Wisner, 61, of Boothwyn, Pa., suffered from chronic fatigue syndrome and had
complained to his physician about it. He was taking an antihistamine to combat a
chronic sinus problem. In addition, NTSB records indicated that Wisner had been
involved in seven accidents since 1990 and had been cited for speeding twice.
One of those incidents resulted in a five-day suspension.
</P>
<P>
	   Wisner was on his last run before retiring on June 20, 1998, and driving in
a mountainous area, when his bus ran into a tractor-trailer legally parked in a
roadside area. The crash -- which occurred at 4:30 a.m. about 60 miles west of
Harrisburg -- pushed the truck into the back of another truck parked in front of
it.
</P>
<P>
	   Wisner, his wife and an 8-year-old boy in their care were killed along with
four other passengers. The truck's two co-drivers, who had been asleep in the
cab, also were injured.
</P>
<P>
	   The board criticized Greyhound's ``lax'' procedures in documenting safety
violations and monitoring the ``widespread speeding'' of its drivers. The board
said the company does not adequately respond to consumer concerns about safety,
noting it had taken no action when a woman complained about Wisner's driving
habits.
</P>
<P>
	   The NTSB recommended that Greyhound revise its scheduling process, improve
its record keeping, and insure that complaints made on its 800 phone line are
acted on and placed in drivers' files.
</P>
<P>
	   The board also suggested that the Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission prohibit
non-emergency parking in pull-off areas adjacent to the highway, provide
adequate rest areas for non-emergency parking and conduct more drills to improve
handling of large-scale disasters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0215 </TRAILER>
