<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Syria Get Down to Business  </HEADLINE>
   By DONNA ABU-NASR Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- President Clinton is ready to plunge back into
difficult peacemaking between Israel and Syria as the two longtime foes engage
in intensive negotiations on a number of thorny issues.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, who was here for the first two days of the talks this week, stayed
away Wednesday. A senior U.S. official said in Washington that the president
probably would return, but would not make a decision until today.
</P>
<P>
	   State Department spokesman James Rubin said Wednesday: ``I think he will be
coming back Thursday.'' He added: ``We see President Clinton's presence as
always useful but we don't want to overdo it.''
</P>
<P>
	   The task now, Rubin noted, is ``how we get from chugging along to a fast
track. ... Our expectations are still neither great nor bleak.''
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, the two delegations began discussions for the first time in
almost four years on issues of substance.
</P>
<P>
	   A committee dealing with mutual security concerns met all day, focusing on
the establishment of a demilitarized zone and an early warning system, Rubin
said. Another team of negotiators took up in some detail the issue of
normalizing relations, he added.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin gave no indication, however, that agreements were reached on any of
the tough issues that stand in the way of this fledgling pursuit of peace.
</P>
<P>
	   Gen. Shlomo Yamai of Israel and Gen. Ibrahim Omar of Syria headed their
governments' delegations in the security talks, while Zvi Shtauber and Walid
Muallem were the Israeli and Syrian delegation leaders, respectively, in the
negotiations on peaceful relations.
</P>
<P>
	   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, along with her military aide, Army
Lt. Gen. Donald Kerrick, joined the security committee sessions, and Assistant
Secretary of State Martin Indyk engaged in the peace terms discussion.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright met over lunch with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and later
held talks with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa. She also held talks
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
	   The delegates worked in the seclusion of a U.S. government retreat just
outside this 239-year-old town, the oldest in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   If the negotiations succeed -- and no one is making any such claim at this
preliminary stage -- Israel would surrender the Golan Heights security buffer
zone along the border, and Syria would establish diplomatic relations with its
longtime adversary.
</P>
<P>
	   Barak has signaled his willingness to make territorial concessions, but is
holding back until Syrian President Hafez Assad authorizes his delegation to
outline what kind of diplomatic, economic and political relationship he would
extend in return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0217 </TRAILER>
