<HEADLINE> Rich Defendants Guilty in Manila  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM GOMEZ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- A court sentenced a group of young men from rich
families to life imprisonment Thursday for the murders of a family of three in a
widely publicized case that helped prompt lawmakers to re-impose the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   Hundreds of police stood guard at the courtroom as the 5-hour-long decision
was broadcast live over six television networks to millions of crime-weary
Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
	   The eight suspects, two of whom are still at large, were found guilty of
stabbing to death Estrellita Vizconde and her two daughters, Carmela, 18 and
Jennifer, 7, in their house in Paranaque city, a Manila suburb, on June 29,
1991. Carmela was raped repeatedly before being stabbed 17 times, court records
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The defendants include Hubert Webb, the son of a former senator and brother
of a TV newscaster. Webb claimed he was in the United States at the time of the
killings.
</P>
<P>
	   At one point during the reading of the decision, Estrellita's husband,
Lauro, cried as the wounds of the victims were described. He was living in the
United States at the time of the murders and has since become an anti-crime
crusader.
</P>
<P>
	   The case has been one of the most closely followed in the Philippines.
Newspapers and TV stations regularly reported developments during the years of
the trial, and many Filipinos believed the defendants' wealthy families
attempted to subvert justice.
</P>
<P>
	   A policeman who allegedly was close to the Webb family was implicated as an
accomplice in the case for ordering the burning of bloodied bedsheets and other
evidence shortly after the killings.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors relied mainly on the testimony of a woman, Jessica Alfaro, who
said she was with the eight men when they committed the killings while high on
drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense lawyers, however, said Alfaro's testimony was not credible because
she was a former drug user.
</P>
<P>
	   They accused Judge Amelita Tolentino of bias and said they would appeal to
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   The killing of the Vizcondes was one of several sensational crimes cited by
Filipino legislators when they decided to restore capital punishment in the
country in 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   The new law does not apply retroactively to the Vizconde case, and the
defendants were subject to a maximum sentence of life imprisonment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0219 </TRAILER>
