<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Hurricane' Learned from New Movie  </HEADLINE>
    By ED SCHUYLER JR. AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   The Hurricane found out something he didn't know when he saw the movie about
his life.
</P>
<P>
	   "Until I saw Denzel Washington portraying me, I didn't know how good I am,"
said Rubin "Hurricane" Carter.
</P>
<P>
	   Carter showed up at the Official All-Star Cafe in New York's Times Square on
Wednesday to plug the just-released film, "The Hurricane."
</P>
<P>
	   At 62, Carter said he weighs 156 pounds, which was about his fighting weight
as a middleweight contender in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Hurricane," however is not so much about Carter, the boxer, as about
inmate No. 45472, who served 19 years in prison in New Jersey after being
wrongfully convicted in 1967 of three murders.
</P>
<P>
	   Carter's New York appearance on Wednesday was really an event staged for
television. When a couple of print media guys talked to Carter after the cameras
were shut off, some Hollywood-type flacks stopped the "interview" quicker than a
faint-hearted referee prematurely halts a fight.
</P>
<P>
	   Carter posed for television and still cameras with 26-year-old John Molnar,
introduced as a welterweight prospect, and said when asked if he was still
interested in boxing, "Oh yea. I'm on my way to Philadelphia to see some
fighters."
</P>
<P>
	   However, in the interview, which lasted about three minutes (one full
round), he said "I'm not interested in boxing, I'm interested in saving lives."
</P>
<P>
	   Carter is associated with the Defense of the Wrongfully Convicted that helps
people correct legal wrongs.
</P>
<P>
	   While Carter said he has no interest in attending fights or watching them on
television, he also said, "Boxing is the sweetest sport in the whole world --
two human beings going fist-to-fist."
</P>
<P>
	   As for "The Hurricane." Carter said, "I think the movie depicts the 63 years
of my life (he'll turn 63 on May 6) accurately."
</P>
<P>
	   The film follows Carter's 1974 book, "The Sixteenth Round," written while he
was in prison. It shows a man who grew up tough, spent time in a reformatory and
gained a following as a glaring, power-punching middleweight who made an
unsuccessful title bid against Joey Giardello on Dec. 14, 1964.
</P>
<P>
	   In the movie, a television broadcaster says while waiting for the decision
to be announced that everyone knows that Carter has won. In the "The Sixteenth
Round," Carter wrote he lost a split decision. Actually, the decision was
unanimous for Giardello.
</P>
<P>
	   Oh well, fighters often see fight different than the judges, and where would
movie makers be without a little poetic justice?
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, Carter recalled a flawed strategy of boxing with the idea of
going the full 15 rounds against Giardello, a master boxer.
</P>
<P>
	   "Any other time, I was in there to get you out of there," Carter said.
</P>
<P>
	   One of those wins, which Carter considers the highlight of his career, came
in on Dec. 20, 1963, against welterweight champion Emile Griffith, who had just
been named Fighter of the Year. Carter angered Griffith at a prefight news
conference, and Griffith was determined to slug it out. Carter knocked him down
twice and stopped him in the first round.
</P>
<P>
	   Carter's boxing record was only a fair 27-12-1, with 19 knockouts, not the
kind of career that would warrant a movie. But, as has been said, "The
Hurricane" is a film about a man whose fierce pride -- he refused to wear prison
clothes -- helped enable him to win his freedom and who now is fighting for
others who claim to be unjustly imprisoned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0221 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0094 </DOCNO>
