<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coonelly in 4th graf CQ, Also moving on national and sports  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Calling each other nicknames like "Cowboy," "Shorty,"
and "Moose," Major League Baseball umpires thought they had solidarity when they
agreed to resign their jobs to protest their wages, an umpire says.
<P>
	   But Larry Poncino, a National League umpire, told a National Labor Relations
Board hearing officer Wednesday that he discovered instead that he was out of a
job and a renegade group of umpires had formed a new union.
</P>
<P>
	   Confronted with his own resignation letter, Poncino said he signed it
because he thought all umpires were signing similar letters. Instead, a majority
of American League umps either didn't resign or quickly withdrew their
resignations.
</P>
<P>
	   The collapsed effort ruined the strategy of the Major League Umpires
Association, led by Richie Phillips.
</P>
<P>
	   "We were an Erector Set going in and we came out a bunch of Tinker Toys,"
Poncino said.
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips' union is trying to convince the hearing officer to overturn the
election it lost 57-35 to the insurgents in November.
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips claimed Wednesday that baseball commissioner Bud Selig and other
top leaders of the sport encouraged a group of insurgent umpires to form a new
union.
</P>
<P>
	   Citing telephone records of calls between Selig's office and insurgent
leader John Hirschbeck, Phillips said the owners illegally conspired with the
anti-Phillips faction.
</P>
<P>
	   The hearing officer, David L. Leach III, refused to let Phillips question
baseball lawyer Frank Coonelly or an organizer of the insurgent Major League
Umpires Independent Organizing Committee about conversations between the two.
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips said the questioning was crucial to support testimony earlier in
the day by Drew Coble, among the 22 umps who lost their jobs in September. Coble
said he was told Selig had promised he could have his job back if he dropped his
support for Phillips.
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips, who has led the umpires since 1978, said the insurgents "were used
by Bud Selig and baseball as a vehicle to break the union and to send a message
to others in baseball."
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips cited telephone records showing six telephone calls on July 22
between Selig's Milwaukee office and Hirschbeck's home, "all at the critical
time these people (umpires) allegedly were being replaced."
</P>
<P>
	   Phillips said there was a meeting that day in Selig's office of the nine top
executives in baseball, including both league presidents. He claimed they talked
about how to break the union.
</P>
<P>
	   "What happened to the 22 was done to bust the Umpires Association," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Poncino testified that he was told by Hirschbeck's brother, Mark, that the
insurgents could have a labor contract within 72 hours if Phillips was ousted or
his union dismantled.
</P>
<P>
	   Poncino said Mark Hirschbeck, an NL ump, said in late September that with
Phillips out of the picture, the umpires could get improved severance benefits
and larger work crews, among other contract improvements.
</P>
<P>
	   Poncino said he asked Mark Hirschbeck how he learned about the possible
contract improvements and Hirschbeck wouldn't say.
</P>
<P>
	   Poncino later asked him if he would repeat the allegations at an arbitration
hearing in Philadelphia. The MLUA filed a grievance attempting to regain the
jobs of the 22.
</P>
<P>
	   "He told me he would have to deny that the conversation ever existed,"
Poncino said.
</P>
<P>
	   The MLUA rested its case, and the insurgents planned to call one or two
witnesses Thursday. Owners said they weren't sure whether they would call any
witnesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-06-00 0223 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A New Hampshire Electoral Sampler  </HEADLINE>
   By TED ANTHONY AP National Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- When Bill Bradley got snippy, they snickered. When Al
Gore invoked Harry Truman, they grinned the grins of those who'd heard the quote
the first time around. And when it came to the issues, they were ready with the
perspective and wisdom that only age can bring.
</P>
<P>
	   They huddled around Lois Brown's TV set and listened -- nine American
voters, seven centuries of life experience among them, processing the ideas and
proposals and mannerisms of two men who would be president.
</P>
<P>
	   For the group of retirees who watched Bradley and Gore go at it Wednesday
night, two things seemed evident: Neither candidate, they concurred, trounced
the other. And, despite both men's faults and striking similarities, both
probably would do a capable job of leading the country.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I found it very difficult to differentiate,'' said Lloyd Heidgerd, 81, a
Democrat and retired science librarian. ``Either could be president, and I
wouldn't be upset.''
</P>
<P>
	   Deep conviction resonated among this group of mostly Democrats, some of them
married couples. Mrs. Brown, 81, declared Gore ``has earned the presidency.''
Robert Back, who turned 77 today, proclaimed Bradley ``comfortable -- like an
old dog.'' And Norm Wilson, a GOP-leaning independent, questioned the vice
president's commitment to candor.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Gore is willing to accept a lot of credit for things he had nothing to do
with,'' groused Wilson, 80, a retired engineer.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Aw, c'mon -- he invented the Internet,'' Back quipped, referring to Gore's
onetime claim.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley is challenging Gore for the Democratic presidential nomination, and
is even or ahead in polling leading up to the New Hampshire primary, the
nation's first. It is set for Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   In the minutes after the debate ended, Mrs. Brown's living room was an
exhilarating place to be. Spirited back-and-forths unfolded. Enthusiastic
splinter conversations erupted. These clearly were folks who, regardless of
their politics or history, pride themselves on being involved in the process.
They scorn those who aren't.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Brown, a widow and retired municipal official who has voted Democratic
all but once in her life and grew to adulthood during the Depression, suggested
the problem with an indifferent electorate might be protracted prosperity.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The trouble is, times have been too good,'' she said. ``People have to
wake up.''
</P>
<P>
	   But how were the candidates? The answers came fast.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Gore was more relaxed than usual,'' said Muriel Back, 77, a retired
librarian.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Gore's answers were more canned,'' countered John Ray, 80, a retired
engineer. ``He comes across as more presidential, but I don't necessarily think
he'd make a better president.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Bradley's more free of the establishment, so he has more chance to be a
real leader,'' said Nan Bliss, 79, a retired arts-and-crafts shop manager.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He seems to be more flexible in his thoughts and expressions,'' said June
Wilson, 76, a retired teacher.
</P>
<P>
	   Health care concerns many of these folks. They live in Heritage Heights, a
retirement community just east of downtown Concord, where Gore plans a visit
Jan. 14. And though they all are independent and mobile, they know many who
aren't. They're aware of the stakes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They're not really saying how their health plans would be financed. They
don't go into enough detail,'' complained Tay Ray, 79, a retired school
librarian.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Either one of them could help a lot of people in this country by modifying
the tax rules on Social Security and prescriptions,'' Wilson said. ``We're
taking a belt in the teeth.''
</P>
<P>
	   Then there is that final intangible: image. The character issue is the bane
and triumph of modern presidential politics. And despite the massive changes
that television has wrought, the image thing predates even the tube.
</P>
<P>
	   Take it from those who were there and are still around, still trying to
figure out the world and make the right choices to elevate the right leaders.
It's complicated, they agreed, even after doing it for so long.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's still a cult of personality. It's not new,'' said Back, born when
Warren Harding was president. ``The presidents we think of are personality boys.
Roosevelt was. Johnson was. I think we're still looking for them.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``FDR,'' mused Norm Wilson, a Woodrow Wilson baby.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Now there was a man,'' said Back.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Now there,'' added Wilson, ``was a leader.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0242 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong shares fall hard  </HEADLINE>
    By DIRK BEVERIDGE AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- Adding to the red ink from Asia's massive stock slide,
Hong Kong blue chips tumbled 5.6 percent by late Thursday afternoon and Tokyo
prices finished down as traders shrugged off Wall Street's calmer performance
and dumped high-tech shares.
</P>
<P>
	   Most Asian stocks were lower in the wake of Wednesday's selloff that hit
some markets so hard it brought back memories of the way prices had plunged more
than two years ago as the financial crisis spread through the region.
</P>
<P>
	   In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index fell sharply from the outset, extending
Wednesday's ominous 7.2 percent dive that was its worst one-day drop since late
October 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   With less than an hour left to trade, the Hang Seng was down 887.04 points,
or 5.6 percent, to 14,959.68. Jittery investors gathered around stock quotation
machines in local banks to survey the damage to a market that had rung in the
new year on Monday with a record finish.
</P>
<P>
	   Hong Kong traders bet wrongly early in the morning that prices would recover
in line with the rebound overnight Wednesday by the New York's Dow Jones
industrial average, which rose 1.1 percent after a 3.2 percent drop on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors pushed futures contracts higher before the Hong Kong Stock
Exchange opened -- only to see share prices fall fast from the start.
</P>
<P>
	   On Asia's top market, the Tokyo Stock Exchange, blue chips shed 2 percent as
investors bailed out of high-tech companies that have taken a beating globally.
</P>
<P>
	   A 5.6 percent drop in the U.S. Nasdaq Composite Index on Tuesday sparked the
selloffs, and although the Nasdaq held its losses Wednesday to just 0.6 percent,
traders figured many high-tech companies were still too expensive.
</P>
<P>
	   Tokyo's Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed 374.28 points
lower to 18,168.27.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of the big decliners in Tokyo included high-tech concerns Sony and
Softbank.
</P>
<P>
	   "Unless Nasdaq and Internet shares stabilize, we'll see some more
corrections in Japan," said David Shirt, a stock salesman at investment house
Jardine Fleming in Tokyo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0244 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Plan Debated in N.H.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore bent Bill Bradley's health care plan out of shape.
Bradley muddled the history of welfare reform. And a near-classic piece of
misrepresentation from another time came back to tweak Republicans again.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democratic presidential rivals did not go as far off course in their
latest debate as they did in earlier matchups.
</P>
<P>
	   But here and there, truth was a casualty and complex ideas were boiled down
into barely recognizable form.
</P>
<P>
	   As usual, the main point of contention Wednesday night was Bradley's
signature health care plan and especially his proposal to end Medicaid and use
subsidies to make health insurance accessible to nearly everyone.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore left viewers of the New Hampshire debate with the impression that the
subsidy would be capped at a measly $150 a month, while Bradley says the figures
in play are weighted averages, not caps.
</P>
<P>
	   But beyond that, $150 a month is Bradley's figure for individuals -- the
average subsidy for a family of four would be more than $400 a month.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All of the people who would be affected in New Hampshire would be left
out,'' Gore stated. Kathleen Hall Jamieson, a specialist in the veracity of
campaign rhetoric and ads, said the claim was wrong.
</P>
<P>
	   While it is reasonable at least to argue that people now on Medicaid may not
make out as well under Bradley's proposals, his plan would reach poor people who
currently are not covered by Medicaid, she said. ``Those people will get a net
advantage in any event.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore tried to put Bradley on the defensive for opposing the 1996 welfare
changes that are generally considered a success. In the course of fighting back,
Bradley did not get legislative history quite right.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley suggested the welfare restrictions he voted against were harsher
than those that exist now. But while some immigrant benefits have been restored,
the major provisions of the welfare legislation, such as time limits, work
requirements and an end to the federal guarantee of benefits, remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
	   As well, he said ``this bill came in October of 1996. October of 1996 -- who
knew if Bill Clinton was going to win? Maybe it would have been Bob Dole. If it
had been Bob Dole, there would have been a long time before there were any
changes made in that welfare reform bill.''
</P>
<P>
	   But the welfare overhaul became law in August 1996. Moreover, Clinton's
defeat of the Republican Dole in the 1996 election was widely expected by
October, if not earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was a strange explanation,'' said Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg
School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania. ``There was not a
point in which Clinton was not leading Dole in the polls.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore took credit in the debate for helping to pass what he called the most
significant gun-control legislation in a generation, with his tie-breaking vote
in the Senate on a bill to require instant background checks at gun shows. He
neglected to mention the bill did not become law.
</P>
<P>
	   The vice president also revived what Jamieson called ``that standard old
deception'' from the 1996 campaign when he said, ``You know, when Newt Gingrich
took over the Congress, he proposed slashing Medicare, making terrible changes
in a lot of the programs that help the American people.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``That was the most often repeated deceptive statement from Democratic
ads,'' Jamieson said. The Republican congressional majority, when Gingrich was
House speaker, did not propose a net cut but rather a slowing in the rate of
growth, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats at one point also proposed cutting the rate of growth of Medicare,
but more modestly.
</P>
<P>
	   Jamieson also was baffled by Bradley's comment, when asked about taking
campaign money from the pharmaceutical industry as a senator, that he never did
anything against the interests of his constituents or his country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0245 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Shares Fall Hard  </HEADLINE>
    By DIRK BEVERIDGE AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong blue chips tumbled 5.6 percent by late this
afternoon and Tokyo prices finished down as traders shrugged off Wall Street's
calmer performance and dumped high-tech shares, adding to the red ink from
Asia's massive stock slide a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   Most Asian stocks were lower in the wake of Wednesday's selloff that hit
some markets so hard it brought back memories of the plunge more than two years
ago when the financial crisis spread through the region.
</P>
<P>
	   In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index fell sharply from the outset, extending
Wednesday's ominous 7.2 percent dive that was its worst one-day drop since late
October 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   With less than an hour left to trade, the Hang Seng was down 887.04 points,
or 5.6 percent, at 14,959.68. Jittery investors gathered around stock quotation
machines in local banks to survey the damage to a market that had rung in the
New Year on Monday with a record finish.
</P>
<P>
	   Hong Kong traders bet wrongly early in the morning that prices would recover
in line with the rebound overnight Wednesday by the New York's Dow Jones
industrial average, which rose 1.1 percent after a 3.2 percent drop on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors pushed futures contracts higher before the Hong Kong Stock
Exchange opened -- only to see share prices fall fast from the start.
</P>
<P>
	   On Asia's top market, the Tokyo Stock Exchange, blue chips shed 2 percent as
investors bailed out of high-tech companies that have taken a beating globally.
</P>
<P>
	   A 5.6 percent drop in the U.S. Nasdaq Composite Index on Tuesday sparked the
selloffs, and although the Nasdaq held its losses Wednesday to just 0.6 percent,
traders figured many high-tech companies were still too expensive.
</P>
<P>
	   Tokyo's Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed 374.28 points
lower at 18,168.27.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of the big decliners in Tokyo included high-tech concerns Sony and
Softbank.
</P>
<P>
	   "Unless Nasdaq and Internet shares stabilize, we'll see some more
corrections in Japan," said David Shirt, a stock salesman at Jardine Fleming in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korean prices swung wildly, with an early gain of 2.9 percent
evaporating as blue chips flip-flopped to finish with a loss of 2.6 percent on
concerns of higher U.S. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
	   Prices in Singapore, Australia, Malaysia and Thailand gave up initial gains
and turned lower, while markets rebounded in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
	   Prices closed marginally higher in the Philippines. New Zealand prices
closed today with a loss of 1.3 percent, with traders saying New York's better
performance failed to improve sentiment.
</P>
<P>
	   Taiwanese blue chips continued to buck the trend, finishing with a gain of
0.8 percent today -- on top of a 1.1 percent gain that made the Taipei market
the region's only winner Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Hong Kong market has been by far the hardest hit, leaving experts
sharply divided today in estimates of what might come next.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. investment bank Morgan Stanley Dean Witter predicted the Hang Seng
could fall another 30 percent to 12,000 points by the end of the year, while
rival Goldman Sachs forecast a record rally to 19,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0247 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 02:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Jan. 6, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel, Syria Get Down to Business
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- President Clinton is ready to plunge back into
difficult peacemaking between Israel and Syria as the two longtime foes engage
in intensive negotiations on a number of thorny issues. On Wednesday, the two
delegations began discussions for the first time in almost four years on issues
of substance. A committee dealing with mutual security concerns met all day,
focusing on the establishment of a demilitarized zone and an early warning
system, State Department spokesman James Rubin said. Clinton, who was here for
the first two days of the talks this week, stayed away Wednesday, but a senior
U.S. official said that the president probably would return Thursday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bradley, Gore Face Off on Health Care
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DURHAM N.H. (AP) -- In a feisty first debate of the new year, Democratic
presidential candidate Bill Bradley said Al Gore is stuck "in a Washington
bunker," and the vice president accused his rival of leaving New Hampshire
residents "high and dry" on health care. Bradley was more aggressive than usual
Wednesday night, forcing Gore to defend himself on a string of issues related to
President Clinton. Gore, armed with notecards and notepads, initially appeared
uncomfortable but warmed to the task of challenging Bradley's health care plan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Freed Militant Arrives in Pakistan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) -- One of three Kashmiri militants freed as part of a
deal to end the Indian Airlines hijacking called on his followers Wednesday to
destroy India and the United States. Maulana Masood Azhar told 10,000 supporters
"I have come here because this is my duty to tell you that Muslims should not
rest in peace until we have destroyed America and India," Azhar said. Though the
Pakistani government earlier said that the hijackers would be arrested if they
stepped foot in their country, there was no effort to detain Azhar or to bar him
from speaking Wednesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Voters Uncertain as Primaries Near
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The presidential campaigns are heating up, candidates are
debating day after day and the news media is delivering it all to the public --
but who's paying attention? Only one in 10 say in a new poll that they had
thought about the presidential campaign or talked about it with anyone on the
previous day. And nearly three-fourths of the public say they hadn't yet picked
a candidate, says the poll on voter interest taken by the Joan Shorenstein
Center on the Press Politics and Public Policy. That's compared with roughly
two-thirds in November.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Media Accused of Gun Control Bias
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The television networks are so badly slanting the gun
control debate they have become the "communications division of the anti-gun
lobby," says the head of a conservative media watchdog group that studied the
issue. The Media Research Center, chaired by Brent Bozell, released a study
Wednesday on two years of television news stories on gun control. The study
analyzed the morning shows and evening newscasts between July 1, 1997 and June
30, 1999. In many cases, the study claimed, pro-gun themes were not covered and
gun proponents were not given air time.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Algerian Held on Immigration Charges
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- An Algerian suspected of having links to a countryman
charged with trying to smuggle explosives into the United States was ordered
held without bond Wednesday. Abdel Hakim Tizegha, 29, is charged with illegally
entering the country and eluding federal officers at the Canadian border. He was
arrested Dec. 24. No link has been made in court between Tizegha and Ahmed
Ressam, who has pleaded innocent to federal charges accusing him of having
bomb-making materials in his rental car as he entered the country on Dec. 14.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hackers Become Security Consultants
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some of the Internet's most adept online snoops are
forming a new company to advise the world's largest banks and hospitals how to
keep their data safe from cyber-intruders. Members of the Boston-based L0pht
Heavy Industries, who once boasted to the Senate that any one of them could
cripple the Internet in the United States within 30 minutes, Thursday were
announcing the creation of their consulting company, AtStake.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Close Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average closed at 18,168.27
points on the Tokyo Stock Exchange Thursday, down 374.28 points from Wednesday.
Overnight on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 124.72 points to
11,122.65.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Panthers Defeat Mighty Ducks 5-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Victor Kozlov ended a six-game goal-scoring drought
with his first hat trick and Pavel Bure had a goal and two assists as the
Florida Panthers beat the Anaheim Mighty Ducks 5-1 Wednesday night. Ray Whitney
had a goal and an assist for the Panthers, who are 6-3-2 against the Ducks since
the teams entered the NHL in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0258 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0104 </DOCNO>
