<HEADLINE> Police investigating second suspect, even as murder trial underway  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   DANIELSON, Conn. (AP) - While prosecutors were trying Ryan Thompson on a
murder charge, police were investigating whether another teen-ager may have
pulled the trigger in the fatal shooting of Robert McCaffrey.
<P>
	   Thompson, now 20, is accused of shooting McCaffery outside an April, 1998
party in the Moosup section of Plainfield.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors say Thompson was not invited to the party and became involved in
a fight with several guests before the shooting occurred. McCaffery was shot
while sitting on the roof of a garage watching the altercation, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
	   In testimony at Thomspson's trial Wednesday, State Police Major Crime Squad
Sgt. John Turner acknowledged that within the past week, a detective was
investigating the theory that Thompson's friend David Stebbins fired the fatal
shot.
</P>
<P>
	   Stebbins, Thompson and several other teens were in a car together just
before the fatal shot was fired.
</P>
<P>
	   When questioned by defense attorney Arthur Meisler, Turner said detective
David LeBlanc came upon information that Stebbins was the shooter. He did not
elaborate, but said LeBlanc did interview a witness.
</P>
<P>
	   Police confiscated a rifle from Stebbins' home, but it has not been proven
that the rifle was used in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
	   An earlier witness said Stebbins' was upset about being picked on at the
party and he told her he had guns in the car and would use them if he had to,
according to court testimony.
</P>
<P>
	   But other evidence points to Thompson.
</P>
<P>
	   Two teen-agers told police Thompson jumped out of the car with a gun and
came back saying he thought he shot someone. Other witnesses also reported
seeing Thompson run to the car after the shot was fired.
</P>
<P>
	   The trial was to continue today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
