<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Seeks More Emergency Rule  </HEADLINE>
   By DILIP GANGULY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- The government asked Parliament today to extend
emergency rule, accusing Tamil Tiger rebels who have conducted a string of bomb
attacks recently of trying to destabilize the small island nation.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense Minister General Anuruddha Ratwatte put forward the request in
Parliament a day after a Tamil rebel blew herself up outside the prime
minister's office, killing herself and 12 others in the third major guerrilla
attack in the past 18 days in Colombo. The prime minister was not in her office
at the time of the attack.
</P>
<P>
	   The emergency rule allows the armed forces to search any home and detain any
person on suspicion of involvement with the rebels, who have been fighting a
secessionist war in the north and east since 1983. The emergency rule has been
in force for more than two years across Sri Lanka, and the government needs
Parliament's approval every month.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The government cannot take any chances, and steps have to be taken in the
national interest by extending the emergency rule,'' said Ratwatte, who is
coordinating the government's war efforts against the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam. Ratwatte has escaped two assassination attempts.
</P>
<P>
	   Parliament is expected to approve the motion later today.
</P>
<P>
	   There was unprecedented security in and around Parliament today.
Anti-terrorist commandos with dogs scanned the area.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, a female assassin killed herself as police tried to question
her outside the office of Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike.
</P>
<P>
	   It wasn't clear whether she wanted to attack the 82-year-old prime minister,
who mostly works from home because of poor health but had been expected at the
office Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Two hours later, unidentified gunmen on motorcycles shot and killed a
pro-rebel Tamil politician, Kumar Ponnambalam. The motive for slaying the
60-year-old politician was not known.
</P>
<P>
	   Three weeks ago, another female suicide bomber blew herself up at an
election rally of President Chandrika Kumaratunga, the prime minister's
daughter. Kumaratunga suffered a serious eye injury.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said today the woman was a member of the Black Tigers, a group they
characterized as the deadliest weapon in the armory of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   The LTTE describes the Black Tigers as a ``major wing'' of its fighting
formations and the female commandos as ``Birds of Freedom.''
</P>
<P>
	   A female LTTE suicide bomber killed former Indian Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi in 1991 in southern India.
</P>
<P>
	   Male and female suicide bombers begin training as children, sometimes at the
age of 10.
</P>
<P>
	   About half of the Tamil Tiger rebels are women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0306 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 03:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Denies Ties To TV License  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE KELLMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEDFORD, N.H. (AP) -- As the race for the Republican presidential nomination
heats up in New Hampshire over tax cuts and his chairmanship of the Senate
Commerce Committee, Sen. John McCain is challenging fellow candidates to reject
attack politics and to make the process noble again.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, the Arizona senator and frequent critic of the influence
of money in politics says his new status here as a serious challenger to George
W. Bush, the GOP presidential front-runner and Texas governor, is raising all
sorts of questions about his ethics.
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, McCain found himself on the defensive Wednesday, the same day the
Boston Globe reported that he had prodded a federal agency by letter to rule on
a license application submitted two years earlier by a campaign donor, Paxson
Communications.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said that he only pushed the Federal Communications Commission to
act, not on which decision to make -- which said is an appropriate step for a
congressional committee chairman with oversight of what he says is an
inefficient agency.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I didn't tell them to approve it; I told them to act,'' he said. ``I think
it's entirely appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, once a back-of-the-pack challenger who now is a genuine threat to
Bush in this state with the nation's first presidential primary on Feb. 1, says
his new status is making him a target for conflict-of-interest questions.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are going to be more stories like that,'' McCain said of the Boston
Globe article. ``When you get increased visibility you get more scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
	   The New York Times followed up late Wednesday night with a story on its Web
site about the Paxson matter and other instances where it said McCain urged the
FCC to act on a matter that later benefited a major contributor to his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain noted that the Commerce Committee has jurisdiction over 80 percent of
the nation's businesses, some of whom have contributed to his campaign. So, he
said, ``there is a natural suspicion'' if he makes decisions that ultimately
help those supporters.
</P>
<P>
	   It is not unusual for members of Congress to send letters to the FCC about
transactions under review. Nine other lawmakers, including Rep. John Dingell,
D-Mich., Rep. Ed Markey, D-Mass., and Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., also sent
inquiries to the agency about Paxson Communications, which owns 73
family-oriented TV stations and has legally provided a private jet for McCain's
use.
</P>
<P>
	   The Boston Globe also reported that company officials coordinated $20,000 in
campaign contributions to McCain, who appeared on at least two nationally
televised news programs Wednesday night to answer questions about his Dec. 10
letter to the FCC concerning Paxson.
</P>
<P>
	   Though McCain defended himself throughout the day, he ended up canceling a
weekend fund-raiser that was to be held by company chairman Lowell ``Bud''
Paxson, saying it would be inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
	   And, in a sign that McCain's campaign was growing increasingly concerned
about the matter, campaign officials poured through his Senate files Wednesday
looking for other instances in which he acted in cases involving donors. Fearing
the Globe story would prompt increased scrutiny of the candidate, aides wanted
to be ready to put his actions into context.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the issue gave Bush a chance to criticize McCain for the second
time in as many days as Republican contenders fought for advantage in this
first-in-the-nation primary state.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think it's really important for people who are advocating reforms to
live up to the spirit of reforms they are advocating,'' Bush told reporters
while campaigning in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
	   Later, in Manchester, N.H., Bush said, ``I respect John McCain'' and
acknowledged that ``I haven't seen the facts.'' But he also said, ``I think
somebody who makes campaign financing an issue has got to be consistent and walk
the walk.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's place in the polls here and his strong fund raising haven't
threatened Bush's front-runner status nationally. But Bush has shown his
determination to prevent that from happening by going after McCain on tax cuts
Monday in their first major policy dispute. The attack inspired McCain to
release details of a tax plan he hadn't intended to put out until Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
	   At one point Wednesday, McCain appeared with William Bennett, the former
education secretary and presidential drug adviser who has written widely on
morality. And he delivered a speech calling for presidential candidates to
refrain from personal attacks and distortion.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Please do not think I claim some special virtue among the candidates,''
McCain told the Boys and Girls Club of Manchester. ``If we accomplish anything
in this campaign, let those of us who seek the highest office in the land help
turn the practice of politics toward a higher plane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0307 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 03:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taxes Top GOP Presidential Debate  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEDFORD, N.H. (AP) -- After sparring at a distance for two days, Republican
presidential contenders George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain meet tonight for a
debate that is likely to provide a prime-time platform for their brewing
argument over who has the better tax-cut plan.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, R-Ariz., also faces the prospect of questions about his decision to
prod a federal regulatory agency to act on a request from one of his campaign
donors.
</P>
<P>
	   The one-hour debate, being held at the University of New Hampshire in
Durham, N.H., is sponsored by The (Manchester) Union Leader, New England Cable
News and New Hampshire Public Television. The moderator was NBC's Tim Russert.
</P>
<P>
	   In the latest spin on the tax theme, Bush said Wednesday that he was
``startled'' that McCain and Democrat Al Gore agree that his proposed five-year,
$483 billion tax plan may be too big for the country to afford.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think it is just right,'' Bush, the Texas governor, told reporters after
touring a Fidelity Investments office here. ``It's a plan that I intend to
defend in the primaries. It's a plan I'm going to campaign on in the general
election, and it's a plan I hope to put in place when I become president of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
	   In June, McCain proposed to expand the 15 percent bottom tax bracket,
eliminate the so-called ``marriage penalty,'' give relief to Social Security
recipients who work and eliminate taxes on estates worth up to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Next week, in response to Bush's challenge, McCain will expand on his plan.
Aides said the package will be significantly smaller than Bush's, but focus on
Americans earning $30,000 to $70,000 a year and with more than half his cuts
helping people who are not wealthy.
</P>
<P>
	   Under McCain's plan, 60 percent of the surplus would help shore up Social
Security and the rest would go to Medicare and debt reduction. Bush has no plans
to pump extra money into Social Security.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Governor Bush should explain to those nice people at his news conference
why 60 percent of his tax plan helps the rich without doing anything to save
Social Security,'' said McCain spokesman Dan Schnur.
</P>
<P>
	   One other expected debate subject centered on whether McCain lives up to his
stern campaign rhetoric about the corrosive effect of special interests on the
political process.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, urged the Federal
Communications in a Dec. 10 letter to act quickly on a matter involving Paxson
Communications, a company that owns 73 family-oriented TV stations and has
legally provided a private jet for McCain's use.
</P>
<P>
	   The Boston Globe first reported the story Wednesday, saying company
officials coordinated $20,000 in campaign contributions to McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said Wednesday that he did not tell the FCC which way to vote. ``I
told them to act,'' the senator said. ``I think it's entirely appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sharing the stage with Bush and McCain tonight are conservative activist
Gary Bauer, millionaire publisher Steve Forbes, Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah and
former U.N. ambassador Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauer said he again will train his focus on Bush, who is running even with
McCain in New Hampshire polls but holds a sizable lead in national surveys.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want to nail Governor Bush on whether he's a conservative,'' Bauer told
a news conference in Manchester on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes, on the other hand, dismissed as ``this little food fight'' the
sparring between Bush and McCain over taxes. He said neither candidate was
getting to the heart of the problem.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This little tax credit, this little tinkering with the code. I think
you've got to be bold, get rid of the thing, give a real tax cut to people
instead of making them go through hoops and loops,'' Forbes told reporters after
greeting voters at a restaurant in Franklin. Forbes has proposed scrapping the
existing tax code, and replacing it with a 17 percent flat tax for everyone,
with exemptions of $13,000 for adults and $5,000 for children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 03:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Villagers Await Reunion With Syria  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE COPANS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GHAJAR, Golan Heights (AP) -- Stranded behind enemy lines during the 1967
Mideast War, the residents of this Alawite village chose to accept Israeli
citizenship rather than leave their homes on the banks of the three main
tributaries to the Jordan River.
</P>
<P>
	   But the precious water in those tributaries could prevent their village from
going back to Syria as part of a peace deal with Israel, being negotiated this
week in Shepardstown, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel will demand that any Golan territory it hands back to Syria exclude
the area around the Hatsbani, Dan and Banias rivers. The water runs into the Sea
of Galilee, Israel's main source of drinking water.
</P>
<P>
	   As Alawite Arabs -- members of the Muslim sect to which Syrian President
Hafez Assad belongs -- many in Ghajar anticipate that the sides will work out an
arrangement that will either restore their village to Syrian sovereignty or
allow them to join their families in Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am hoping and praying that we will be returned to Syria,'' said Yousef
Salman, 26, who said most of the 1,760 villagers are willing to relocate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But my father's brothers, who fled the village to Syria, have memories.
They want to come back here.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bloody battles almost 33 years ago over the precious water sources were
fought east of Ghajar, ending with Israeli troops capturing the farmland
villagers had cultivated for more than 300 years.
</P>
<P>
	   In that war, Israel captured the Golan Heights, which it later annexed and
is now considering returning in exchange for peace with Syria. The Syrian
government says it must return the entire Golan -- which would include the
village.
</P>
<P>
	   But during the 1967 war, neither Israeli nor Syrian soldiers even tried to
enter Ghajar, located on the border between Lebanon and the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
	   The villagers said Syria forgot about them.
</P>
<P>
	   All but 200 residents fled, and the rest, unable to reach their fields, were
on the verge of starvation three months after the war ended. Village elders
finally asked to be put under Israeli control, so they could return to their
fields.
</P>
<P>
	   Salman Mohammed al-Hatib, who has headed the village for the last 41 years
and presided over the decision to come under Israeli control, is cautious about
expressing his loyalties. He refuses to say which country he prefers, Syria or
Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We don't have personal opinions,'' said al-Hatib, 70, seated under the
Israeli flag that hangs behind his desk. ``We want peace and hope for the
reunification of the families.''
</P>
<P>
	   The residents of Ghajar do not, like many of the 18,000 Druze Arabs living
on the Golan Heights, hold pro-Syrian protests to demonstrate their loyalty to
Assad.
</P>
<P>
	   The Alawites want to make sure not to antagonize Israel since it may
continue to rule over them even after a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, because they have common roots with Assad, Ghajar residents feel
confident that the Syrian leader will treat them fairly if the village comes
under Syrian control, regardless of their behavior now.
</P>
<P>
	   The Alawite people make up between 6 and 11 eleven percent of Syria's 15
million citizens. Many Muslims consider members of the secretive, Shiite sect to
be heretics, and the group tends to stick together.
</P>
<P>
	   In Ghajar, most of the older residents still work the land, tending olive
groves or cows in the pastures set among the mine fields that surround the
village.
</P>
<P>
	   But younger villagers have largely shrugged off their parents' attachment to
the land in favor of mostly menial jobs in nearby Israeli towns.
</P>
<P>
	   Salman admits that he studied mechanical engineering at an Israeli
university, speaks Hebrew and carries an Israeli ID card.
</P>
<P>
	   But he has always dreamed of leaving this land for Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   He hopes eventually to take the woman he will marry next week, also from
Ghajar, to Syria. He said he is ready for a fresh start in a new place.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Everyone here has a deep connection to the home, like the olive trees to
the land,'' Salman said, playing with a gold ring on his finger. ``But I don't
feel Israeli. My nationality is Syrian.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 0311 </TRAILER>
