<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerian Held on Immigration Charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- An Algerian accused of illegally entering the United States
remains jailed without bond as investigators look into whether there is a
widespread plot to smuggle explosives into the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Abdel Hakim Tizegha, 29, was to appear before a federal magistrate on
Wednesday, but his attorney did not challenge a government motion to detain him.
</P>
<P>
	   Tizegha is charged with illegally entering the country and eluding federal
officers at the Canadian border. He was arrested Dec. 24 in Bellevue, a suburb
east of Seattle, after allegedly crossing the border at Blaine, about 100 miles
north of here.
</P>
<P>
	   No link has been made in court between Tizegha and Ahmed Ressam, who has
pleaded innocent to federal charges accusing him of having bomb-making materials
in his rental car as he entered the country on Dec. 14.
</P>
<P>
	   But newspaper reports have said that Tizegha is linked to Ressam and that
Tizegha and another man investigated in the case, Abdel Ghani, are longtime
friends. Ghani is charged with helping Ressam.
</P>
<P>
	   A fourth man, Abdel Majid Dahoumane, is believed to have stayed with Ressam
at a motel in British Columbia. Warrants have been issued for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   According to former CIA counterterrorism chief Vincent Cannistraro, all four
are part of a terrorist splinter group in Algeria that is supported by Osama bin
Laden, the Saudi exile believed to have masterminded last year's attack on two
U.S. embassies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   Cannistraro, citing French counterterrorism officials, said Wednesday the
men belong to a faction that broke with the Armed Islamic Group in Algeria,
known by its French acronym GIA, over its practice of targeting fellow Muslims.
</P>
<P>
	   French investigators have said Ressam has links to Fateh Kamel, who has been
jailed in Paris since April and is suspected of being the leader of an Islamic
militant group. Cannistraro said Kamel is the leader of the GIA splinter group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
