<HEADLINE> Tokyo Share Prices Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell Thursday on hefty selling of
high-technology issues despite Wall Street's overnight rebound. The U.S. dollar
was higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average ended the day down 374.28
points, or 2.02 percent, at 18,168.27. On Wednesday, the key average plunged
460.31 points, or 2.42 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 104.38 yen at 3 p.m. (0600 GMT), up 1.20 yen from 103.18
yen posted late Wednesday in Tokyo and above 104.35 yen overnight in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, traders taking profits sold high-tech issues which had
posted significant gains over the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   "The market is under a correction phase after rallies late last year in high
technology and information shares," said Hidenori Karaki, general manager at
Tokyo-Mitsubishi Personal Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   "But the market's fundamentals are not bad," he said, citing steady buying
interest from foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
	   In a market dominated by sell orders, pharmaceutical issues rose as
investors shifted away from high-tech into domestic demand-related issues.
</P>
<P>
	   "Until price fluctuations of information technology shares stabilize,
investors will shift to biotechnology-related issues," said Kunihiro Hatae,
general manager at Tokyo Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   Overnight on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 124.72
points, or 1.1 percent, to 11,122.65. The Dow had risen as much as 216 points in
earlier trading. It plunged 359.58 points on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-laden Nasdaq Composite Index ended a highly volatile session
Wednesday with a loss of 24.09 points, or 0.6 percent, at 3,877.60. On Tuesday,
it suffered its worst point loss, declining 229.46 points.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section shed 42.25 points, or 2.56 percent, to 1609.59. The TOPIX closed down
65.63 points, or 3.82 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency trading, the dollar climbed higher after overseas investors sold
yen for dollars to cash in on Japanese stocks and other yen-denominated assets.
</P>
<P>
	   Japanese life insurers and investment trust funds also bought the dollar,
traders said. The same players bought the euro for yen as well.
</P>
<P>
	   The euro was traded at 108.28 yen, up from 107.24 yen late in Tokyo on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar began gaining earlier this week after the Bank of Japan bought
the currency to stem the yen's rise.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan's vice finance minister, Haruhiko Kuroda, told reporters Thursday that
the yen was still too strong.
</P>
<P>
	   "In terms of fundamentals, it is still clearly excessive," Kuroda said.
</P>
<P>
	   Too strong a yen hurts the income of export-based industries, which
repatriate profits earned overseas in dollars back to Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond was at 1.7000,
up from 1.6950 Wednesday. Its price stood at 101.70, down 0.04 point from
101.74.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
