<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wildlife activists blame whale's death on captivity  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NIAGARA FALLS, Ontario (AP) - A whale's death at a marine park has
revived a wildlife protection group's complaints about keeping animals captive.
<P>
	   The white beluga whale, along with eight others, was taken from the Russian
Sea of Okhotsk by Zoolex, a Moscow broker. Zoolex transported the whales across
Russia to Moscow, where they rode 10-hour flights to Toronto and then were
brought to Marineland in Niagara Falls, Ontario, in October.
</P>
<P>
	   The whale died Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
	   Zoocheck Canada, a Toronto-based animal protection agency, has repeatedly
criticized Marineland for importing the belugas and has been investigating the
park for three years. So while preliminary tests did not indicate the animal's
cause of death, the group has already blamed the stress of being taken from the
ocean and the park environment.
</P>
<P>
	   "The autopsy found no organ problems or disease," said John Holer, owner of
the Marineland theme park, who maintains that the capture and travel caused no
trauma. Tissue from the dead whale has been sent to an offsite laboratory for
further tests.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's very unscientific, but my belief is that these animals just give up
the will to live," said Rob Laidlaw, director of Zoocheck Canada. "They are put
into situations where they experience enormous amounts of stress that they
haven't evolved to deal with."
</P>
<P>
	   Laidlaw said some Russian businesses capture whales "netted in fishing nets,
tied to boats and driven to shore where they are pulled up onto shore by their
tails."
</P>
<P>
	   He added, "Even under the very, very best circumstances, there's still
stress involved in lifting an animal out of the water when that's their normal
habitat."
</P>
<P>
	   Laidlaw also argued that Marineland's tank isn't large enough.
</P>
<P>
	   The remaining belugas, including three purchased from Zoolex last May, live
in a tank of 5 million gallons of seawater.
</P>
<P>
	   Because Marineland is a privately owned business, animal habitats are not
subject to Ontario government regulation.
</P>
<P>
	   Holer said the whale seemed healthy until Christmas Day, when it stopped
eating and hung to one side of its tank. Blood tests that day indicated a
failing immune system.
</P>
<P>
	   Belugas, which can grow to be up to 16 feet long and 3,300 pounds, have been
known to swim 3,000 to 4,000 square-miles in a three month period. They can dive
up to 6,500 feet.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's very upsetting to the staff when an animal dies," said Ann Marie
Rondinelli, of Marineland's marketing department. "It's like a family, so it's
painful that the poor animal is dead."
</P>
<P>
	   Nine North American aquariums and zoos house beluga whales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-06-00 0323 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 03:23 </DATE_TIME>
