<HEADLINE> Neighbors welcome Clintons to their town  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. (AP) - When the first dog, Buddy Clinton, needs a
shampoo, the pet care center in Chappaqua is ready.
<P>
	   Christine DiPaulo, owner of Wags &AMP; Whiskers pet grooming, said the Secret
Service already had visited her store. After the Clintons leave the White House
for good, this will likely be the place the presidential pooch gets his
shampoos.
</P>
<P>
	   The agents "asked if it would be all right if somebody stayed with the pet,"
DiPaulo said. "I said, 'Of course.' I don't really expect to see Mrs. Clinton,
though."
</P>
<P>
	   The Westchester County hamlet is welcoming its newest arrivals - President
Clinton and wife Hillary - with open arms.
</P>
<P>
	   "I would be willing to offer my services, and I'm pleased to have her in
this little town," said hair stylist Santa Nikkels, owner of Santa's Salon &AMP;
Spa. "I would be able to do her hair at (her) home."
</P>
<P>
	   Nikkels was so thrilled by the Clintons' imminent arrival that she sent Mrs.
Clinton a letter volunteering her services.
</P>
<P>
	   "I told her, 'I'm excited because I'm new here, too,"' said Nikkels, an
Ecuadorian immigrant who opened her Chappaqua shop just six months ago.
</P>
<P>
	   While some residents in the town of 17,000 have griped about the incessant
attention drawn by the Clintons, most people seemed eager to greet them as they
moved into their $1.7 million home.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think there's been some disturbance for the people on the (Clintons')
street," said Chappaqua resident Wilma Rapp, a customer at the Q Nails salon.
"Other than that, people feel pretty good about the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
	   "You tell somebody you live in Chappaqua and they say, 'Oh! Hillary!"'
</P>
<P>
	   Town Supervisor Marion Sinek, who stopped outside the Clintons' home on
Wednesday, said the couple had chosen to live in Chappaqua for the same reason
as many locals.
</P>
<P>
	   No, not to run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a beautiful suburb with beautiful streets like this," the Democratic
official said, standing on the Clintons' new block. "We are happy to have them.
We welcome them."
</P>
</TEXT>
