<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 04:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspects arrested in money-laundering prostitution case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   DALLAS (AP) - Federal agents operating fake financial-services companies
in Dallas and Columbus, Ohio, helped uncover a money-laundering ring tied to
prostitution in cities across the nation.
<P>
	   One undercover Dallas company, Tejas Financial, laundered more than $2
million in credit-card charges paid to prostitutes during the investigation,
which goes back to the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   Trials or sentencing dates are set for January and February for the
suspects, including a New Jersey lawyer and a Garland man who once claimed to
control much of the Dallas area's prostitution business, The Dallas Morning News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
	   Assistant U.S. Attorney James T. Jacks said hundreds of escort services were
netted in the cases. Most of the cases have been farmed to other U.S. attorney's
offices for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
	   But up to 15 cases are being handled in Dallas, including those of about 10
suspects from the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
	   Jacks obtained a conspiracy and money-laundering indictment against Boston
resident John Okowinski. He is accused of using at least five Massachusetts
escort services as fronts for prostitution and laundering some proceeds through
Tejas Financial Services, an Internal Revenue Service shell company in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
	   Also last month, U.S. District Judge Joe Kendall sentenced former Boston
pimp Carl Orlowski, 46, to five months in prison and fined him $4,000 for
promoting prostitution in interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
	   Orlowski agreed to cooperate with prosecutors after admitting he ran
prostitutes through his escort services.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigation put many prostitution operations out of business, but it
was aimed at the money laundering business, Jacks said.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the suspects netted were the business partners involved with Paramus,
N.J., company Entertainment Management Services Inc., which prosecutors say
charged prostitution clients up to 18 percent of their profits for laundering
credit-card charges.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm running a national prostitution money-laundering ring," Robert A.
Hollis, a New Jersey lawyer and partner in EMS, told two undercover IRS agents,
Andrew Merlino and Mark Parsons. "All of our clients are pimps and madams."
</P>
<P>
	   Hollis has pleaded guilty to money laundering and admitted that he helped
wash up to $3.4 million in profits from illegal sex operations and is scheduled
to be sentenced Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
	   Hollis' business partners, former Boston escort-service operator Kenneth
Patrick Byrnes and former EMS bookkeeper David S. Schneider, were indicted this
fall on money-laundering charges. They are set for trial Jan. 18, although that
might be delayed.
</P>
<P>
	   Okowinski, who is set for trial Jan. 18, refused to comment. His attorney,
John F. Lubben III, could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
	   Several co-defendants, including confessed Garland prostitution operator
Allen C. Walker, have agreed to testify against Okowinski.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
