<HEADLINE> Rapper's Film Career Successful  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Ice Cube's foray into the film world is proving to be just
as successful as his rap career.
</P>
<P>
	   The 30-year-old rapper, who made his acting debut in 1991's "Boyz 'N the
Hood," is releasing the sequel to his successful comedy "Friday" next week.
"Next Friday" was written and produced by Ice Cube, who also stars in the film.
</P>
<P>
	   "I wrote them because we had seen South Central movies like 'Boyz 'N the
Hood' and 'Menace II Society' showing my neighborhood one way, and I wanted to
show what I thought about it," the rapper says in the Jan. 6 edition of Time Out
New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Ice Cube also made his directorial debut with 1998's "The Players Club" and
was one of the stars of last year's critically acclaimed "Three Kings" with
George Clooney.
</P>
<P>
	   Ice Cube said he was not disappointed that "Three Kings" underperformed at
the box office.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's no guarantee that a lot of people are going to see a movie. But the
people who did see it: Do they like it? That's all that matters."
</P>
</TEXT>
