<HEADLINE> Dow Up 5.89; Nasdaq Down 56.77  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed at the start of trading today,
with technology shares remaining weak while blue chips managed a slight advance.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 5.89 at 11,128.54.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 7.66 at 1,394.45, and the Nasdaq composite index was down 56.77 at
3,820.77.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks continued to tumble in profit-taking from last year's
record-breaking rise. Some of last year's best performers fell. Yahoo! fell 8
5/8 to 401 7/8, and Qualcomm fell 5 15/16 to 150 1/2.
</P>
<P>
	   The sector was also pressured by Gateway's warning late Wednesday that
fourth-quarter earnings would miss expectations. The computer maker blamed a
decline in sales due to Y2K fears and component supply problems.
</P>
<P>
	   Gateway, which fell steeply in extended-hours trading Wednesday, bounced
back today and was up 4 11/16 to 58 11/16. But traders said the company's
warning contributed to weakness in other computer makers' share prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Dell dropped 2 7/16 to 47 1/2, and Apple fell 1 1/2 to 102 1/2.
</P>
<P>
	   The market has been rattled this week by growing concerns that the Federal
Reserve will soon raise interest rates in an effort to stave off inflation. The
Fed raised rates three times in 1999, and is expected to resume its course of
action as early as Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders said the market might revive on Friday if the Labor Department's
monthly unemployment report, which contains data on wages and the number of jobs
created, shows modest or slowing growth.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, the government said its weekly tally of new claims for unemployment
benefits rose by 33,000 last week, the largest increase in a year. Jobless
claims had fallen by 7,000 in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Labor Department analysts stressed that the claims level is often
volatile during holiday periods and they cautioned against reading too much into
one week's movement in jobless claims.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 118.79 million shares, slightly behind
Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index fell 1.61 to 477.22.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas indexes continued to slip amid fears of higher interest rates in
the United States. Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 2.02 percent. In afternoon
trading, Germany's DAX index was down 1.0 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down
1.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 1.0 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
