<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 61.12; Nasdaq Down 62.74  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with technology shares remaining
weak while blue chips advanced on the strength of old-fashioned cyclical
companies.
</P>
<P>
	   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
61.12 at 11,183.77.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 0.12 at 1,401.99, and the Nasdaq composite index was down 62.74 at
3,820.77.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks continued to tumble in profit-taking from last year's
record-breaking rise. Some of last year's best performers fell. Yahoo! lost 10
13/16 to 399 11/16, and Qualcomm fell 7 1/2 to 148 15/16.
</P>
<P>
	   That wave of selling, which has been exacerbated by investors' desire to
sell now and pay their capital-gains taxes in 2001, may soon ebb, said Larry
Rice, chief investment officer at Josephthal &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   "These stocks will bounce back," he said. "There are too many people who are
still eager to buy. And these companies still hold great potential for making a
lot of money."
</P>
<P>
	   Still, fears of slowing profits for two high-tech firms depressed the sector
today. Gateway warned late Wednesday its fourth-quarter earnings would miss
expectations due to a slowdown in sales. The computer maker blamed Year 2000
computer worries and component supply problems.
</P>
<P>
	   Gateway, which fell steeply in extended-hours trading Wednesday, bounced
back today and was up 5 7/8 to 59 7/8. But traders said the company's warning
contributed to weakness in other computer makers' share prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Dell dropped 2 21/64 to 47 39/64, and Apple fell 3 5/8 to 100 3/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Intel fell 2 3/8 to 81 1/4. Gateway blamed the semiconductor maker for some
of its supply problems.
</P>
<P>
	   MCI WorldCom was down 3 9/16 at 47 3/4 after Salomon Smith Barney analyst
Jack Grubman lowered his earnings and revenue estimates for fiscal year 2000.
Grubman said the company's revenue is likely to grow 14.4 percent from 1999 to
2000, below his previous estimate of 15.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader market has been rattled this week by growing concerns that the
Federal Reserve will soon raise interest rates in an effort to stave off
inflation. The Fed raised rates three times in 1999, and is expected to resume
its course of action as early as Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
	   As fears have escalated, investors have shifted some money from technology
stocks to cyclical stocks, which depend upon economic growth. Caterpillar rose 2
to 51 1/8 and Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose 1 11/16 to 91 7/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors are now awaiting Friday's monthly unemployment report from the
Labor Department, which contains data on wages and the number of jobs created,
shows modest or slowing growth.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, the government said its weekly tally of new claims for unemployment
benefits rose by 33,000 last week, the largest increase in a year. Jobless
claims had fallen by 7,000 in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Labor Department analysts stressed that the claims level is often
volatile during holiday periods and they cautioned against reading too much into
one week's movement in jobless claims.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 310.72 million shares, slightly behind
Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index fell 2.99 to 475.84.
</P>
