<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans Lead Wheat, Corn Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices rose today in early
dealings on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
	   The rise extended gains Wednesday when March soybeans reached a four-week
high -- mostly on forecasts calling for continued dry weather in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat futures posted smaller gains in part due to technical factors. The
gains were milder due to continued weak export demand.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders are monitoring dry soil conditions in the southern Plains states
that may damage red winter wheat crops, eventually lessening the supply.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts say corn is also likely to get a boost from the rise in soybean
prices. But they say any increases will continue to be tempered by farmers'
large stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
	   In early trading, wheat for March delivery was up  3/4 cent to $2.50 1/2 a
bushel; March corn rose 1 1/4 cents to $2.04 1/4 a bushel; March oats were a 
1/4 cent higher at $1.09 1/2 a bushel; and March soybeans rose 1 3/4 cents to
$4.78 3/4 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, livestock and meat futures prices were mixed in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   February live cattle were up 0.28 cent to 69.35 cents a pound; March feeder
cattle rose 0.27 cent to 85.97 cents a pound; February lean hogs fell 0.35 cent
to 55.27 cents a pound; and February pork bellies were up 0.43 cent to 81.55
cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
