<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germans Recall some Soccer Jerseys  </HEADLINE>
    By HANS GREIMEL Associate Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Three major department store chains are yanking
yellow-and-black jerseys of one of Germany's most popular soccer teams after
reports that the Nike-made shirts are laced with a toxic chemical usually
reserved for anti-barnacle paint on ships.
</P>
<P>
	   The Kaufhof and Karstadt department stores stopped selling the $75 jerseys
for the northern German soccer club Borussia Dortmund Wednesday after the German
magazine "Plusminus," which commissioned a private lab to test various textiles,
reported the problem.
</P>
<P>
	   Tributyltin, or TBT, might seem a good additive for sports shirts in that it
is used to kill bacteria and quell the stench of excessive sweating. But British
and Dutch tests have shown the substance to cause mutations in marine snails and
the World Wildlife Fund is calling for its global ban.
</P>
<P>
	   At high levels in humans, it is believed to cause neurological problems,
damage the immune system and harm the liver, said Juergen Kundke, a scientist
with the German Institute for the Protection of Consumer Health.
</P>
<P>
	   "We don't know how much is in the shirts, so we can't analyze the risks," he
said. "We knew that the substance was still used in coatings for ships, but it
shouldn't be in textiles that people wear."
</P>
<P>
	   However, by Thursday afternoon, mega-chain Hertie had joined the recall and
Karstadt said it was also pulling other official team jerseys made by Nike as a
precaution, even though only the Borussia Dortmund shirts were tested.
</P>
<P>
	   A Nike spokeswoman in Germany, Susanne Walter, said the company was still
looking into the claims, but didn't say when the company was likely to have
results from its own inquiry.
</P>
<P>
	   "We didn't know anything about the existence of the substance in the jerseys
until Monday," she said. "We are taking the situation very, very seriously."
</P>
<P>
	   Kundke suggested that it may be too soon to jump to conclusions about the
toxicity of the shirts.
</P>
<P>
	   "From a strictly scientific standpoint, only one lab has analyzed the
textiles so far. So it would really need more testing to know more specifics,"
he said. "Right now, we don't know how high the levels are."
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Kundke said those who are worried should wash the shirts to rinse off
the TBT or wear the jersey with an undershirt to keep it from touching the body,
as the chemical is known to pass through skin.
</P>
<P>
	   Borussia Dortmund, one of the nation's most popular clubs and 1997 European
champion, doesn't seem too worried, though. The team plans to wear the jerseys
at a scrimmage Saturday, and club spokesman Josef Schneck noted that all of the
players tend to wear undershirts.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are taking the issue seriously," Schneck said. "But the team is not
overcome with panic."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
