<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Confidence Not Rattled  </HEADLINE>
    By DIRK BEVERIDGE AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- The market was way down Thursday as a dozen men crowded
around a computer in the Wing Lung Bank, staring at stock prices as intently as
Las Vegas die-hards would watch the bars and cherries spin on a slot machine.
</P>
<P>
	   There were no jackpots to cheer for, as the blue chips got pounded by heavy
selling that pushed the Hang Seng Index down 4.4 percent following Wednesday's
precipitous dive of 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   But instead of panicking, many stock-crazy Hong Kong investors are trying to
guess when prices will bottom out so they can buy more.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's overselling," said Frederick Wong, a bank clerk checking the
prices at a branch of BOCI Securities Ltd.
</P>
<P>
	   Hong Kong has been harder hit than any other major market since the world's
traders staged a sell-off that began Tuesday in New York. But analysts say
ordinary stock players are correct in thinking the current jolt -- while painful
-- isn't about to derail Hong Kong's recovery from recession.
</P>
<P>
	   The Hong Kong market just got too high, market professionals say, in rallies
fueled more by Internet hype than sound economics.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was way ahead of itself," said Vivian Kwok, chief stock analyst at
Sassoon Securities. She predicts more price volatility in the market but says
"Hong Kong's economy is on track."
</P>
<P>
	   The economy recently turned the corner and is growing again after a 15-month
recession.
</P>
<P>
	   Every time Hong Kong stocks go a bit wild, people congregate around
computers in the lobbies of local banks and brokerages, calling up prices every
few seconds to make sure they don't miss a thing. Hong Kong exists to make
money, and playing the stocks is a natural in a town where horse racing is the
main sport and the casinos of nearby Macau are a favored weekend haunt.
</P>
<P>
	   Many investors have been cursing out loud at the stock quotation screens,
but they aren't deterred.
</P>
<P>
	   Wong said he lost about 20,000 Hong Kong dollars ($2,560) over the past two
days. This after seeing the market set a record on Monday, the first trading day
of 2000. Will he sell out? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm trying to wait and buy at the bottom," Wong said.
</P>
<P>
	   The volatile market has attracted some wildly differing price forecasts.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. investment bank Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised eyebrows Thursday by
predicting the Hang Seng could tumble another 30 percent this year to 12,000
points. Rival Goldman Sachs quickly countered that the Hang Seng should set new
records -- all the way to 19,000.
</P>
<P>
	   But after Wednesday's slide, which saw the Hang Seng plunge from above
17,000 points to below 16,000 in just minutes -- only to be followed by a brief
dip below 15,000 points on Thursday -- who knows what to bet on next?
</P>
<P>
	   The Hang Seng finished Thursday at 15,153.23 after bouncing off late
afternoon lows that had it down as much as 6.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the small-time investors were packed in six deep in a lobby of
the Po Sang Bank, watching every price.
</P>
<P>
	   "Overall, I'm confident," said Dick Wong, a customs officer. "The economy is
getting better."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
