<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HUD Insuring Larger Mortgage Loans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a move designed to boost the number of homeowners
around the nation, the government will begin insuring mortgage loans up to
nearly $220,000 in high-cost areas for single family homes.
</P>
<P>
	   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo said Thursday that on
Jan. 1, HUD began insuring mortgage loans for single-family homes ranging from
$121,296, in communities where housing costs are lower, to $219,849, in areas
with higher housing costs.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1999, the limits ranged from $115,200 to $208,800.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These higher loan limits will help create more homeowners, more home
constructions, more jobs and more economic growth,'' Cuomo said. ``They will
transform the American dream of homeownership into a reality for families across
the nation.''
</P>
<P>
	   The new loan limits are part of a regular annual adjustment HUD makes to
account for rising home prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Under federal law, the loan limits are indexed to the conforming loan limits
of Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae, federally chartered corporations that buy and
package mortgages.
</P>
<P>
	   HUD also raised the mortgage loan limits for Federal Housing Administration
insurance for two, three and four-family homes.
</P>
<P>
	   For two family units, the new limit in low cost areas is $155,232 ranging to
$281,358 in high cost areas. The limit had been $147,408 up to $267,177.
</P>
<P>
	   The new range for three-family units is from $187,632 in low cost areas to
$340,083 in more expensive neighborhoods. The limit had been $178,176 to
$322,944.
</P>
<P>
	   For four family units, the new limit range is $233,184 in less costly areas
to $422,646. The limit range had been $221,448 to $401,375.
</P>
<P>
	   The new limits are expected to help drive the nation's home ownership rate
past its current level of 67 percent of all households. More than 70 million
American families own their homes, more than any other time in the nation's
history, according to HUD officials.
</P>
<P>
	   The FHA, which does not make home loans directly but insures loans made by
private lenders, insured nearly 1.3 million home mortgages in 1999 at a value of
$124 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   One housing expert said that while the increase probably would not greatly
affect first time home buyers because they will purchase homes that fall under
the limit ceiling, the higher loan limit could help others.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It will have a marginal impact overall but every little bit helps. For
people on the margins of affording homes, it will be a windfall,'' said Robert
E. Litan, a former associate director of the Office of Management and Budget who
now works at the Brookings Institution, a political think tank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
