<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Claims Frito-Lay Stole Can Idea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A Utah inventor has filed suit claiming snack food
maker Frito-Lay Inc. stole his idea for a can shaped like a soda-pop container
that can dispense other food.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Kirkland filed the suit late last month in U.S. District Court alleging
the PepsiCo Inc. division violated a patent he has been awarded by the U.S.
Patent and Trademark Office. The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
	   Frito-Lay spokeswoman Lynn Markley on Wednesday said the company had not yet
seen the lawsuit and therefore could not comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
	   Frito-Lay, headquartered in Plano, Texas, last year sold more than $11
billion of snack foods such as Lay's potato chips, Doritos tortilla chips and
Cheetos cheese-flavored snacks.
</P>
<P>
	   Kirkland alleged in the suit that he filed for patent protection for this
new method of vending snack foods in 1993 and later approached Frito-Lay with
his idea in hopes of forming a joint venture.
</P>
<P>
	   Developing a can capable of dispensing food provides a way for a variety of
snacks to be sold in machines originally manufactured to sell only beverages.
</P>
<P>
	   "While his patent applications were pending, Frito-Lay had been
(independently) test marketing this exact idea," said Julie Morriss, Kirkland's
attorney.
</P>
<P>
	   Kirkland was awarded a patent on Dec. 28 and filed the suit the same day. He
lives in Sandy, Utah, and Frito-Lay has a manufacturing plant in Kearns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1412 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
