<DOCNO> APW20000106.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Plans Early Marriage Tax Vote  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Looking to spotlight a top Republican priority early in
this election year, House Speaker Dennis Hastert said today that the House's
first major vote of 2000 will be on easing the ``marriage tax penalty'' on
millions of couples.
</P>
<P>
	   Hastert, R-Ill., said the House would also vote quickly on tax breaks to
help families save for public and private school costs, and ``community
renewal'' tax cuts for businesses investing in low-income and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
	   He also said the GOP was working on a plan to erase the national debt, the
accumulated mountain of federal IOUs that now stands at $5.6 trillion. No
details of that plan were available.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is only the start of our agenda to make certain that we secure the
blessings of prosperity for our children into the next century, but I think it's
a good start,'' Hastert said in remarks prepared for a news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   Though GOP aides said the cost of the tax cuts was not yet available, they
said the reductions -- and their price tag -- would be similar to elements of
the tax package President Clinton vetoed last September. Together, the three tax
cuts the House will vote on had a 10-year cost of $125 billion in last year's
vetoed bill.
</P>
<P>
	   The cuts would be paid for from projected budget surpluses, a House aide
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Votes on the tax measures are expected before the spring, said the aide.
</P>
<P>
	   When Clinton vetoed the $792 billion, 10-year tax package last September, he
argued it would have devoured federal budget surpluses that should instead be
devoted to shoring up Medicare and other federal programs.
</P>
<P>
	   Many Republicans feel the three tax cuts Hastert described were among the
most popular elements of the vetoed tax measure. They hope that advancing them
as separate, smaller bills will draw more attention to the proposals themselves,
blunting Clinton's ability to focus the debate on their price tag.
</P>
<P>
	   The strategy will also align congressional Republicans with Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the GOP's leading presidential contender. He has made reducing
the marriage penalty tax a major feature of his $483 billion, five-year tax cut.
</P>
<P>
	   The ``marriage penalty'' is the additional tax many two-income couples must
pay above what they would owe if they were single. To ease it, last year's GOP
tax bill would have gradually doubled the standard deduction, and increased the
amount of income subject to the lowest, 15 percent tax bracket for couples
filing jointly.
</P>
<P>
	   That bill would also have created 20 ``renewal communities,'' including four
in rural areas, where businesses could get tax breaks for creating jobs,
cleaning up former industrial sites and other actions.
</P>
<P>
	   It also would have raised to $2,000 the current $500-a-year limit on
families' contributions to education savings accounts. The money can be
withdrawn tax-free and used for public and private elementary and secondary
schools and colleges.
</P>
<P>
	   The economy has continued performing so well that budget analysts from both
political parties say they expect surplus projections from the Congressional
Budget Office and the White House, due in several weeks, to be hundreds of
billions of dollars bigger over the next decade than was expected last summer.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, both budget offices envisioned 10-year surpluses of $3 trillion,
two-thirds of which came from Social Security and was considered untouchable by
both parties for use for spending or tax cuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1413 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
