<DOCNO> APW20000106.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert:Tax Relief Heads GOP Agenda  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tax relief for married couples and for parents saving for
education costs will be among the first legislative items lawmakers will take up
when they return later this month, House Speaker Dennis Hastert said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Hastert, R-Ill., said another early priority will be legislation he proposed
with President Clinton in November that would steer investments to America's
neediest communities. Congress reconvenes on Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We passed an ambitious tax relief package last year which the president
decided to veto,'' Hastert said after two days of House GOP leadership meetings
to discuss this year's agenda. ``This year we will continue to fight for tax
relief for working families.''
</P>
<P>
	   Provisions to address the education savings account and the extra tax burden
faced by some married couples who file jointly were both part of the $792
billion, 10-year tax package passed by Congress last year but vetoed by Clinton
as being excessively large.
</P>
<P>
	   Reducing the marriage penalty paid by millions of two-income couples would
have cost an estimated $119 billion, while raising tax-exempt contribution
limits to IRA-like education savings accounts and other steps to promote
education savings were estimated at $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The marriage penalty is the additional tax many two-income couples must pay
above what they would owe if they were single. To ease it, last year's GOP tax
bill would have gradually doubled the standard deduction, and increased the
amount of income subject to the lowest, 15 percent tax bracket for couples
filing jointly.
</P>
<P>
	   That tax bill also would have raised to $2,000 the current $500-a-year limit
on families' contributions to education savings accounts. The money can be
withdrawn tax-free and used for public and private elementary and secondary
schools and colleges.
</P>
<P>
	   The GOP outline of its goals for the election-year session came a day after
Clinton and Democratic leaders met at the White House and said they would push
legislation to shore up Social Security and to fix the nation's crumbling
schools.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democrats also said they would also seek to pass legislation unfinished
from last year, including gun restrictions, an increase in the minimum wage and
a patient's bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Hastert said House Republicans also were working to formulate a plan to
retire the nation's debt in the near future. He said that in the past three
years, as perennial budget deficits have changed into surpluses, the government
has paid off more than $300 billion in public debt.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore, who is campaigning for the Democratic presidential
nomination, has said that one of his goals is to retire the national debt, now
at $5 trillion, by 2015.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1415 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Successor To Be Named by Feb.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- International Monetary Fund chief Michel Camdessus plans
to step down as scheduled in mid-February and a successor is expected to be
named by then, a top IMF official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Frenchman has said he would leave by Feb. 16 after heading the
182-nation lending institution for a record 13 years.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is no reason to believe he is changing his plans," said Camdessus'
deputy, Stanley Fischer, an American.
</P>
<P>
	   "We haven't discussed what would happen if a successor hasn't been named,"
Fischer said when reporters asked if he would serve as interim managing director
while the search continues. "I notice that as deadlines get closer, they usually
promote action so I expect a successor will have been named by the time he
leaves."
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and finance ministers from the
other industrialized nations are expected to discuss a new IMF leader when they
meet this month in Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   Under an informal agreement made when the IMF and its sister institution,
the World Bank, were set up after World War II, the top IMF job goes to a
European while an American heads the bank.
</P>
<P>
	   Germany has been pushing the name of its deputy finance minister, Caio
Koch-Weser, a Brazilian born, 26-year veteran of the World Bank, but so far his
candidacy has drawn a lukewarm response in other European countries and the
United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1420 </TRAILER>
