<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Exceed Expectations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Even with all the hype about the Internet during the
holiday season, shoppers still piled into the nation's big retail chains and
spent more money than storeowners had expected.
</P>
<P>
	   Many bricks-and-mortar merchants reported Thursday that sales in December
were the strongest for the month since 1992 and they made it through Christmas
virtually unscathed by competition from their Web-only rivals.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was a great holiday season, and the Internet didn't take away many sales
from anybody," said Michael Niemira of Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd., which saw
its retail sales index of about 80 U.S. chains rise 6.6 percent in December,
above estimates of a 5.5 percent to 6 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
	   The last year has been very strong for the nation's merchants. With low
unemployment and big gains on Wall Street, Americans have been comfortable about
their financial well-being and eager to shop.
</P>
<P>
	   The buying binge clearly didn't stall out over Christmas. Consumers began
their holiday buying over Thanksgiving weekend, and kept the shopping spree
going well into the new year. In fact, the last week of December was one of the
strongest of the month.
</P>
<P>
	   Many chains said that sales were so good that they didn't have to slash
prices drastically to clear out inventory, as has been the case in some past
years. That will likely mean higher profits for those stores that sold more
goods at full price.
</P>
<P>
	   With the robust sales figures in hand, Wall Street analysts raised their
fourth-quarter earnings estimates for many retailers, including Wal-Mart,
Federated Department Stores and Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
	   "The markdowns this time around were much less than we saw a year ago.
That's great news for earnings," said Kurt Barnard, who runs the consulting firm
Barnard's Retail Trend Report in Upper Montclair, N.J.
</P>
<P>
	   The strong season for traditional retailers came even with the intense buzz
surrounding the Internet. Web merchants spent heavily on advertising that touted
the convenience of online shopping compared with the crowds at the mall during
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
	   But most Americans still choose to shop at bricks-and-mortar stores. A new
survey of about 500 people by Andersen Consulting found that 98 percent bought
at least some of their gifts at retail chains this Christmas.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, many merchants found great success of their own on the Internet
during the holidays. Some of fastest-growing Web sites -- including Gap.com, and
JCPenney.com -- were linked to physical stores.
</P>
<P>
	   "The traditional retailers are just starting to make their move on the
Internet, but still many people came to them because of their brand names,"
Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
	   The big winners last month were the discount chains, including Wal-Mart and
Target. Not only did shoppers buy toys, electronics and Christmas decorations at
their stores, but they also stocked up on water, flashlights and batteries in
preparation of any problems that could have come with Y2K.
</P>
<P>
	   It was also a big season for jewelry stores, including Tiffany and Zale
which had indulgent consumers snapping up expensive rings and earrings.
Electronics chains, such as Best Buy and Circuit City, saw brisk sales on DVD
players, digital cameras and other gadgets.
</P>
<P>
	   Stores specializing in clothing were hurt by warmer-than-normal weather at
the start of December, but most -- such as the Gap and Limited -- managed to win
back shoppers once temperatures turned cooler at mid-month.
</P>
<P>
	   While the season overall was strong, there were some weak spots.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pokemon craze couldn't help two of the nation's biggest toy stores. Toys
R Us reported disappointing sales, due in part to the fact that it ran out of
some popular electronic toys and video games. Consolidated Stores' K-B Toys
chain also struggled with weak sales.
</P>
<P>
	   Moderately priced department store chain J.C. Penney faced another tough
month, with its sales just rising slightly. Women's clothing chain Ann Taylor
also only had a tiny gain last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1429 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
