<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Group To Honor 3 Companies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- A New York-based women's advocacy group said Thursday that
three American companies will be honored for programs that advance women --
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., IBM Corp. and Northern Trust Co.
</P>
<P>
	   Catalyst said in a statement that its annual awards will be presented to the
firms in a ceremony March 21 at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., the principal operating subsidiary of The Charles
Schwab Corp. based in San Francisco, is being honored for a quarter of a century
of efforts to hire and promote women, Catalyst said. It said that at Schwab,
women make up 36 percent of corporate officers.
</P>
<P>
	   The group cited IBM for its global women leaders development task force. It
said women now make up 20 percent of IBM's North American executives, up from 14
percent in 1995. IBM is based in Armonk, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
	   Northern Trust Co., the flagship of Northern Trust Corp. of Chicago,
specializes in banking, investment and trust services. Catalyst said its
"diversity at work" program has resulted in women representing 49 percent of the
company's officers, up from 39 percent a decade ago. It said that nearly a
quarter of the women were from minority groups.
</P>
<P>
	   Catalyst has presented the awards since 1987. The nonprofit research group
also produces several surveys a year on women executives and advises businesses
on women's issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
