<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday, Jan. 6, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   Sales of New Homes Fall 7.1 Pct.
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sales of new homes fell 7.1 percent in
November, the biggest decline in two years, responding to higher
mortgage rates. The drop in single-family sales followed a big 9
percent October increase. Even with the setback, the Commerce
Department reported today, homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 865,000 units in November. Economists had been
predicting a slowdown since June, when the Federal Reserve started
pushing interest rates higher in an effort to dampen such
interest-sensitive sectors of the economy as housing.
</P>
<P>
	   Jobless Claims Jump by 33,000
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for
unemployment benefits rose by 33,000 last week, the largest
increase in a year, the government reported today. The Labor
Department said the number of new applications for jobless benefits
climbed to 309,000 for the week ending Saturday, the first time
this figure has been above the 300,000-level in 13 weeks. Jobless
claims had fallen by 7,000 in the previous week. But Labor
Department analysts stressed that the claims level is often
volatile during holiday periods and they cautioned against reading
too much into one week's movement in jobless claims.
</P>
<P>
	   Retail Sales Exceed Expectations
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Even with all the hype about the Internet during
the holiday season, shoppers still piled into the nation's big
retail chains and spent more money than storeowners had expected.
Many brick-and-mortar merchants reported Thursday that sales in
December were the strongest for the month since 1992 and they made
it through Christmas virtually unscathed by competition from their
Web-only rivals. ``It was a great holiday season, and the Internet
didn't take away many sales from anybody,'' said Michael Niemira of
Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd., which saw its retail sales index of
about 80 U.S. chains rise 6.6 percent in December, above estimates
of a 5.5 percent to 6 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
	   Dow Up 165.98; Nasdaq Down 101.73
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with technology shares
remaining weak while blue chips advanced on the strength of
old-fashioned cyclical companies that rise with a growing economy.
Just before 3 p.m. EST, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
165.98 at 11,288.63. Broader stock indicators were mixed. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was higher and the Nasdaq composite
index was down 101.73 at 3,775.81. Technology stocks continued to
tumble as investors sold stocks to lock in profits from last year's
record-breaking rise.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EST
Dow Industrials:        11288.63 + 165.98
