</P>
<P>
	   Europe Stocks Close Mostly Lower
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Telecommunication companies once again led the
slide in European stocks today. Most exchanges closed lower for the
fourth consecutive day, although investors recovered confidence
after early gains d Wall Street. As Thursday unfolded, European
investors sold off telecom stocks while buying chemical stocks and
shares in food and beverage companies. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of
606 shares in European companies fell 1.53 points or 0.4 percent to
352.21. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index fell 2.53 points to close at
383.12. London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 1.4 percent to 6,447.2.
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index fell 0.4 percent to 6,474.92, The Paris
CAC-40 Index was down 0.5 percent to 5,450.11, with
STMicroelectronics the biggest loser.
</P>
<P>
	   Microsoft To Offer 'Pocket PC'
</P>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- In an attempt to revive its sagging share of the
handheld computing market, Microsoft will redesign and rebrand its
Windows CE handheld devices in hopes of staging a comeback against
market leader Palm Computing. In a speech at the 2000 International
Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas, Microsoft chairman Bill
Gates said yesterday a new series of handheld devices called
``Pocket PCs'' will debut in late spring. The biggest difference
between the Pocket PC and its predecessors is that the new devices
will be more oriented toward storing and using different kinds of
media, from electronic books with easy-to-read type to video and
audio clips in Windows Media and the popular MP3 digital formats.
</P>
<P>
	   Microsoft, Barnes &AMP; Noble Make Deal
</P>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. and Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. plan to
develop and market electronic books using Microsoft's new
``ClearType'' technology. Barnes &AMP; Noble's bookstores, along with
the barnesandnoble.com Web site, will begin offering e-books
starting in the middle of this year, according to Barnes &AMP; Noble
vice chairman Steve Riggio. By that time, Redmond, Wash.-based
Microsoft will have included its Microsoft Reader software, under
development for more than a year, in most of its operating systems,
including systems that run WebTV and a new series of palm-size
computing devices due out in the next several months. Dick Brass,
Microsoft vice president of technology development, discussed the
plan today at the 2000 International Consumer Electronics Show in
Las Vegas. New York-based Barnes &AMP; Noble will market the Microsoft
Reader e-books aggressively, both in stores and online.
</P>
<P>
	   Head of Lotus Development Resigns
</P>
<P>
	   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Jeffrey Papows, the embattled head of
the software maker Lotus Development Corp., quit today following a
year in which he was sued for sex discrimination and accused of
lying on his resume about his education and military record. A
spokesman would not say why Papows was leaving the company, which
is owned by IBM. The resignation takes effect Feb. 1. He will be
succeeded by Al Zollar, who spent his 23-year career at IBM.
</P>
<P>
	   Goodyear Cuts Jobs in England
</P>
<P>
	   AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co. plans to eliminate
650 jobs at its Birmingham, England, plant as it ends Dunlop truck
tire production there and shifts some work to other plants.
Goodyear took control of Dunlop tire operations in North America
and Europe in September as a result of an alliance with Japan's
Sumitomo Rubber Industries Ltd.
</P>
<P>
	   Kellogg Hires Ford Exec As CFO
</P>
<P>
	   BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) -- Kellogg Corp. has hired Thomas J.
Webb, a Ford Motor Co. financial specialist, as its chief financial
officer. Webb becomes executive vice president of the cereal maker,
which has suffered flat cereal sales and a sliding market share. He
was chief financial information officer of Ford, where he worked
for 22 years. Kellogg's chief financial officer John R. Hinton and
four other top executives resigned in March. Long the biggest U.S.
cereal maker, Kellogg fell behind Minnesota-based General Mills in
the four-week period ended Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
	   Pennzoil Closing Refinery
</P>
<P>
	   ROUSEVILLE, Pa. (AP) -- Pennzoil-Quaker State Co. plans to close
its refinery and packaging plant in northwestern Pennsylvania that
employs about 300 people and is trying to sell its refinery in
Shreveport, La. The company said today it would charge $293 million
against after-tax earnings because of closing the plant in
Rouseville and for a writedown in the value of the Shreveport
refinery. The Rouseville refinery processes Penn Grade Crude oil
and ships it to other oil companies. The nearby packaging plant
prepares Pennzoil and Wolf's Head oils for market.
</P>
<P>
	   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
