<HEADLINE> Dow Up 174.98; Nasdaq Down 111.69  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with technology shares remaining
weak while blue chips advanced on the strength of old-fashioned cyclical
companies that rise with a growing economy.
</P>
<P>
	   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 174.98 at 11,297.63. About 45 points of the gain came
from 3M, the maker of Post-It notes and Scotch tape, which soared 9 1/8 to 102
3/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up
4.96 at 1,407.07, and the Nasdaq composite index was down 111.69 at 3,765.85.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks continued to tumble as investors sold stocks to lock in
profits from last year's record-breaking rise. Yahoo! dropped 33 9/16 at 376
15/16, and Qualcomm fell 13 3/16 at 143 1/4.
</P>
<P>
	   A three-day selloff in technology stocks, which has been exacerbated by
investors' desire to sell now and pay their capital-gains taxes in 2001, may
soon ebb, said Larry Rice, chief investment officer at Josephthal &AMP; Co. in New
York.
</P>
<P>
	   "These stocks will bounce back," he said. "There are too many people who are
still eager to buy. And these companies still hold great potential for making a
lot of money."
</P>
<P>
	   Still, fears of slowing profits for two high-tech firms depressed the sector
today. Personal computer maker Gateway warned late Wednesday its fourth-quarter
earnings would miss expectations due to a slowdown in sales. The company blamed
Year 2000 computer worries and component supply problems.
</P>
<P>
	   Gateway, which fell steeply in extended-hours trading Wednesday, bounced
back today and was up 4 9/16 to 59 9/16. But traders said the company's warning
contributed to weakness in other computer makers' share prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Dell dropped 11/16 to 47 13/16, and Apple fell 4 1/2 to 98 3/4.
</P>
<P>
	   Intel fell 1 7/8 to 80 1/8. Gateway blamed the semiconductor maker for some
of its supply problems.
</P>
<P>
	   MCI WorldCom was down 4 3/16 at 47 1/8 after influential Salomon Smith
Barney analyst Jack Grubman lowered his earnings and revenue estimates for
fiscal year 2000. Grubman said the company's revenue is likely to grow 14.4
percent from 1999 to 2000, below his previous estimate of 15.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader market has been rattled this week by growing concerns that the
Federal Reserve will soon raise interest rates in an effort to stave off
inflation. The Fed raised rates three times in 1999, and is expected to resume
its course of action as early as Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
	   As inflation fears have escalated, investors have shifted some money from
technology stocks to cyclical stocks, which depend upon economic growth.
Caterpillar rose 2 5/8 to 51 3/4 and Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose 3 1/8 to 92 7/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors are now awaiting Friday's monthly unemployment report from the
Labor Department, which contains data on wages and the number of jobs created.
Any sign of modest or slowing growth could prompt some new buying, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, the government said its weekly tally of new claims for unemployment
benefits rose by 33,000 last week, the largest increase in a year. Jobless
claims had fallen by 7,000 in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Labor Department analysts stressed that the claims level is often
volatile during holiday periods and they cautioned against reading too much into
one week's movement in jobless claims.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 867.00 million shares, slightly ahead of
Wednesday's late pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index fell 1.98 to 476.85.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
