<HEADLINE> Universal Press Chief Stepping Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- The co-founder of Universal Press Syndicate, the
comic-strip distributor that stuck with "Doonesbury" until it became a part of
the country's pop culture, is giving up his day-to-day duties of the company.
</P>
<P>
	   John McMeel, 63, will remain as chairman and president of Andrews McMeel
Universal, the parent company of Universal Press.
</P>
<P>
	   Bob Duffy, who has been with University Press for 24 years, will become
president. Lee Salem, who has edited "Doonesbury" and helped the strips "Calvin
and Hobbes" and "Cathy" get their start, will become executive vice president
and editor.
</P>
<P>
	   Universal Press distributes various strips, including "Garfield," along with
columnists such as Abigail Van Buren, William F. Buckley and Roger Ebert.
</P>
<P>
	   "A wise man once said, 'Change is the way that things progress,' " said
McMeel, who will step down on Universal Press' 30th anniversary on Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
	   McMeel and Jim Andrews were the founders of the company.
</P>
<P>
	   Kathleen Andrews, Jim Andrews' widow, will continue as vice chairman of
Andrews McMeel Universal, a business that offers products on the Internet and
sells greeting cards, gift items and humor books.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
