<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazi Victims, Austria Banks Settle  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal judge approved a $40 million settlement Thursday
between an estimated 1,000 Holocaust victims or their heirs and two Austrian
banks accused of confiscating their assets.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Shirley Wohl Kram said that the settlement is fair and
adequate and that the alternative is years of litigation so drawn-out that many
of the victims would be dead before they saw any payout.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is an historic event" said Gerhard Randa, chairman and chief executive
of Bank Austria. He said it marks "the first time that any of the
Holocaust-related claims cases has reached a concluded settlement."
</P>
<P>
	   "We sincerely hope that the victims of the Nazi regime who are the
beneficiaries of this settlement may find a measure of solace in this tangible
acknowledgment of moral responsibility for the terrible events they suffered
more than a half century ago," Randa added.
</P>
<P>
	   It will at least several months before any payments go out. The two sides
have to wait to see whether the judge's approval is challenged on appeal, and
they also have to evaluate each of the victims' claims.
</P>
<P>
	   The amount each of the victims will get depends on how much was lost and how
well they can prove their case.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawyers estimate there are about 1,000 valid claims from victims or their
heirs.
</P>
<P>
	   The corporate predecessors of the two banks, Bank Austria and Creditanstalt,
were accused of confiscating Holocaust victims' assets and refusing to turn them
over to those who survived the war.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge noted that the claims are based on acts that occurred more than 50
years ago in wartime Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   "Many of the records were either lost or destroyed during or after the war,"
the judge wrote. "Litigating this case without these documents and records would
undoubtedly add to the complexity of this already difficult case."
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the survivors and heirs are old and would not receive any money
before their death if not for a settlement, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
	   Others eligible to share in the settlement include those whose assets were
looted elsewhere by the Nazis and transferred to those banks and those whose
money transfers to concentration camp inmates through the banks were diverted.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, the judge said: "Those persecuted by the Nazis were the
victims of unspeakable acts of inhumanity. It is unlikely that any sum of money,
no matter how large, could ever be thought of as righting the wrongs committed
during the Holocaust."
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement, the banks said they "unreservedly accept moral
responsibility" for the activities of the banks or their predecessors during the
Holocaust. They said they "express their profound regret" for their actions and
are committed to opening their archives to provide a greater understanding of
the period.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, notice of the settlement has been mailed directly to 27,883 current
or former Austrian citizens in 68 countries determined to be victims of Nazi
persecution. Also, notice of the deal was published in newspapers in countries
with large populations of World War II survivors, and information was also
posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   Only 72 people have requested exclusion from the settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1605 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0190 </DOCNO>
