<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks With N. Korea To Resume  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Talks between U.S. and North Korean officials will resume
in Berlin this month, the Clinton administration announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   A previous round of talks adjourned last November 19.
</P>
<P>
	   The State Department, in a statement, said that a U.S. delegation led by
U.S. envoy Charles Kartman would meet with a North Korean delegation headed by
Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye Gwan.
</P>
<P>
	   On the agenda are preparations for a visit to the United States by a
high-level North Korean official, said the announcement by State Department
spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
	   The discussions have dealt with ways to improve relations and with North
Korea's missile program.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration has said that North Korea's agreement in September not to
test a long-range ballistic missile was expected to lead to a visit by a senior
Pyongyang official.
</P>
<P>
	   However, a senior North Korean diplomat earlier this week cast uncertainty
on such a visit.
</P>
<P>
	   Chu Chang Jun, North Korea's ambassador to China, told a news conference in
Beijing that North Korea had been prepared to send senior officials to the
United States until Washington committed ``acts of betrayal against our
country.''
</P>
<P>
	   He did not elaborate, and U.S. officials proceeded with plans for the next
round of talks in Berlin -- and for visit to the United States by a high-level
official from the communist regime.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We look forward to hosting a high-level visit at the earliest
opportunity,'' another State Department spokesman, James Foley, said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
	   He said it was up to North Korea to designate which official would come.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will continue to work on preparations for such a visit when our
bilateral talks resume'' in Berlin, Foley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Separately, White House National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said the
administration puts a high priority on the talks because it remains concerned
about North Korea's missile program.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want to pursue that very actively,'' he said in an address to the
National Press Club. ``North Korea has a choice. It can either pursue more
normal relations ... or it can continue with its threatening nuclear and missile
programs and continue to be isolated and continue to be contained by the rest of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're prepared to go down either path,'' Berger said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1605 </TRAILER>
