<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Killers Sought in Namibia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY JOHN GROBLER Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
	   WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) -- Namibian security forces have crossed into
neighboring Angola in their efforts to capture the suspected killers of two
French girls and their brother, state radio said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   France, meanwhile, has decided to conduct its own inquiry into the ambush of
the Bidoin family, which occurred Monday evening as they drove through a
conflict zone.
</P>
<P>
	   Uniformed gunmen are accused of executing the three Bidoin siblings after
the attack that left their parents wounded. Autopsies were conducted Thursday on
the bodies of Aurelie, 15, Cecile, 10, and their 18-year-old brother Michael.
The results were not immediately released.
</P>
<P>
	   The assailants' tracks led from the remote Caprivi Strip, where the attack
occurred, into Angola, the Namibian Broadcasting Corp. said.
</P>
<P>
	   The assailants reportedly wore uniforms, but it was unclear to which armed
group they belong.
</P>
<P>
	   French officials said they have received full cooperation from Namibian
authorities, but decided to conduct their own investigation into the deaths.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is serious concern back in France because it was three children who
were killed,'' said the French Embassy's charge d'affairs, Didier Ortolland.
</P>
<P>
	   The parents, Claude and Brigitte Bidoin, were recovering in the hospital in
Windhoek, he said. Both are teachers on the French island territory of Mayotte
off the southeast African coast and had been in Namibia on holiday.
</P>
<P>
	   They were to be evacuated to a hospital in France as soon as Claude Bidoin,
who was shot in the chest, is stable enough to travel, Ortolland said.
</P>
<P>
	   Namibia has blamed rebels of the National Union for the Total Liberation of
Angola, known as UNITA under its Portuguese acronym, for the assault.
</P>
<P>
	   The Angolan army, with Namibia's cooperation, last month launched an assault
on UNITA in the border region.
</P>
<P>
	   UNITA, which has blamed the attack on undisciplined Angolan troops, has
denied involvement in what it called a ``heinous crime.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We don't know exactly who these criminals are because in this region there
are different groups of armies of different origins,'' a French government
spokesman, Francois Rivasseau, told reporters in Paris.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We can only condemn this awful action very vigorously.''
</P>
<P>
	   Namibian state radio said seven UNITA soldiers were killed in a skirmish
with Namibian forces, and four captured near Susuwe, a Caprivi town which lies
close to the point where Zambia, Angola and Namibia meet.
</P>
<P>
	   Eight Angolan soldiers have been admitted to a hospital in the Namibian
border town of Rundu with wounds suffered in gunbattles and land mine explosions
near Jamba, in southeastern Angola, state radio reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The report quoted an unidentified Angolan soldier as saying that Jamba,
UNITA's stronghold in the region, had not fallen, contrary to Angola's previous
claim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1608 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Adviser Discusses Putin  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Acting President Vladimir Putin's first major test will be
whether he can protect Russia's young democratic processes in the heat of his
own presidential campaign, President Clinton's national security adviser said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If he does that, if Russia passes power from its first democratically
elected president to its second democratically elected president, I think that
will be a good thing,'' Sandy Berger told a National Press Club audience.
``We'll have to watch very carefully over the next three months.''
</P>
<P>
	   Berger, touching on a range of foreign policy issues, said the next three
months would be a crucial time in Russian history.
</P>
<P>
	   Any backsliding to a more authoritarian rule ``could present us with a
threat, which means we have a stake in Russia's success'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite sharp differences with the West over the government's military
offensive in Chechyna, Putin appears to enjoy strong support from the Russian
people and a newly elected Duma, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Acting President Putin has said he intends to uphold the rights of free
press, free speech, freedom of conscience, private property. And we obviously we
will be very interested to see him do this,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think the real test for acting President Putin will come in the next
three months when he will be both the custodian of Russian democracy and the
Russian Constitution at the same time he will be a candidate for president
within that system,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
	   Presidential elections are expected for March 26. Former President Boris
Yelstin handed power to Putin as he unexpectedly announced his own resignation
on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
	   Turning to other international issues, Berger said it was remarkable that
the world had made the transition to 2000 without a single terrorist attack.
But, he said, it wasn't by any stroke of luck -- but rather because of good
intelligence and law enforcement work.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Just because we dodged a bullet doesn't mean there was no bullet to
dodge,'' Berger said. ``Attacks were almost certainly prevented...We need to
keep meeting this challenge, just as we did last week.''
</P>
<P>
	   On other topics, the White House official:
</P>
<P>
	   --Said that, while both Israel and Syria were serious about making peace,
``one should not underestimate the degree of difficulty'' in reaching a peace
agreement in the talks now underway in West Virginia
</P>
<P>
	   --Denied a suggestion that the United States was relegating Iraq to a lower
status of concern. ``Iraq cannot be on the back burner as long as Saddam Hussein
in head of Iraq...One cannot diminish our effort on Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
	   --Expressed hope that Congress would act to grant China permanent
preferential trade status as well as enacting legislation to ease trade barriers
with sub-Saharan Africa and the Caribbean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
