<HEADLINE> Soybeans Fall on S. America News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- Forecasts for rain in bone-dry growing regions of South
America sent soybean prices lower Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade. Grains
were mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   Soybean futures, linked for months now to the weather in Brazil and
Argentina, rose early in the trading session to more than $4.80 a bushel. But
the higher prices failed to find support and were driven down on wet weather
forecasts for those top producing nations as well as a late drop in soymeal
prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Brazil developments also affected the corn market, with that country's
purchase of U.S. corn helping push the price upward slightly.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat prices followed soybeans lower, giving up early gains that were
attributed to technical factors and continued weak export demand.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery fell 1 1/4 cents to $2.48 1/2 a bushel; March corn
rose  3/4 cent to $2.03 3/4 a bushel; March oats fell  1/4 cent to $1.09 a
bushel; March soybeans fell 1 1/2 cents to $4.75 1/2 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Beef and pork futures advanced in trading on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   February live cattle rose 1.10 cent to 70.07 cents a pound; March feeder
cattle rose .67 cent to 86.37 cents a pound; February lean hogs rose .10 cent to
55.17 cents a pound; February pork bellies rose 1.18 cent to 82.30 cents a
pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
