<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Housing Raise Proposed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will propose in his 2001 budget that
within five years the government pay the full cost of housing for military
members who live off base, Defense Secretary William Cohen said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   As a first step, the 2001 budget will propose using $160 million to reduce
service members' out-of-pocket costs for off-base housing to an average 15
percent of the rent or mortgage from the current average of nearly 19 percent.
This will be done by raising what the Pentagon terms its ``basic housing
allowance'' -- a tax-free government stipend.
</P>
<P>
	   By 2005 all costs for off-base housing would be paid by the government, just
as is the case now for on-base housing. The Pentagon budget will earmark $3
billion over the next five years to cover these costs.
</P>
<P>
	   The initiative, which is likely to find favor in a Congress that often
pushes for quality-of-life improvements for the military, is part of a Clinton
administration campaign to make military life more attractive. The Pentagon in
recent years has had trouble recruiting new members and retaining those already
in uniform.
</P>
<P>
	   In announcing the housing plan to a group of Marines at Camp Pendleton,
Calif., on Thursday, Cohen reminded them that their base pay rose 4.8 percent on
Jan. 1, and that many will get additional increases of as much as 5.5 percent on
July 1. He said he also would seek ways to improve military health care.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the housing proposal as described by Cohen, an enlisted soldier in the
rank of Army specialist or Marine Corps corporal, for example, would see his or
her monthly housing cost drop by $35 in 2001 and by a cumulative $175 a month by
2005.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is real money going into your pockets,'' Cohen told the troops.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the active-duty military force of 1.4 million, about 750,000 receive
monthly allowances for off-base housing. Many choose to live off base because,
in the Defense Department's reckoning, about 200,000 of the 300,000 housing
units on its bases are substandard and in need of repair or replacement.
</P>
<P>
	   As more bases have closed in recent years, military members have
consolidated at a smaller number of locations -- in many cases finding
themselves in more expensive off-base real estate markets.
</P>
<P>
	   Increasing allowances for those who live off base is one of several aspects
of Cohen's plan to improve housing. The others are using military construction
funds to repair or replace some of the 200,000 military housing units judged to
be substandard, and using private contractors to build more on-base housing.
</P>
<P>
	   Late last year the Army signed a 50-year, $3 billion contract with Carson
Family Housing of Charlotte, N.C., to privatize family housing at Fort Carson,
Colo. The privatization approach is meant to achieve housing improvements more
quickly than through the traditional use of government construction funds.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The military simply cannot afford to build, own and maintain enough
quality housing to meet our needs,'' Cohen said in a statement released at the
Pentagon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1623 </TRAILER>
