<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia, Europe Stocks Continue Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned in a mixed performance today as investors,
still taking profits on technology issues, put their money into blue-chip
shares. Prices dropped sharply in earlier trading in Asia, and were off more
modestly in Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 130.61, or 1.42 percent, 11,253.26,
according to prelminary calculations, while the Nasdaq composite index, which
suffered its biggest-ever point drop on Tuesday amid concerns about rising U.S.
interest rates, was off 119.39 at 3,758.15, a loss of 2.88 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks continued to tumble as investors sold stocks to lock in
profits from last year's record-breaking rise, and that gave the Nasdaq a 7.46
percent drop so far in 2000. But blue chip stocks including the Dow industrials
rose as investors gravitated toward companies that do well during times of
higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
	   In Europe, key market gauges fell 1.36 percent in London, 0.54 percent in
Paris and 0.42 percent in Germany.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. and European trading was calm compared to Asia, where big declines have
brought back memories of the way prices plunged more than two years ago as the
financial crisis spread through the region.
</P>
<P>
	   The main market indicator in Hong Kong dropped 4.4 percent today and Tokyo's
main index lost 2 percent after bigger declines on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index slid sharply from the outset, at one point
coming close to matching Wednesday's ominous 7.2 percent dive that was its worst
one-day drop since late October 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   The Hang Seng finished with a loss of 693.49 points, or 4.4 percent, at
15,153.23.
</P>
<P>
	   On Asia's top market, the Tokyo Stock Exchange, its best-known index shed 2
percent as investors bailed out of high-tech companies that have taken a beating
globally.
</P>
<P>
	   A 5.6 percent drop in the Nasdaq on Tuesday sparked the selloffs, and
although the Nasdaq held its losses Wednesday to just 0.6 percent, traders
figured many high-tech companies were still too expensive.
</P>
<P>
	   Tokyo's Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed 374.28 points
lower at 18,168.27. The index had fallen 2.4 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korea's main market index fell 2.6 percent. Prices in Singapore,
Australia, Malaysia and Thailand gave up initial gains and turned lower. The key
market gauge fell 1.3 percent in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
	   The market in Indonesia rebounded, while prices rose marginally in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
	   Taiwanese blue chips continued to buck the trend, finishing with a gain of
0.8 percent today -- on top of a 1.1 percent gain that made the Taipei market
the region's only winner Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1642 </TRAILER>
