<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadorians Allowed in Volcano Zone  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Thousands of residents of an evacuated town near the
active Tungurahua volcano began returning to their homes Thursday under an
agreement that followed a deadly confrontation with soldiers.
</P>
<P>
	   About 3,000 residents came back to the town of Banos after the deal was
announced, and soldiers immediately started to pull out of the area.
</P>
<P>
	   The agreement signed Thursday by Ignacio Vargas, governor of surrounding
Tungurahua province, ordered the soldiers to withdraw from the area around the
volcano, and said residents could return at their own risk. It also called for
the creation of an emergency evacuation plan.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday night, a 30-year-old woman died in a confrontation between
hundreds of area residents and troops at a military checkpoint. Five soldiers
and two civilians suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
	   Residents of the tourist town on the volcano's slopes, about 75 miles
southeast of the capital, Quito, have accused soldiers of looting abandoned
buildings and say the ban on returning has brought them economic disaster.
</P>
<P>
	   For months, authorities have warned that the 16,553-foot volcano could erupt
within days or weeks, as it has done at least a dozen times since 1534.
</P>
<P>
	   The town's 17,000 people were evacuated in October, after the volcano awoke
from a 79-year slumber. About 8,000 people from nearby villages and scattered
hamlets also were ordered out of the area.
</P>
<P>
	   Last weekend, about 2,000 Banos residents reached the town by hiking
mountain trails, bypassing the military checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
	   Defying orders to leave, they opened grocery stores, bakeries and a pharmacy
in an attempt to return to normal life. They also dug ditches in the roads to
prevent military patrols from passing through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1643 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mudslide Victims Found in Caribbean  </HEADLINE>
   By FABIOLA SANCHEZ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Authorities have found dozens of victims of last
month's devastating mudslides floating in the Caribbean Sea near some of
Venezuela's top beaches.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the bodies were found during the last several days in Falcon state,
about 100 miles northwest of Caracas, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Forty-one bodies have been found in the area so far, said Melquiades Jordan,
Falcon's civil defense director.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dec. 15 mudslides wiped out entire neighborhoods on the slopes of a
mountain range that separates Caracas from the Caribbean Sea. Officials estimate
that between 5,000 and 30,000 people were killed, many of them washed out to
sea.
</P>
<P>
	   Uprooted trees, refrigerators, sofas, washing machines and other household
objects have also washed up on the beaches in Falcon state.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials temporarily shut down most beaches in the state, although those in
Morrocoy National Park -- coral reef-formed islands that are a top tourist
destination -- remained open.
</P>
<P>
	   Forensic experts were attempting to identify the bodies, but Jordan said the
work was difficult because many of the bodies were badly decomposed.
</P>
<P>
	   The mudslides left 150,000 people homeless. The government is building
subsidized houses for many of the survivors as part of a plan to move city
dwellers to the countryside.
</P>
<P>
	   President Hugo Chavez said late Wednesday the government might expropriate
idle farm land from owners who refuse to pay taxes and don't cooperate with the
relocation plans.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking in a televised interview, Chavez called on land owners to donate
idle land for the relocation efforts, adding ``if they don't want to, the state
could expropriate abandoned land.'' He said the owners would be paid for their
land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1644 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Rejoin Mideast Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- President Clinton plunged back into slow-moving
Mideast peace talks as face-to-face negotiations between Israelis and Syrians
ground to a halt.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. aim is a treaty that would exchange the Golan Heights, a strategic
border territory Israel has held for more than three decades, for diplomatic and
economic relations with Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   Syria began Wednesday to outline its offer in a mixed committee under the
supervision of Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk. A committee on new
border security measures met all day, as well.
</P>
<P>
	   But there were no face-to-face negotiations over Syria's key demand: a
specific timetable for Israel to relinquish the Golan Heights, which Syria lost
in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
	   The State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the talks, now in their
fourth day, were still ``chugging along.'' But he said the American hosts were
dissatisfied with the pace and would like to see it accelerated.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's intervention Thursday was his third of the week. On tap were
separate meetings with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa after conferring with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright on her own 90-minute meeting with al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
	   The president, wearing a leather flight jacket, waved to bystanders as he
alighted from his helicopter and made no statement.
</P>
<P>
	   In Washington, Clinton's assistant for national security, Sandy Berger, told
reporters to ``not underestimate the degree of difficulty'' in the negotiations
being held near this oldest town in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These are very difficult issues that divide the parties,'' Berger said.
``They've been at war three times since the 1940s. There are very strong views
on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
	   In contrast to discontent within the Syrian delegation, Barak and his
delegation appeared pleased that the negotiations were focused on peace terms
and security measures, such as installing an early-warning system at the border
and clearing it of troops.
</P>
<P>
	   Barak found time Wednesday to jog and do calisthenics at a gymnasium in the
hotel the two delegations are sharing behind police barricades.
</P>
<P>
	   An Israel source, insisting on anonymity, said the talks were likely to go
into a second week -- after a weekend break -- and that Barak planned to stay
on.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said that Albright, meanwhile, had directed her assistants to prepare
a ``working document'' detailing negotiations held in 1996 as well as talks last
month in Washington and here this week.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That will enable us at the appropriate time to move forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked if Israel could be secure without retaining the Golan Heights, which
overlooks its northeastern towns that were targets of cross-border attacks
before 1967, Rubin said, ``Israel is going to have to make that decision.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We believe that Israel has legitimate security needs and we believe those
needs can be met,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton has assured Israel and Syria he was willing to play a helpful and
consistent role in trying to iron out their differences.
</P>
<P>
	   Although two trips are on his schedule for next week -- to Arizona and Texas
on Monday and Tuesday and to New York on Thursday -- White House press secretary
Joe Lockhart said the peace talks would take precedence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1646 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
