<DOCNO> APW20000106.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert:Tax Relief Heads GOP Agenda  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans are drawing up plans to eliminate the
portion of the national debt held by the public, now estimated at $3.7 trillion,
House Speaker Dennis Hastert said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Hastert, R-Ill., also said after a GOP leadership conference that tax relief
for married couples and for parents saving for education costs will be among the
first legislative items lawmakers will take up when they return later this
month.
</P>
<P>
	   Hastert's office said it was the first time the speaker publicly committed
to eliminating the debt. With the recent emergence of budget surpluses, the
Clinton administration also is talking about abolishing the public debt by 2015.
Hastert said his plan, too, would envision an end to the debt in 10 years to 15
years.
</P>
<P>
	   The last time the debt was eliminated was 1835, when Andrew Jackson was
president. The national debt totals $5.76 trillion, which includes $3.7 trillion
owed the public in treasury bills and savings bonds and $2 trillion the
government owes Social Security and other trust funds. The national debt crossed
the $1 trillion mark in 1983.
</P>
<P>
	   Other GOP priorities announced at a news conference of party leaders include
blocking new Internet taxes, passing other high-tech bills and winning approval
for China's accession to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
	   Hastert said another early priority will be legislation he proposed with
President Clinton in November that would steer investments to America's neediest
communities. Congress reconvenes on Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We passed an ambitious tax relief package last year which the president
decided to veto,'' Hastert said after two days of House GOP leadership meetings
to discuss this year's agenda. ``This year we will continue to fight for tax
relief for working families.''
</P>
<P>
	   The early-session emphasis on targeted tax relief, a strategy also deployed
by Democrats, did not rule out another try at a comprehensive tax cut package,
Hastert said. ``We may consider a bigger bill at the end'' of the session, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The speaker also noted that presidential politics will come into play this
summer, and congressional Republicans would try to coordinate tax policy with
the GOP presidential nominee. The front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, has
proposed a five-year, $483 billion tax cut plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Provisions to address the education savings account and the extra tax burden
faced by some married couples who file jointly were both part of the $792
billion, 10-year tax package passed by Congress last year but vetoed by Clinton
as being excessively large.
</P>
<P>
	   Reducing the marriage penalty paid by millions of two-income couples would
have cost an estimated $119 billion, while raising tax-exempt contribution
limits to IRA-like education savings accounts and other steps to promote
education savings were estimated at $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The marriage penalty is the additional tax many two-income couples must pay
above what they would owe if they were single. To ease it, last year's GOP tax
bill would have gradually doubled the standard deduction, and increased the
amount of income subject to the lowest, 15 percent tax bracket for couples
filing jointly.
</P>
<P>
	   That tax bill also would have raised to $2,000 the current $500-a-year limit
on families' contributions to education savings accounts. The money which can
now be withdrawn tax-free and used for college expenses, would be usable for
public and private elementary and secondary school costs as well.
</P>
<P>
	   The GOP outline of its goals for the election-year session came a day after
Clinton and Democratic leaders met at the White House and said they would push
legislation to shore up Social Security and to fix the nation's crumbling
schools.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democrats also said they would also seek to pass legislation unfinished
from last year, including gun restrictions, an increase in the minimum wage and
a patient's bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Other tax goals named by the GOP leaders included stopping new taxes from
being imposed on Internet access and giving a tax break to people who adopt a
child with special needs.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., chairman of the House GOP Policy Committee,
said the party also will seek to pass a high-tech agenda, including electronic
signature legislation that stalled last year and a second measure setting
standards for computer encryption.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
