<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SKorea To Probe War Execution Claim  </HEADLINE>
   By SANG-HUN CHOE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The Defense Ministry said Thursday it will
investigate a newspaper report that South Korean police massacred thousands of
political prisoners early in the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
	   The national daily Hankook Ilbo said the prisoners were people accused of
collaborating with the communists and that they were executed in the first weeks
of the war to prevent their release by advancing North Korean troops. The paper
quoted declassified U.S. documents.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have started checking into available documents in our ministry,'' said
Yoon Il-young, spokesman for the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
	   The newspaper said the documents were uncovered by a Korean-American
scholar, Do-Young Lee, in U.S. government archives. Copies of the documents were
made available to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   One of the documents quotes the U.S. Embassy's Army attache at the time, Lt.
Col. Bob Edwards: ``Orders for execution undoubtedly came from top level as they
were not confined to towns in front line areas.''
</P>
<P>
	   In the report dated Sept. 23, 1950, Edwards said 1,800 political prisoners
were executed over three days in the first week of July 1950 in Taejon, 90 miles
south of Seoul.
</P>
<P>
	   Army photos uncovered at U.S. national archives also showed the execution of
political prisoners in Taegu, a provincial city in southeast South Korea, in
April 1951, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Korean Peninsula was divided into the communist North and U.S.-allied
South at the end of World War II. The North invaded the South in June 1950,
instigating a three-year war. The United States led allied U.N. forces to defend
the South against North Korean troops backed by China and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
	   In September, The Associated Press cited U.S. veterans, Korean witnesses and
declassified documents in reporting that U.S. warplanes and ground troops killed
hundreds of South Korean refugees at No Gun Ri, South Korea, in late July 1950,
as American soldiers retreated under fire from North Korean troops.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korea and the United States are investigating that case.
</P>
<P>
	   When the war started, President Syngman Rhee's government in South Korea
rounded up tens of thousands of people accused of being communist sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the prisoners were believed to have been killed by retreating South
Korean police who feared they would collaborate with North Korean troops,
according to historians.
</P>
<P>
	   The South Korean parliament opened an investigation after Rhee's government
was toppled in 1960 amid nationwide student uprisings.
</P>
<P>
	   But the investigation ended abruptly when military strongman Park Chung-hee
took power in a coup the following year.
</P>
<P>
	   Calls for reopening the investigation were ignored during the years of
military-backed governments that followed Rhee's ouster.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korea turned to democracy in the late 1980s, and its first civilian
president took power in 1993. Kim Dae-jung, the first opposition leader elected
president in South Korea, has made human rights issues a priority since assuming
office in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1657 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Businesses Granted New Tax Deduction  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Businesses will gain a new tax deduction for the costs of
meeting international quality standards under a ruling by the Internal Revenue
Service, which reversed its previous position.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision Thursday involves a series of quality guidelines -- known as
ISO 9000 -- that businesses around the world use for goods and services.
Companies get certified by the International Organization for Standardization by
documenting their processes so all current and future employees will continue to
meet the same standards.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Association of Manufacturers, the National Federation for
Independent Business and other organizations petitioned the IRS in 1998 to
permit companies to fully deduct the costs of gaining certification in a single
year, instead of spreading the costs out over multiple years.
</P>
<P>
	   Obtaining certification, the groups said in a joint letter, ``can be both
expensive and time consuming, particularly for small businesses.'' An average
cost estimate was placed at $60,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The IRS ruling says that costs incurred by businesses to ``obtain, maintain
and renew'' the certification will now be fully tax deductible in one year,
except for certain long-term costs such as creation of a company manual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
