<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technology Shares Fall Again  </HEADLINE>
    By BRUCE MEYERSON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks slid for a third straight session today,
pushing the Nasdaq market's rapid retreat from record highs as investors
scurried to protect last year's phenomenal gains.
</P>
<P>
	   The tech-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 150.34 points to close at
3,727.20 as Wednesday's partial recovery in the technology group quickly
unraveled.
</P>
<P>
	   The loss, which would have been the biggest ever if not for Tuesday's record
229-point drop, left Nasdaq about 400 points from the record high of 4,131.15
reached on Monday, the first session of the new year.
</P>
<P>
	   For most of today's session, the selling was modest compared to Tuesday and
early Wednesday. But the losses piled up over the final hour of trading, dashing
hopes that high-flying tech shares might soon resume a powerful rally that drove
the Nasdaq to a 50 percent gain over the past two months and 85 percent for all
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   The sheer size of 1999's gains may have been the driving force behind the
post New Year's drop, rather than the fears of rising interest rates, many
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   With such huge profits tucked away in stocks --especially technology and
Internet-related shares -- many investors were waiting to sell after Dec. 31 so
they could delay paying taxes on those gains until April 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   While most experts agree that there's plenty of excess that can be wrung
from technology stocks, they also stand by the main premise behind 1999's stock
swell -- that even though most Internet companies continue to lose money, all
companies will eventually prosper from the rapid spread of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   The main question Wednesday wasn't why, but how long and how far stocks
might drop before resuming the rally of the past five years.
</P>
<P>
	   The selloff didn't stop Goldman Sachs on Tuesday from issuing a list of
stocks the investment firm expects to rise at least 35 percent this year. More
than a third of the 85 names on that list were Internet-related, including
America Online, the leading Web service, and Cisco Systems, the biggest
manufacturer of Internet equipment.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Internet is the most important business phenomenon in our lifetime,"
said Byron Wien, the U.S. investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
"I still believe that, but many stock prices were suggesting a profit reality
that was pretty hard to achieve."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
