<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Home Sales Fall; Retail Sales Soar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sales of new homes, hurt by rising mortgage rates, took
their biggest tumble in two years, but the nation's retailers enjoyed their best
Christmas in seven years as confident consumers spent with abandon.
</P>
<P>
	   Economists said the latest batch of economic data released Thursday depicted
a U.S. economy that ended 1999 just as it had begun, galloping full speed ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial markets, which had swooned earlier this week on worries that all
the strength will push the Federal Reserve to move interest rates up further,
were mixed on Thursday. The Dow Jones industrial average gained 131 points
Thursday to close at 11,253, but the technology-laden Nasdaq index suffered
another big loss.
</P>
<P>
	   The Commerce Department reported that sales of new homes plunged by 7.1
percent in November, the biggest decline since December 1997. Rising mortgage
rates were blamed for the weakness with sales falling in all regions of the
country, led by a huge 31.5 percent plunge in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
	   But even with the dropoff in home sales, total activity remained close to
record levels at a seasonally adjusted annual sales pace of 865,000 units.
</P>
<P>
	   The nation's big department store chains reported Thursday that they enjoyed
their strongest December sales since 1992.
</P>
<P>
	   The nationwide chains reported heavy demand for everything from toys,
jewelry and DVD players to Y2K survival items such as flashlights and batteries.
Big winners included Wal-Mart and Target, two discount chains.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumer demand has been fueled by the lowest unemployment rate in 30 years
with many economists predicting the 4.1 percent current level could fall to 4
percent when the December figure is released on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Reserve, expressing concerns that a dwindling supply of
available workers would trigger inflationary wage demands, began in late June
pushing interest rates higher to slow the economy down.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said they still believe that last year's three Fed rate increases
would be followed by two to three more rate increases in 2000 as the central
bank struggles to contain an economy Fed policymakers still believe is growing
too rapidly for comfort.
</P>
<P>
	   While Fed efforts to dampen demand in interest-rate sensitive sectors such
as housing and autos would normally raise fears of a possible recession, few
economists see any threat that higher rates will derail the current expansion,
which next month will become the longest in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
	   Part of the reason for that optimism is a belief that the global economy,
which has come through a financial crisis that saw deep recessions in Asia and
elsewhere, is beginning to recover.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Asia recovery looks spectacular," Stanley Fischer, deputy managing
director of the International Monetary Fund, told reporters at a briefing
Thursday. He said not only crisis countries South Korea and Thailand were
rebounding but also Indonesia, where he said "the outlook is much brighter,
especially after democratic elections."
</P>
<P>
	   Economists predicted sales of both new and existing homes would dip further
in coming months as mortgage rates continue to rise. A national survey by
Freddie Mac, the mortgage company, reported Thursday that 30-year, fixed-rate
mortgages hit 8.15 percent this week, a level that has not been surpassed in
more than two years.
</P>
<P>
	   David Seiders, chief economist at the National Association of Home Builders,
said that the increase in mortgage rates, which started 1999 at 6.79 percent,
had added $100 a month to the cost of financing a $100,000 mortgage.
</P>
<P>
	   He predicted that new home sales would set a second consecutive record high
in 1999 of 908,000 sales but would decline to 840,000 in 2000, still a solid
year.
</P>
<P>
	   "That won't be bad news for most builders because many of them have been
having trouble finding enough construction workers to meet demand," Seiders
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Even with sales falling, new home prices kept rising with the average price
climbing to a record of $209,700 in November, up 4.2 percent from October. The
median, or midpoint, price rose 5.3 percent to $167,400.
</P>
<P>
	   Economists said the price increases were being exaggerated by a drop-off in
sales to low-income buyers because of the rising mortgage rates, while buyers of
more expensive homes remained in the market.
</P>
<P>
	   Home sales fell 31.5 percent in the Northeast to an annual rate of 50,000
units, the weakest showing since 1996. Sales fell in all regions, including
declines of 7.8 percent in the Midwest, 5.4 percent in the West and 3.1 percent
in the South.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
