<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Backs Ruling on Cuban Boy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Hundreds of Cuban-Americans chanting ``Liberty! Liberty!''
blocked intersections and cut off access to the Port of Miami on Thursday to
protest the U.S. government's decision to return 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to
his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   Police arrested more than 70 people, including two prominent Cuban exile
leaders, for refusing to disperse.
</P>
<P>
	   In Washington, Attorney General Janet Reno essentially ruled out any chance
she will reverse Wednesday's decision by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service to send the boy back to the communist island.
</P>
<P>
	   For the past six weeks, Elian has been the subject of protests in Florida
and Cuba -- and in the middle of an international debate over where he belongs.
Fidel Castro kept up the pressure with another government-orchestrated
demonstration Thursday in Havana.
</P>
<P>
	   The boy was found Thanksgiving Day clinging to an inner tube at sea after
his mother, stepfather and eight other people drowned while trying to reach
Florida by boat. He has been living in Miami with his paternal great-uncle and
great-aunt.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian, whose whereabouts were kept secret after Wednesday's decision,
arrived back at his relatives' home Thursday afternoon. His great-uncle hoisted
Elian on his shoulders and the boy smiled and waved to cheering supporters
outside the house.
</P>
<P>
	   His cousin Marisleysis Gonzalez said Elian had not been told of the decision
to send him back because it may not prove final. Lawyers for the boy's American
relatives asked Reno to reverse the decision and planned to request a
restraining order from a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
	   But Reno said she had consulted with INS Commissioner Doris Meissner and
agreed with the decision. ``Based on all the information we have to date, I see
no basis for reversing,'' Reno said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The INS has until Jan. 14 to send the boy back.
</P>
<P>
	   In Miami, several hundred protesters gathered outside a downtown federal
building, pushed back police barricades and marched several blocks to the Port
of Miami, where most of the arrests were made.
</P>
<P>
	   About 50 officers in riot gear guarded the port's entrance in the shadow of
Freedom Tower, a former customs building where many Cubans entered the United
States in the 1960s. About 780,000 Cuban-Americans live in Miami-Dade County,
accounting for 35 percent of its 2.1 million residents.
</P>
<P>
	   Demonstrators shouted ``Clinton! Coward! Miami hates you!'' They carried
posters in English and Spanish and waved U.S. and Cuban flags.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm defending my rights because where the rights of one person end, the
rights of another begin,'' said Meri Pino, 70, who refused to move from the port
entry.
</P>
<P>
	   Police arrested people who sat on the pavement and others who crossed police
lines. Those arrested included Cuban exile leaders Ramon Sanchez, head of the
Democracy Movement, and Jose Basulto, founder of Brothers to the Rescue, an
anti-Castro group.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're not going to let anyone get hurt,'' said police Lt. Bill Schwartz.
``We're not going to let the streets be taken over by a mob.''
</P>
<P>
	   The headquarters of Royal Caribbean International, a leading cruise line, is
on port property, and the demonstration kept employees from leaving for several
hours. No major cruise ships were in port Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere, small groups of protesters intermittently blocked intersections.
Gov. Jeb Bush lifted tolls on highways near protests to relieve rush-hour
congestion.
</P>
<P>
	   At least 10 people carrying a large Cuban flag sat down in the middle of a
main downtown street, crippling traffic during a downpour. Motorists honked
their horns in irritation or support.
</P>
<P>
	   During the morning rush-hour, two dump trucks and a pickup truck slowed all
three lanes of downtown-bound traffic to about 20 mph on the major east-west
route in Miami. The Florida Highway Patrol issued several citations and
threatened to arrest drivers slowing traffic.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm Haitian and they send all the Haitians back,'' motorist Fritz Rene,
31, said at one blocked intersection as he was trying to get to work. ``Whenever
anything happens to the Cubans, they go crazy.''
</P>
<P>
	   Marisleysis Gonzalez said she supported the demonstrators but asked them to
remain peaceful.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are a lot of Cubans here who have suffered and they are willing to
stop this because the laws here are not being fair,'' the boy's cousin said
outside her home. ``They haven't given us the opportunity to speak on behalf of
him.''
</P>
<P>
	   American officials had suggested that Elian's father come to Florida to get
his son. The U.S. National Council of Churches said the boy's relatives in Cuba
want the organization to bring the boy back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
