<HEADLINE> Ecuador Deploys Police Amid Protests  </HEADLINE>
   By CARLOS CISTERNAS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Police firing tear gas dispersed about 1,000
demonstrators marching on the presidential palace Thursday to demand President
Jamil Mahuad's resignation.
</P>
<P>
	   Similar protests over Mahuad and his handling of the economy were held in
Ecuador's largest city, Guayaquil, as well as the southern city of Cuenca.
Defying a countrywide state of emergency, the students tried to block traffic by
setting small fires in streets but were quickly driven away by police.
</P>
<P>
	   The state of emergency empowered the armed forces to maintain order and
contain demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
	   In Quito's center, heavily armed riot police, some in armored vehicles,
formed a cordon around the presidential palace. Protesters were dispersed about
six blocks from the site.
</P>
<P>
	   In several areas, large numbers of soldiers and police were patrolling
provincial highways and guarding gas stations, state buildings and streets in
the cities, radio reported. Businesses in major cities, however, were operating
normally.
</P>
<P>
	   The leftist-led Unified Workers Front, Ecuador's main labor federation with
600,000 workers, had announced the series of protests against Mahuad's
government, Congress and Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   The Harvard-educated Mahuad has faced three national strikes since taking
office in August 1998. His critics accuse him of incompetence in resolving
Ecuador's worst economic crisis since the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
	   Inflation topped 60 percent in 1999, the economy shrank 7 percent, and the
value of Ecuador's currency plunged 30 percent in one year, from 7,000 sucres to
the dollar to 23,000 sucres today.
</P>
<P>
	   Mahuad has said he plans to finish his term, which runs until January 2003.
The armed forces have expressed their support for him.
</P>
<P>
	   More marches were planned for later in the day Thursday, but so far turnout
has been lower than expected. Organizers said they were hoping for the same
massive response that in February 1997 helped oust former President Abdala
Bucaram. Congress kicked Bucaram out of office for ``mental incompetence'' after
at least two million people took to the streets in major cities throughout the
small Andean country of 12 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The Popular Front, a group of unions, student organizations and neighborhood
associations, joined the front in Thursday's protests.
</P>
<P>
	   Luis Villacis, president of the Popular Front, said protesters had started
blocking provincial highways. He appealed to Ecuadorians to take to the streets.
</P>
<P>
	   Government spokesman Vladimiro Alvarez said authorities were bracing for
violence and had information about where Molotov cocktails and bombs had been
prepared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
