<HEADLINE> Rector May End Mexico Univ. Strike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The head of Latin America's largest university got
approval Thursday for a plan to completely overhaul the institution's bylaws in
hopes of ending an eight-month student strike.
</P>
<P>
	   Rector Juan Ramon de la Fuente's proposal calls for the election of a
500-member University Congress made up of faculty, students, researchers and
workers, to revise the bylaws of the National Autonomous University of Mexico.
The election will be held within the next 45 days.
</P>
<P>
	   The 120-member University Council, made up of faculty representatives,
overwhelmingly approved the plan after almost five hours of deliberation.
</P>
<P>
	   The university, popularly known as UNAM, has been shut down since April,
locking out 268,000 students.
</P>
<P>
	   Strikers initially protested a plan to raise tuition from the equivalent of
a few cents to $140 annually. Though authorities dropped the fee hike, the
demands grew to include automatic admission for UNAM prep school graduates and
relaxation of academic levels.
</P>
<P>
	   Negotiations to end the strike have repeatedly deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
	   In November, de la Fuente replaced Francisco Barnes de Castro, the rector
who had backed the fee hike and had been unable to resolve the strike.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, 500 students staged a sit-in outside the building where de la
Fuente was meeting with faculty members. The students held signs saying they
rejected his latest proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
