<HEADLINE> Shellfish Warning Issued in France  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- France's food safety watchdog on Thursday recommended a ban on
the sale of shellfish and salt from coastlines most affected by oil spilled from
a sunken tanker.
</P>
<P>
	   The food safety agency, known as AFSSA, said that any shellfish harvested
after the oil spill and not immediately placed in purified water should not be
sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency also recommended a government ban on fishing from the shore in
the region, and said fish caught at sea should be tested before sale to make
sure they are not contaminated.
</P>
<P>
	   The Maltese-registered tanker, ``Erika'', broke up and sank on Dec. 12,
spilling 3 million gallons of heavy oil into the waters off the picturesque
Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
	   The tanker was chartered by Franco-Belgian oil group TotalFina to transport
oil from the Netherlands to Italy.
</P>
<P>
	   The oil has since begun to wash up on land. Specialists and volunteers are
still scraping the oil from 250 miles of coastline.
</P>
<P>
	   AFSSA also recommended Thursday that salt and seaweed from the ``visibly
affected'' coasts should not be sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency said it expected to produce a more detailed analysis of the risks
to food once it had an exact breakdown of the components contained in the leaked
oil.
</P>
<P>
	   Another worry for environmentalists is some 6 million gallons of oil still
contained in the holds of the broken vessel, most in the rear half of the
tanker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1733 </TRAILER>
