<P>
	   Accounting Firm Violations Found
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A review led by an independent consultant has
found thousands of violations by accounting giant
PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP -- and many of its partners -- of rules
requiring accountants to remain independent from companies they
audit. The Securities and Exchange Commission, which made the
consultant's review public today, said its investigation of New
York-based PricewaterhouseCoopers is continuing. A year ago, the
firm agreed in a settlement to conduct the review after the SEC
alleged that some of its accountants owned stock in corporations
they audited. Dave Nestor, a spokesman for PricewaterhouseCoopers,
said he had no comment on the report but provided a copy of a
letter sent by chairman Nicholas G. Moore and chief executive James
J. Schiro to the firm's partners. The letter termed the report
embarrassing. The executives added that that the violatons of the
independence rules mentioned in the report, while unacceptable,
``did not in any way impair the professional objectivity and
integrity'' of the company's audits.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales of New Homes Fall 7.1 Pct.
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Higher mortgage rates dampened sales of new
single-family homes in November, the Commerce Department said
today. They fell 7.1 percent, the biggest decline in two years. The
drop followed a 9 percent October increase. Even with the setback,
homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 865,000
units in November. Economists had been predicting a slowdown since
June, when the Federal Reserve started pushing interest rates
higher in an effort to dampen such interest-sensitive sectors of
the economy as housing.
</P>
<P>
	   Jobless Claims Jump by 33,000
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for
unemployment benefits rose by 33,000 last week, the largest
increase in a year, the government reported today. The Labor
Department said the number of new applications for jobless benefits
climbed to 309,000 for the week ending Saturday, the first time
this figure has been above the 300,000-level in 13 weeks. Jobless
claims had fallen by 7,000 in the previous week. But Labor
Department analysts stressed that the claims level is often
volatile during holiday periods and they cautioned against reading
too much into one week's movement in jobless claims.
</P>
<P>
	   Retail Sales Exceed Expectations
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Even with all the hype about the Internet during
the holiday season, shoppers still piled into the nation's big
retail chains and spent more money than storeowners had expected.
Many brick-and-mortar merchants reported today that sales in
December were the strongest for the month since 1992 and they made
it through Christmas virtually unscathed by e-commerce competition.
</P>
