<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Destroyers Will Use New Technology  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Navy said Thursday its next-generation destroyer will
be the first class of ships powered by an all-electric propulsion system so
efficient that each ship would need a crew of 95 instead of the 300 on today's
destroyers.
</P>
<P>
	   Navy Secretary Richard Danzig, at a news conference, said the Pentagon
budget to be submitted to Congress in early February will propose spending about
$250 million in the next six years to develop the ``electric drive'' technology
to be used on the DD-21 ships.
</P>
<P>
	   Eventually other classes of surface ships -- and perhaps submarines, too --
would be built with the electric drive, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Navy plans to build 32 DD-21 destroyers at a cost of $25 billion. The
first is expected to enter the fleet in about 10 years. Two contractor teams --
one led by Bath Ironworks and Lockheed-Martin and the other by Ingalls
Shipbuilding and Raytheon Corp. -- are competing for the contract to build the
new destroyers.
</P>
<P>
	   The surface ships in today's Navy -- aside from nuclear-powered aircraft
carriers -- are powered by gas turbine or diesel engines that are attached to
reduction gears. Those gears reduce the speed of rotation of the drive shaft so
that it turns the ship's propeller at the appropriate speeds.
</P>
<P>
	   In the DD-21, the same gas turbine or diesel engines will be used. But the
reduction gears, which take up a tremendous amount of space and are difficult to
maintain, will be gone. In their place will be smaller, more efficient and
quieter electrical generators attached to electric motors. The motors will
control the speed of the propeller independent of the engines, and there will be
no need for a long drive shaft.
</P>
<P>
	   The result is a propulsion system that takes up much less space on board,
requires fewer people to operate and maintain, and is quieter. The ships also
will have more electric power available for on-board weapons and will be less
vulnerable to attack because the quieter engines will make them stealthier,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``From a warfighter's perspective this is a very important development,''
said Rear Adm. Michael Mullen, director of the Navy's surface warfare division.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1736 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census Seeks Head Count Workers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Uncle Sam wants you!
</P>
<P>
	   The Census Bureau launched an effort Thursday to hire a half-million
part-time workers to conduct the national head count.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our goal is to have a pool of local people who are familiar with their
communities and committed to a successful count in their own neighborhoods,''
Census Director Kenneth Prewitt said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
	   His agency has 520 offices open across the country with each needing to hire
800 to 1,000 people for four to six weeks around census day, April 1. He said
the agency will spend $9.5 million on help-wanted advertising.
</P>
<P>
	   Overall, the census is on schedule, Prewitt said, with 150,000 people hired
so far and a pool of about 1 million applicants. He said the agency wants an
overall pool of about 3 million to choose from.
</P>
<P>
	   Those hired so far include about 6,000 welfare-to-work applicants, he said.
And Congress is considering special exemptions so Social Security and public
assistance recipients can take Census jobs without losing benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   Legal residents aged 18 and older are eligible to work for the Census
Bureau. They do not need to be citizens, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In many areas the agency is seeking bilingual workers. Pay varies from $8.25
to $18.50 per hour.
</P>
<P>
	   Prewitt urged anyone interested in a Census job to call the agency's
toll-free number, 1-888-325-7733.
</P>
<P>
	   Prewitt said other aspects of the effort are also on schedule, including:
</P>
<P>
	   --The first local counts will get underway in two weeks in rural parts of
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
	   --Printing is ahead of schedule with all 123 million long forms finished and
the work about 75 percent complete on the short forms.
</P>
<P>
	   --The agency has verified 20 million rural addresses, adding 10,000 new
ones, and is now sending the 100 million city addresses to local governments for
verification.
</P>
<P>
	   --Advertising campaigns are beginning and will increase leading up to census
day, in an effort to improve on the 65 percent of households that returned forms
by mail in 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   --The agency has obtained 4.5 million square feet of office space, 17,000
telephones, 100,000 pieces of furniture and thousands of pieces of office
equipment.
</P>
<P>
	   Prewitt said about two-thirds of the workers hired so far are women, many
seeking a second part-time job. And he noted that the majority of people who
worked for the agency in dress rehearsals are coming back for the final count.
</P>
<P>
	   Overall there are about 860,000 jobs to be filled, but not all at the same
time, so Prewitt said the agency expects many people will do more than one of
them.
</P>
<P>
	   The effort to count the estimated 274 million people in the United States is
a decade-long effort, Prewitt stressed, noting that planning for the 2010 count
is already underway.
</P>
<P>
	   He warned that ``the conditions that make it difficult to count this country
completely have magnified since 1990,'' including the presence of more
immigrants, a larger non-English speaking population, a more mobile population,
more total households and more irregular living arrangements.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We believe we can do a basic enumeration better than we did in 1990,'' he
said, but that does not necessarily mean a more accurate census.
</P>
<P>
	   Prewitt said he expects there will still be an undercount, in particular
among minorities, and the agency will need to do a post-census quality check to
measure that undercount and correct it in the overall totals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
