<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Platinum at 6-Week Low; Cocoa Falls  </HEADLINE>
    By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Platinum prices plummeted to a six-week low Thursday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in a continuing selloff by investors bracing for Russia to
resume its massive exports of the metal.
</P>
<P>
	   In other futures markets, cocoa fell as a result of military tensions in the
Ivory Coast, and corn rose.
</P>
<P>
	   After declining along with other precious metals at the start of the new
year when Y2K fears fizzled, platinum's plunge steepened Tuesday on news that
acting Russian President Vladimir Putin had signed quotas for the export of
platinum this year.
</P>
<P>
	   That resumption would return the world's No. 2 producer of platinum to the
market; its yearlong absence shrank world supplies and drove prices to a
two-year high three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest selloff by funds sent the price for the March contract down
another $7.90 to $394 an ounce Thursday after dipping as low as $388.10. The
closing price is some 10 percent lower than the peak of $435 reached on Dec. 14.
</P>
<P>
	   "The bottom line is that Russia's one step closer to making platinum
exports," said Dave Meger, a senior metals analyst for Alaron Trading Corp. in
Chicago. "But it's one thing for them to say something and entirely another for
them to do it.
</P>
<P>
	   "Right now the market's extremely oversold," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   March cocoa futures shot up $10 to $841 a ton on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP;
Cocoa Exchange on word of fresh tension in Ivory Coast, the world's top cocoa
producer. Reports said army troops were agitated after the formation of a new
government on Wednesday, with shots fired at a barracks and soldiers stationed
outside the state radio station to quell any disturbances.
</P>
<P>
	   Also buoying prices was a report from the Netherlands Cocoa Association, the
world's biggest cocoa processor, that it ground nearly 3 percent fewer beans in
1999. That signals a decline in world demand for chocolate.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn prices went in the opposite direction of other grains and soybeans,
which declined on the Chicago Board of Trade, after Brazil bought 80,000 tons of
corn from the United States instead of neighboring Argentina, its primary
supplier. Traders also cited rumors that Brazil may buy a total of 250,000 tons.
Both Brazil and Argentina have been affected by drought.
</P>
<P>
	   March corn settled up  3/4 cent to $2.03 3/4 a bushel after rising as high
as $2.05 3/4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
