<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Web Auction Co. Settles Complaint  </HEADLINE>
   By TED BRIDIS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An online auction company agreed to settle charges by the
Federal Trade Commission that it sent deceptive e-mail to customers of its
Internet auction rival, eBay, federal regulators said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ReverseAuction.Com was accused of sending unsolicited e-mail warning eBay
customers that their online identities ``will expire soon'' and encouraging them
to visit its own Web site.
</P>
<P>
	   ReverseAuction, which said it now has 35,000 customers, called the FTC's
action ``unprecedented.'' It said that it disagreed with the charges but that it
signed the consent order ``to complete a pending round of financing (and) put
this matter behind it.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``No reasonable person who read our e-mail could have been misled,'' said
Ron Johnston, ReverseAuction's chief executive officer. ``No one could have been
deceived or harmed by our e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
	   In the e-mail, the company said: ``As long as you visit us now and claim
your ID, no one else can get it! Then when you decide to trade on our site, you
will be able to use your carefully built reputation.''
</P>
<P>
	   The FTC's complaint, accepted 5-0 by the commissioners, alleged that
ReverseAuction committed deceptive or unfair acts in violation of federal law
because the company allegedly told customers its actions were authorized by
eBay.
</P>
<P>
	   But the complaint, filed Thursday in federal court, includes a copy of the
e-mails sent by ReverseAuction, which said explicitly: ``eBay is a registered
trademark owned by eBay Inc., which does not authorize or endorse
ReverseAuction.com).''
</P>
<P>
	   The settlement prohibits ReverseAuction from making misrepresentations and
to warn customers who registered with the company as a result of those e-mails
that it knew their eBay identities were not expiring and that it was not acting
on behalf of its competitor.
</P>
<P>
	   Two commissioners, Orson Swindle and Thomas B. Leary, agreed that
ReverseAuction's e-mails were deceptive but disagreed they were unfair. The two
said the actions did not meet the legal standard of causing or likely to cause
``substantial injury to consumers that is not reasonably avoidable by consumers
themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
