<HEADLINE> Dollar Continues Rise Against Yen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar continued to rise against the yen Thursday, but
Japanese financial authorities remain concerned that their currency is too high.
The pound rose on signs of economic strength in England.
</P>
<P>
	   In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 105.40 Japanese yen, up
from 104.35 yen. The dollar has been rising back against the yen since the Bank
of Japan stepped into currency markets earlier this week to sell yen for
dollars.
</P>
<P>
	   But officials in Tokyo still say they feel their currency is overvalued and
poses a threat to an economic recovery. The high yen hurts Japanese exporting
companies like Sony and Toyota by shrinking the value of earnings they bring
back to Japan from overseas.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan's vice finance minister, Haruhiko Kuroda, told reporters Thursday in
Tokyo that the yen was still too strong. "In terms of fundamentals, it is still
clearly excessive," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Dollar-euro trading was quiet. The euro was quoted at $1.0315 in late New
York trading, unchanged from its level late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The British pound rose to $1.6480 from $1.6418 after a report showed a
strong increase in retail sales in Britain last month, the latest sign leading
analysts to expect a rate increase from the Bank of England next week.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar also was quoted at 1.5555 Swiss francs, just above 1.5554 late
Wednesday, and 1.4589 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4485.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. Since the euro was
even with its previous rate against the dollar, the dollar also remained flat
against currencies participating in the euro.
</P>
<P>
	   Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8958 German marks;
6.3586 French francs; and 1,877.07 Italian lire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
