<HEADLINE> Figure in Kohl Case Wants Money Back  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- A businessman whose cash handover to aides of Helmut Kohl has
embroiled the German ex-chancellor in a political scandal now wants the money
back, a newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Karlheinz Schreiber said the $550,000 he turned over in 1991 at a Swiss
shopping mall wound up with ``individuals'' -- apparently Kohl's aides -- but
never reached the coffers of the conservative party Kohl then led.
</P>
<P>
	   Schreiber, who is fighting extradition from Canada on German charges of tax
evasion, intends to have his German lawyers take legal steps to get the money
back, the Handelsblatt business daily quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
	   The 65-year-old Schreiber, who holds dual German-Canadian citizenship, is
being sought in his native Germany for allegedly failing to pay more than $14
million in taxes on commissions he received for business deals. He denies the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
	   Revelations late last year about the Swiss transaction touched off
investigations into the campaign financing of Germany's Christian Democrats, the
party Kohl chaired for 25 years until his 1998 election defeat.
</P>
<P>
	   It's unclear where the cash came from, but Kohl has since admitted
soliciting up to $1 million in covert campaign funds in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors opened a criminal probe against Kohl this week, and parliament
is investigating whether payoffs influenced decisions during his 16-year
administration -- something Kohl adamantly denies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
