<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazi Suspect Leaves Britain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Rather than face a third deportation, an 86-year-old man
accused of Nazi war crimes fled Britain on Thursday, as Latvia began
investigating allegations of atrocities linked to him during World War II.
</P>
<P>
	   Konrad Kalejs, who had been in London for six months, left rather than
contest the British government's move to deport him. At Heathrow airport, he
boarded a Singapore Airlines flight bound for Singapore, and it was believed he
intended to go on to Melbourne, Australia, the Air News agency reported.
</P>
<P>
	   After his departure, the Latvian Embassy in London announced it had launched
the criminal investigation, and called for international help in gathering
evidence.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If in the result of the investigation, the Latvian general prosecutor's
office will gather enough evidence confirming the guilt of Mr. Kalejs, then
after the court's decision, Latvia will consider requesting the extradition of
Mr. Kalejs,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kalejs, who has held an Australian passport since 1957, was previously
deported from the United States and Canada because of allegations linking him to
a unit that took part in the murder of more than 30,000 people, primarily Jews,
in Latvia.
</P>
<P>
	   Kalejs has denied the allegations, and described his accusers as ``liars and
storytellers.''
</P>
<P>
	   Britain's decision to initiate deportation proceedings rather than detain
Kalejs outraged Jewish activists, but Home Secretary Jack Straw said there was
not enough evidence for a criminal prosecution in Britain.
</P>
<P>
	   The Australian government has said it cannot block Kalejs' return.
</P>
<P>
	   Australian Justice Minister Amanda Vanstone said a special body set up in
Australia to investigate Nazi war crimes had reported in 1992 that there was not
enough evidence to prosecute Kalejs.
</P>
<P>
	   More recently, Australian federal police agents thoroughly reviewed
information on Kalejs, Vanstone said. She did not say if the review included new
information or just the existing file.
</P>
<P>
	   But lawyer Robert Greenwood, who headed the now disbanded War Crimes Special
Investigation Unit, said Kalejs had never been investigated fully by Australian
officials.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We knew a lot about Mr. Kalejs, but we never targeted Mr. Kalejs as a
prime suspect in the real sense with a view to bringing a prosecution,''
Greenwood told the British Broadcasting Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   Vanstone said the Special Investigation Unit's report to Parliament in 1992
said ``all known witnesses'' had been interviewed in relation to Kalejs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1810 </TRAILER>
