<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise on Tech Stock Slump  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose Thursday, as investors moved money out of
slumping technology stocks and into less risky investments.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year bond rose 13/16 points, or $8.13 per $1,000 in face
value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell to 6.55 percent
from a two-year high of 6.62 percent reached late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors continued their onslaught on technology stocks Thursday, driving
the tech-heavy Nasdaq composite index down 150.41 points. The Nasdaq has fallen
nearly 10 percent since closing at an all-time high on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, government-secured bonds and old-guard stocks benefited from the
flight from technology. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 130.61 to
11,253.26.
</P>
<P>
	   Bond prices have fallen in recent weeks amid concerns that the Federal
Reserve plans to raise interest rates again early this year now that fears of a
Year 2000 computer disaster have dissipated.
</P>
<P>
	   Rising interest rates hurt bonds, which pay a fixed rate of return. The Fed
raised rates three times in 1999 -- in June, August and November -- to slow the
red-hot economy and to keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.39 percent as the discount fell
0.03 percentage point from Wednesday's 5.27 percent. Six-month yields were 5.67
percent, as the discount fell 0.05 percentage point from Tuesday to 5.43
percent. One-year yields were 6.00 percent as the discount fell 0.02 percentage
point from Wednesday to 5.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities fell 1/16
point to 3/32 point and intermediate maturities fell 9/32 to 7/16 point,
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was
5.50 percent, up from 5.38 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer said the new contract for its index
of 40 actively traded municipal bonds rose 1/16 to 91 23/32. The average yield
to maturity was unchanged at 6.27 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
