<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Change Urged for Canada Broadcaster  </HEADLINE>
    By TOM COHEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- A government regulatory commission on Thursday renewed the
license of the Canadian Broadcasting Corp. for seven more years, but demanded
programming changes that will strain the national broadcaster's budget.
</P>
<P>
	   The Canadian Radio-Television and Telecommunications Commission said the CBC
-- as the national broadcaster -- must "reflect all the communities of the
country" and demanded more regional arts programming, including drama, dance,
documentaries and entertainment magazine programs, during prime time.
</P>
<P>
	   Noting professional sports consume about 25 percent of prime time
programming, the commission said the network must reduce coverage of pro sports
over the next seven years while boosting amateur sports programming.
</P>
<P>
	   The announcement drew an immediate protest from CBC president Robert
Rabinovitch, who said the changes would cost $34 million a year.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is no way the CBC can implement these decisions," said Rabinovitch,
who assumed his position two months ago. "The money just isn't there."
</P>
<P>
	   Francoise Bertrand, the commission chairwoman, acknowledged the changes
would reduce advertising revenue but said it was up to the CBC to make ends
meet.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission suggested the CBC should avoid major innovations to its
programming "in a time of budgetary constraints" by devoting "all available
resources to its existing services in order to reach the most listeners and
viewers possible."
</P>
<P>
	   Considered the major force in linking Canada's diverse communities, the CBC
faces the new demands after a decade of declining budgets and reduced services.
At the same time, competition from private networks and foreign broadcasters
through satellite and cable transmissions has increased.
</P>
<P>
	   In recent years, the amount of government funding for the CBC has dropped by
25 percent to $515 million a year, with the full-time work force shrinking by
more than 20 percent to just over 7,000. The federal government contributes
about two-thirds of the CBC's budget, with ad revenue accounting for most of the
rest.
</P>
<P>
	   To handle previous budget cuts, the CBC reduced its foreign news bureaus and
decreased domestic news programs, including the halt of regional weekend news
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
	   But the commission said Thursday the regional weekend news programs must be
resumed. It said its demands for more regional programming during prime time,
increased news coverage and reduced professional sports broadcasts were intended
to "give an even greater voice to all our citizens."
</P>
<P>
	   Vince Carlin, a former BBC senior manager who now is chairman of the School
of Journalism at Ryerson Polytechnic University, called many of the commission's
demands useless.
</P>
<P>
	   "It seems like the exercise of power without the responsibility for any of
the effects of it," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1824 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guyana Says AT&AMP;T Service Cut  </HEADLINE>
    By BERT WILKINSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) -- Guyana's monopoly phone company said Thursday
that it no longer has long-distance international service via U.S.
telecommunications giant AT&AMP;T because of a dispute over access fees.
</P>
<P>
	   "We knew this might have happened, but we are very unhappy with the way they
did it, by just putting up a continuous busy signal," said Guyana Telephone and
Telegraph Co. spokesman Lennox Cornette.
</P>
<P>
	   Guyana insists that AT&AMP;T cut off service. But AT&AMP;T said in a statement
Thursday that the Guyana company had begun blocking service Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
	   AT&AMP;T rivals Sprint and MCI have continued their international services to
Guyana, the local company said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Guyanese company, owned by Atlantic Tele Network in the U.S. Virgin
Islands, said it refused to accept a reduction in the fee that AT&AMP;T pays for
each call put through on the Guyanese network.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Communications Commission ruled in August 1997 that access rates
should be reduced over several years to more accurately reflect the true costs
of service. In Guyana, the rate is to be cut from 85 U.S. cents per minute per
call to 23 cents, the local company said.
</P>
<P>
	   AT&AMP;T, which is based in New York, said in a written statement Thursday that
it hopes to resolve the dispute and resume service in Guyana.
</P>
<P>
	   "The current accounting rate we have with Guyana Telephone and Telegraph has
remained unchanged for the past 13 years and doesn't reflect today's call
termination costs," AT&AMP;T said.
</P>
<P>
	   The FCC contends that American consumers pay more than they should for
international calls because foreign telephone companies, many of them
monopolies, charge U.S. phone companies an average of 70 percent above cost for
completing calls.
</P>
<P>
	   Caribbean leaders have asked President Clinton to reconsider the fee
changes, estimating that rate cuts could cost them $250 million a year. Some
leaders said that local phone rates could soar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1825 </TRAILER>
