<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Storm Cleanup Kills French Soldiers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NONTRON, France (AP) -- Two French soldiers who were helping restore
storm-damaged electricity services in France were killed in a freak accident
Thursday, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said.
</P>
<P>
	   The men were asphyxiated by the heating system in the house where they were
staying while they helped state electricity company EDF with its repair work,
Jospin said.
</P>
<P>
	   The prime minister, who was in the southwestern region of Dordogne to see
the damage caused by the gales, did not give any other details of the deaths.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In a way, they paid with their lives for their commitment to their fellow
citizens,'' Jospin said.
</P>
<P>
	   The tragedy brings to 90 the number of deaths related to the devastating
storms that ripped through France on Dec. 26 and Dec. 27, smashing buildings,
tearing up trees and snaring power cables. Six thousand soldiers were deployed
around the country to help with the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite a massive repair operation, 170,000 homes across France are still
without electricity and thousands have no phone lines.
</P>
<P>
	   EDF chairman Francois Roussely said Wednesday the storms caused so much
damage it could take three years to fully restore the national electricity
system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 1837 </TRAILER>
