<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded heavily Thursday
on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares plunged in extended-hours trading Wednesday after the personal
computer maker said fourth-quarter earnings would miss expectations. But today,
Salomon Smith Barney and Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown defended the company, saying
the shortfall is a one-time lapse and the stock remains a good investment.
</P>
<P>
	   Sony denied reports that its president had expressed displeasure at a recent
spike in Sony's share price by saying it was approaching a "bubble" level.
Shares tumbled nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said same-store sales rose 5 percent in the five-week period
ended Jan. 1, exceeding estimates. Total sales for the period rose 27 percent.
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette and Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown raised their ratings
on the stock.
</P>
<P>
	   Ann Taylor was among the weakest performers as major retailers released
their December results. The company said same-store sales rose 0.9 percent from
last December. Analysts had expected a gain of as much as 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The casino operator said Wednesday its fourth-quarter earnings will fall
below year-ago results because of slow business over the New Year's Eve weekend.
Company executives blamed Year-2000 worries.
</P>
<P>
	   Cobalt, which provides Internet marketing for auto dealers, plans to offer a
Web site where auto dealers can buy and sell cars and parts to one another.
Cobalt said the Motorplace.com site should launch by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
	   Tollgrade, which makes remote testing equipment for telephone lines, expects
to report fourth-quarter earnings of about 75 cents a share. Analysts had
anticipated earnings of 38 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said same-store sales for December fell 3 percent. Urban
Outfitters, a retailer of trendy clothing and household items, said total sales
for December rose 20 percent from December 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
