<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Deploys Police Amid Protests  </HEADLINE>
   By CARLOS CISTERNAS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Police firing tear gas dispersed about 1,000
demonstrators marching on the presidential palace Thursday to demand President
Jamil Mahuad's resignation, claiming he has mismanaged Ecuador's economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Similar protests over Mahuad were held in Ecuador's largest city, Guayaquil,
as well as the southern city of Cuenca. Defying a countrywide state of
emergency, students tried to block traffic by setting small fires in streets,
but were quickly driven away by police.
</P>
<P>
	   The state of emergency gave the armed forces the power to maintain order and
contain demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
	   In central Quito's center, heavily armed riot police, some in armored
vehicles, formed a cordon around the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
	   Another attempt by 300 protesters, mainly high school students, to reach the
palace later Thursday also was turned back by police firing tear gas.
</P>
<P>
	   Protest leaders said at least 10 people were hurt in Thursday's clashes with
the police, and more than 20 were detained. Authorities said they had no
information on how many were hurt or arrested.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Red Cross said at least two people had been injured, including a
17-year-old male student who suffered a bullet wound in the neck. It was unclear
who fired the shot, it said.
</P>
<P>
	   In several areas throughout the country, soldiers and police were patrolling
provincial highways and guarding gas stations, state buildings and city streets,
radio reported. Businesses in major cities, though, were operating normally.
</P>
<P>
	   The leftist-led Unified Workers Front, Ecuador's main labor federation with
600,000 workers, organized the protests against Mahuad's government, Congress
and Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   The Harvard-educated Mahuad has faced three national strikes since taking
office in August 1998. His critics accuse him of incompetence in resolving
Ecuador's worst economic crisis since the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1999, inflation topped 60 percent, the economy shrank 7 percent, and the
value of Ecuador's currency plunged 30 percent, from 7,000 sucres to the dollar
last year to 23,000 sucres today.
</P>
<P>
	   Mahuad has said he plans to finish his term, which runs until January 2003.
And the armed forces have expressed their support for him.
</P>
<P>
	   Protest organizers appeared disappointed Thursday with the overall turnout,
which was lower than expected. They said they were hoping for the same massive
response that in February 1997 helped oust former President Abdala Bucaram.
Congress kicked Bucaram out of office for ``mental incompetence'' after at least
two million people took to the streets in major cities throughout the small
Andean country of 12 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Government spokesman Vladimiro Alvarez said authorities were bracing for
violence and had information about where Molotov cocktails and bombs had been
prepared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
