<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Probe: Korea Air Instruments Failed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A Korean Air cockpit crew was warned of the failure of a vital
navigational instrument moments before a fatal crash near London, an interim
accident report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The attitude director indicator, which provides the angle of the aircraft at
night and in clouds, malfunctioned during a previous flight and was inspected by
a Korean Air ground engineer just before the cargo plane took off Dec. 22,
according to the report by the Air Accidents Investigation Branch.
</P>
<P>
	   Minutes afterward, the crew received warnings that the indicator was not
working, the report said. The recovered ``black box'' flight data recorder
showed that a buzzer sounded repeatedly in the cockpit, indicating the
instrument was showing conflicting readings, it said.
</P>
<P>
	   When the Boeing 747 reached 2,000 feet, it banked to the left and descended
almost vertically. The plane turned into a fireball on impact near Stansted
Airport, killing all four people on board.
</P>
<P>
	   No copy of the technical log was left at Stansted, and the engineer was one
of the four men killed in the crash.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There was no record of what the ground engineer entered in the technical
log to clear the fault and no way of knowing if he briefed the oncoming
commander about the fault,'' the Air Accidents Investigation Branch said.
</P>
<P>
	   The report came to no conclusions about the cause of the crash, and noted
the investigation was continuing.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, an official from the Air Accidents Investigation Branch confirmed
that the plane had been carrying several hundred pounds of depleted uranium,
which had a low level of radioactivity.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our information is that it remained intact after the crash, and that there
is no hazard to those working at the site or people living nearby,'' a spokesman
said, speaking with customary anonymity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
