<HEADLINE> Swedish Leader Mulls Nazi Probe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Succumbing to pressure from politicians and a
Jewish group, the prime minister said he would consider appointing a panel to
investigate Sweden's ties with Nazi Germany, a news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Swedish parliamentary leaders and the Nazi-hunting Simon Wiesenthal Center
have called on the government to re-examine its World War II relationship with
Germany after a documentary about Swedes who fought for Hitler.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There could be a commission, research project or some other method to find
out exactly what the Swedish Nazis did,'' Persson was quoted as saying in a
Wednesday night interview with Swedish Television.
</P>
<P>
	   Sweden was neutral during the war and traded goods with both sides.
</P>
<P>
	   The Simon Wiesenthal Center, which had also demanded that Swedes who
committed crimes while fighting in German armies be brought to trial, welcomed
Persson's comments while repeating its insistence that war criminals face court
proceedings
</P>
<P>
	   ``Allow me to congratulate you on your wise and courageous decision to call
for an investigation of the Nazi war criminals currently living in Sweden,'' the
center's Israeli director, Dr. Efraim Zuroff, said in a statement. ``The need to
bring those responsible for them to justice remains as strong as ever.''
</P>
<P>
	   The documentary called ``The Swedes who fought for Hitler'', which was
televised earlier this week, showed Swedes who had volunteered for Adolf
Hitler's army and participated in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
	   Sweden has made a concerted effort to raise public awareness of the
Holocaust after a 1997 survey showed that nearly a third of youths between ages
12 through 18 did not believe the genocide of Jews, Gypsies and other minorities
took place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
