<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   High pressure brought generally clear conditions to the West on Thursday,
while snow and gusty winds blew across the upper Midwest.
</P>
<P>
	   The snow showers spread from the Dakotas to Wisconsin and northern Michigan.
Wind gusts were clocked at more than 30 mph in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
	   A weak cold front associated with this system stretched south into the
Plains where most locations reported clear and dry conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   High pressure centered over the mid-Atlantic brought mostly clear skies and
dry conditions to the Southeast and lower Ohio Valley. A few clouds gathered
over sections of Florida and areas along the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
	   High pressure also dominated the Rockies, bringing clear but windy
conditions to most of the West.
</P>
<P>
	   Santa Ana winds roared through Southern California, tearing off a roof,
overturning big-rigs and turning desert areas into traffic-snarled dust bowls.
</P>
<P>
	   No major injuries were reported as winds gusting to 60 mph swept through the
area. The winds eased by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
	   A system moving into the Northwest created cloudy skies from Washington to
northern California, with isolated showers in far western Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   Extremes across the Lower 48 on Wednesday ranged from a high of 80 degrees
in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., to a low of minus 14 degrees in Stanley, Idaho.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
