<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Candidates Debate in N.H.  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DURHAM, N.H. (AP) -- An aggressive George W. Bush pledged in campaign debate
Thursday night to push for ``tax cuts, so help me God'' if elected to the White
House and accused presidential rival John McCain of seeking campaign finance
changes that would hurt the conservative cause.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, his insurgent candidacy at a crossroads in the first-in-the-nation
primary state, used the forum to strongly defend his actions on behalf of a
political donor who was seeking action from the Federal Communications
Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   The tax cut pledge uttered by Bush, the national GOP front-runner, was
all-but-unequivocal: ``If there's a recession it's important to cut taxes to
make sure the economy grows. ... It's also important to cut the taxes where
there's times of plenty. ... It's important to cut the taxes to make sure
Washington, D.C., does not spend the surplus.''
</P>
<P>
	   His questioner asked whether he was saying ``no new taxes, so help me God''
-- a reference to former President George Bush's no-new-taxes pledge that he
broke once he won the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not only no new taxes. This is tax cuts, so help me God,'' said
Bush, son of the former president.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, McCain and the other GOP contenders, Steve Forbes, Alan Keyes, Gary
Bauer and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, met on a stage at the University New
Hampshire -- the site of a debate one night earlier of the Democratic
presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
	   The series of debates continues Friday night in South Carolina, where the
GOP contenders will meet once again, and again next week as the opening round of
primaries approaches.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain swiftly parried Bush's attack on the issue of campaign finance and
possible damage to the Republican Party, noting that his proposal includes steps
to limit union political activity.
</P>
<P>
	   And he was unequivocal in defending a letter he wrote to the FCC on behalf
of a political donor. ``My job is to make the bureaucrats work for the people,''
said McCain, who is chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee. ``I would do the
same thing again, almost anytime.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain smiled broadly as he issued his defense -- keeping a widely rumored
temper in check -- although his aides fretted that the issue of the letter could
seriously damage a candidacy based on a pledge of rooting out the influence of
special interests.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, for one, declined to prod McCain on the issue. ``I thought his answer
was fine,'' he said when moderator Tim Russert asked for his opinion.
</P>
<P>
	   The political subtext explained the course of the debate. Bush's tax cut
pledge was designed to strike a chord in a state where residents are fiercely
proud there is no income tax.
</P>
<P>
	   And his criticism of McCain on campaign finance -- his jab that it would
hurt Republicans -- was designed to peel away GOP voters from his closest rival.
</P>
<P>
	   Similarly, McCain's chances for victory in New Hampshire rest with
independents, and his defense of his actions before the FCC seemed an effort to
assure those voters who are attracted to his image as a reformer who will end
politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
	   The 60-minute debate was feisty, and none of the men on stage hesitated to
interrupt.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm going to take some time here,'' Hatch declared at one point, more than
halfway through a confrontation in which he struggled for airtime.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauer underscored his signature issue, saying he would not appoint any
justice to the Supreme Court ``who would sacrifice even one child,'' a pledge he
has uttered often in his effort to show unbreakable opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes, a wealthy publisher, sharply criticized the Clinton administration's
decision to send a Cuban boy whose mother died escaping Havana back to his
homeland to be reunited with his father. The child is ``Bill Clinton's human
sacrifice to Fidel Castro,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   There was an incendiary exchange over gays in the military that followed the
pledges Wednesday night by both of the Democratic presidential hopefuls that
they would make sure that homosexuals could serve openly.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauer said that Democratic stance would further the ``radical homosexual
agenda,'' and an animated Keyes said, ``I will return to the ban on homosexuals
in the military.''
</P>
<P>
	   Said Bush, ``I'm a don't ask, don't tell man.''
</P>
<P>
	   But the main political dynamic of the evening was the struggle between Bush
and McCain, close rivals in the polls in New Hampshire, which holds the first
primary of the year on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   The two argued over taxes and campaign finance and snapped at each other a
time or two.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said Bush's tax plan would use the entire surplus.
</P>
<P>
	   ``No it doesn't,'' retorted the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Yes it does,'' shot back McCain, standing a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush was asked at one point whether his personal religious beliefs would
affect his White House policies. Russert asked whether he would take the popular
Christian expression `What would Jesus do' into the Oval Office, and Bush
replied, ``I would take an expression into the Oval Office: 'Dear God Help
Me.'''
</P>
<P>
	   To which Bauer said, ``So would we.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
