<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Lower in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was higher against the yen early Friday in Tokyo,
largely maintaining its strength gained overseas. Japanese stock prices opened
lower.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 105.22 yen, up 0.84 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo but
below its late New York level of 105.40 yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 26.25 points, or 0.14
percent, to 18,142.02 in the first 30 minutes of trading. On Thursday, the
average closed down 374.28 points, or 2.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the dollar held on to much of its strength in early
Asian trading Friday after hitting a seven-week high against the yen in overseas
markets.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. currency's strength on Thursday came from cross-trading among
European and Asian currencies, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts say the yen's decline was exacerbated as hedge fund managers
shifted some of their currency holdings from yen to euros and investors
continued to cover dollar-yen and euro-yen short, or oversold, positions.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the yen's weakness, Japan's vice finance minister for international
affairs, Haruhiko Kuroda, said Friday that the currency is still overvalued.
</P>
<P>
	   "The yen is still too strong," Kuroda said. "I think the correction to the
excessively strong yen has started," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The high yen hurts Japanese exporting companies by reducing the value of
dollar earnings they bring back to Japan from overseas.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 108.53 yen, up from 107.88 yen
late Thursday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, prices started lower as selling of Japanese technology
stocks continued early Friday following a decline in the Nasdaq Composite Index
on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 130.61 points, or 1.2
percent, to 11,253.26 at Thursday's close. But the Nasdaq, dominated by
technology stocks, fell 150.31, or 3.9 percent, to 3,727.23.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 21.92 points, or 1.36 percent, to 1,587.67. The TOPIX closed
down 42.25 points, or 2.56 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond was unquoted in
early trading. On Thursday, it settled at 1.6800 percent and its price stood at
101.87.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 2033 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
