<DOCNO> APW20000106.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Doesn't Regret FCC Letter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Sen. John McCain said Thursday he had no regrets
about writing a federal agency on behalf of a political supporter, even as his
chief presidential rival sought advantage in the controversy and aides scrambled
to minimize damage.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Senator McCain must answer these questions,'' George W. Bush told
reporters asking about McCain's actions. The Texas governor and Republican
presidential front-runner used the incident to cast McCain as a Washington
insider.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain defended his actions Thursday night as he joined Bush and four other
Republican presidential candidates in Durham for their first debate of the new
year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My job, as chairman of the Commerce Committee, as every other major
committee chairman in Washington, is to make the bureaucrats work for the
people,'' McCain said. ``And that has to do with making decisions. I would do
the same thing again, at almost any time.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said that he and other members of Congress have had problems with the
Federal Communications Commission and that, ``I will continue to exercise my
oversight and try to get them to do their job.''
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier, as the questioning consumed another day of campaigning, the Arizona
senator said, ``I fully understand that with all of these hundreds of thousands
of millions of dollars washing around Washington, controlled by special
interests, that we're all under suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has acknowledged that that he sent a letter as chairman of the Senate
Commerce Committee, urging FCC action on a TV license request by Paxson
Communications. The senator has made campaign trips aboard a Paxson plane, and
the company has coordinated political donations to McCain's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator, who reimbursed Paxson for the trips, did not argue for any
particular decision in his letter. He urged the FCC to resolve the matter one
way or another, after a two-year wait.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked if he regretted the letter, McCain said, ``Of course not. I acted in
order to have bureaucracies that are under my responsibility and oversight in
Congress to act in response to the taxpayers' wishes and needs. I've done that
on many, many occasions,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the FCC, McCain has sent 215 letters to the commission in the
past three years. During the same period, the commission has received 7,000 to
8,000 pieces of correspondence a year from members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   The three-term senator has erased Bush's lead in New Hampshire polls, making
him the main threat to the GOP front-runner and increasing scrutiny of his own
underdog campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   In private, McCain was said to be offended that his character is being
called into question, and suspicious that his political rivals had a hand in
published reports about the letter.
</P>
<P>
	   He was typically upbeat during his public events Thursday, and didn't seem
sensitive to the new scrutiny. Over lunch with Manchester firefighters, he
listened to their pitch for more federal money. ``You'll have my support in
return for this delightful (meal),'' McCain joked. ``Every politician has his
price. Mine is obviously a chili lunch.''
</P>
<P>
	   Afraid that a media frenzy was about to consume the campaign, aides have
spent hours cataloguing thousands of letters McCain has written regulators --
some of them on behalf of donors -- to be prepared if the documents become
public, which advisers expects will happen. They say none of the documents show
McCain in an unethical light.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides hoped the story would run its course by next week, but feared that TV
ads spotlighting the matter could give it longer life. They said they don't
expect any ads to air because Steve Forbes, who can afford the spots, wants
McCain to help weaken the front-running Bush. They are certain, aides said, that
Bush doesn't want to be viewed as a negative campaigner.
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, the Texas governor brushed off attempts by reporters to get him to
comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Senator McCain must answer these questions. Senator McCain is chairman of
a very powerful committee in the United States Senate. He's a committee
chairman, he's been there for a period of time to the point where he can earn
this chairmanship,'' Bush said. ``Ask him these questions. I'm a person that
comes from Texas. I'm not a committee chairman. I'm a governor.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rather than demanding McCain answer questions about his actions, aides said
Bush was trying to highlight the contrast between his work outside Washington
and McCain's service in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
	   In a good sign for McCain, he wasn't asked a single question about the
matter in a town hall with New Hampshire residents. Afterward, some voters
defended McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't see any problem with that part of his job of being senator,'' said
Gary Gordon of Bow, N.H. McCain is required to ``expedite things for his
constituents. Two years seems a long time to be waiting,'' Gordon said. ``Let's
get real.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 2035 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
