<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Approves Lethal Injection  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida lawmakers in a special session Thursday
passed a bill to give death row inmates the option of lethal injection rather
than the electric chair, which came under scrutiny because of fiery and bloody
executions in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate passed the bill unanimously, and the House by a vote of 102-5,
sending the measure to Gov. Jeb Bush, who was expected to sign it.
</P>
<P>
	   Still pending final action was a proposal to speed up appeals by death row
inmates. The Republican governor insisted that the measure come with any changes
to the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   Florida is one of only four states of the 38 with capital punishment that
require execution by electrocution -- the others are Georgia, Alabama, Nebraska.
Florida has used its electric chair since the early 1920s.
</P>
<P>
	   Flames have erupted during two electrocutions in the last decade, and the
last condemned man, Allen Lee ``Tiny'' Davis, suffered a nosebleed during his
electrocution. Pictures of his bloody body and contorted face were posted on the
Internet and viewed by hundreds of thousands of people after the state Supreme
Court upheld use of the electric chair.
</P>
<P>
	   Executions in Florida came to a halt when the U.S. Supreme Court agreed in
October to review whether the electric chair amounts to cruel and unusual
punishment. Switching to lethal injection would allow Bush to resume signing
death warrants.
</P>
<P>
	   The legislation passed Thursday makes lethal injection Florida's primary
method of execution, but allows condemned inmates to choose electrocution. Some
lawmakers said they approved the bill only because appeals challenging the
electric chair have halted executions.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We don't want the courts to be the legislators,'' Republican state Sen.
Ginny Brown-Waite said. ``My constituents want ... the delays stopped. We're
here today to make sure that justice truly is swift.''
</P>
<P>
	   The House voted 75-36 for Bush's appeals-reform package but failed to get
the two-thirds vote needed. Lawmakers planned to return to work on that issue
Friday morning. The Senate passed its version of the appeals bill 30-7, but it
was different than the House version.
</P>
<P>
	   The 44 people executed in Florida in the last 20 years went to the electric
chair more than 10 years after being sentenced. Bush wants that shortened to
five years.
</P>
<P>
	   Supporters of the appeals reforms -- mostly Republicans -- said the bill
would stop frivolous appeals and bring legitimate ones before a court more
quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents -- all Democrats -- argued that lawmakers were overstepping their
authority and usurping a role that belonged to the judiciary. They also
criticized their colleagues for defeating an amendment to allow racial bias to
be considered in appeals.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of the negotiations, Bush appointed a task force Thursday to study
issues of racial discrimination in capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
	   And senators pushing for lethal injection agreed to take up another bill to
ban the execution of mentally retarded people. That measure passed the Senate
unanimously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 2040 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orthodox Christmas Celebrated  </HEADLINE>
   By DINA KRAFT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BETHLEHEM, West Bank (AP) -- Leaders of the world's 15 Orthodox churches led
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat through a candlelit Christmas Mass in
Bethlehem, the town of Jesus' birth.
</P>
<P>
	   The midnight gathering Thursday marked an extraordinary bid for unity among
the world's sometimes fractious Eastern Orthodox churches, which held their
first synod in 60 years a day earlier in Jerusalem, and their first ever in the
Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
	   As church bells pealed, host Greek Orthodox Patriarch Diodoros I of
Jerusalem led Arafat into the recesses of the Church of the Nativity, a cave
where tradition says Jesus was born. Arafat, a Muslim, lit a candle.
</P>
<P>
	   Due to differences in the calendar, Orthodox Christmas falls on Jan. 7.
Orthodoxy's traditional domain includes more than 200 million worshippers and
encompasses Russia, much of Eastern Europe, the Balkans and some regions around
the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
	   About half the Palestinian Christians living in the West Bank, Gaza Strip
and Israel celebrate Christmas according to the Eastern calendar.
</P>
<P>
	   This year's Orthodox celebrations were enlivened by visits of Eastern
European heads of state, including Russia's Boris Yeltsin, who stepped down last
week as president.
</P>
<P>
	   The patriarchs led a procession to Bethlehem's Manger Square earlier
Thursday. Greek Orthodox priests wore red cloaks embroidered with gold thread.
Russian Orthodox priests marched in their long black robes and elaborate
headpieces.
</P>
<P>
	   Altar boys in white carried silver candlesticks and struggled to protect the
flames from a biting wind. And Palestinian and Jordanian choirs sang hymns.
</P>
<P>
	   Thousands of spectators, undeterred by the chilly weather, watched the
procession from behind police barricades.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are so many patriarchs and leaders from our country here,'' said
onlooker Natalie Klenova of Moscow, a government worker. ``It gives us so much
pride.''
</P>
<P>
	   In Cairo, thousands of Coptic Christians attended their faith's Christmas
mass, which was overshadowed by the weekend clashes between Muslims and
Christians in southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
	   Hymns filled Egypt's main cathedral in the mass, led by the head of the
Coptic Orthodox church's Pope Shenouda III.
</P>
<P>
	   Shenouda spoke of the peaceful relations between Muslims and Christians,
though he never referred directly to the Dec. 31-Jan. 2 violence around
el-Kusheh village, which left 20 people dead. Most of the victims were
Christians.
</P>
<P>
	   Shenouda also noted that the Coptic Christmas on Friday comes just a day
before the start of the Muslim holiday of Eid al-Fitr. ``We thank God that these
two feasts come consecutively symbolizing the national unity that we live in,''
he said. Christians form about 10 percent of Egypt's mostly Muslim population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 2041 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Candidates Deabte in N.H.  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DURHAM, N.H. (AP) -- An aggressive George W. Bush pledged in campaign debate
Thursday night to push for ``tax cuts, so help me God'' if elected to the White
House and accused presidential rival John McCain of seeking campaign finance
changes that would hurt the conservative cause.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, his insurgent candidacy at a crossroads in the first-in-the-nation
primary state, used the forum to strongly defend his actions on behalf of a
political donor who was seeking action from the Federal Communications
Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   The tax cut pledge uttered by Bush, the national GOP front-runner, was
all-but-unequivocal: ``If there's a recession it's important to cut taxes to
make sure the economy grows. ... It's also important to cut the taxes where
there's times of plenty. ... It's important to cut the taxes to make sure
Washington, D.C., does not spend the surplus.''
</P>
<P>
	   His questioner asked whether he was saying ``no new taxes, so help me God''
-- a reference to former President George Bush's no-new-taxes pledge that he
broke once he won the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not only no new taxes. This is tax cuts, so help me God,'' replied
Bush, Texas governor and son of the former president.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, McCain and the other GOP contenders, Steve Forbes, Alan Keyes, Gary
Bauer and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, met for 60 animated minutes on a stage at
the University New Hampshire -- the site of a debate one night earlier of the
Democratic presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
	   The series of debates continues Friday night in South Carolina, where the
GOP contenders will meet once again, and again next week as the opening round of
primaries approaches.
</P>
<P>
	   There was an incendiary exchange over gays in the military that followed the
pledges Wednesday night by both of the Democratic presidential hopefuls that
they would make sure that homosexuals could serve openly.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauer said that Democratic stance would further the ``radical homosexual
agenda,'' and an animated Keyes said, ``I will return to the ban on homosexuals
in the military.''
</P>
<P>
	   Said Bush, ``I'm a don't ask, don't tell man.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton administration's policy, which the president has said has not
worked well, is to allow gay service members if they do not make their sexual
orientation known.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said that policy could be fine-tuned, but he added, ``I cannot change
a policy that's working.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain swiftly parried Bush's attack on the issue of campaign finance and
possible damage to the Republican Party, noting that his proposal includes steps
to limit union political activity.
</P>
<P>
	   And he was unequivocal in defending a letter he wrote to the FCC on behalf
of a political donor. ``My job is to make the bureaucrats work for the people,''
said McCain, who is chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee. ``I would do the
same thing again, almost anytime.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain smiled broadly as he issued his defense -- keeping a widely rumored
temper in check -- although his aides fretted that the issue of the letter could
seriously damage a candidacy based on a pledge of rooting out the influence of
special interests.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, for one, declined to prod McCain on the issue. ``I thought his answer
was fine,'' he said when moderator Tim Russert asked for his opinion.
</P>
<P>
	   The political subtext explained the course of the debate. Bush's tax cut
pledge was designed to strike a chord in a state where residents are fiercely
proud there is no income tax.
</P>
<P>
	   And his criticism of McCain on campaign finance -- his jab that it would
hurt Republicans -- was designed to peel away GOP voters from his closest rival.
</P>
<P>
	   Similarly, McCain's chances for victory in New Hampshire rest with
independents, and his defense of his actions before the FCC seemed an effort to
assure those voters who are attracted to his image as a reformer who will end
politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
	   The 60-minute debate was feisty, and none of the men on stage hesitated to
interrupt.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm going to take some time here,'' Hatch declared at one point, more than
halfway through a confrontation in which he struggled for airtime.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauer underscored his signature issue, saying he would not appoint any
justice to the Supreme Court ``who would sacrifice even one child,'' a pledge he
has uttered often in his effort to show unbreakable opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes, a wealthy publisher, sharply criticized the Clinton administration's
decision to send a Cuban boy whose mother died escaping Havana back to his
homeland to be reunited with his father. The child is ``Bill Clinton's human
sacrifice to Fidel Castro,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   But the main political dynamic of the evening was the struggle between Bush
and McCain, close rivals in the polls in New Hampshire, which holds the first
primary of the year on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   The two argued over taxes and campaign finance and snapped at each other a
time or two.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said Bush's tax plan would use the entire surplus.
</P>
<P>
	   ``No it doesn't,'' retorted the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Yes it does,'' shot back McCain, standing a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush was asked at one point whether his personal religious beliefs would
affect his White House policies. Russert asked whether he would take the popular
Christian expression `What would Jesus do' into the Oval Office, and Bush
replied, ``I would take an expression into the Oval Office: 'Dear God Help
Me.'''
</P>
<P>
	   To which Bauer said, ``So would we.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 2044 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahamas Hangs Convicted Stabber  </HEADLINE>
   By DEBY NASH Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- A man who stabbed a German couple to death was
hanged Thursday, the fourth execution since the Bahamas resumed capital
punishment in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   David Mitchell, 27, was convicted in the stabbing deaths of Horst and Traude
Henning on the island of Abace, where they had lived for many years.
</P>
<P>
	   No motive was ever established for the 1994 killings, which occurred as the
couple was sleeping.
</P>
<P>
	   Three hangings had been scheduled Thursday, but a second person convicted
won a stay of execution and the third, 51-year-old John Higgs, committed suicide
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Higgs apparently slashed his wrists with a razor blade even though there was
a suicide watch and heavy security at Nassau's Fox Hill Prison ahead of the
proposed hangings. A coroner's inquest into Higgs' suicide began Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   A death notice for Mitchell was posted on a wooden board and hung from the
prison's gate.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 300 people turned out for his burial, some crying, some cheering,
as Mitchell's casket was lowered into the ground at a Nassau cemetery.
</P>
<P>
	   Two freshly dug graves on either side, intended for the other men who were
to be executed, stood empty.
</P>
<P>
	   Higgs was convicted of the 1993 murder of his wife, Joan, whose body was
found buried under a staircase in an unfinished apartment building in Nassau.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bahamas executed its first convict in 12 years in 1996, becoming the
first of several Caribbean countries to resume hangings in a bid to deter
increasing and more violent crime.
</P>
<P>
	   Twenty-five inmates remain on death row.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 2045 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debate Dodged Uncomfortable Issues  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush practically swore on a stack of Bibles
to cut taxes as president, but declined to say Thursday in a debate among
Republican candidates what would happen if the economy or national security
comes up against Armageddon.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush went down the same path of certitude that Vice President Al Gore took
when he vowed in a Democratic debate that a Gore administration would produce
budget surpluses -- period.
</P>
<P>
	   But Gore scooted back in a hurry when asked what might happen during a
national crisis, saying ``all bets are off.'' Bush let his pledge hang out there
when pressed, terming developments like wars ``extreme hypotheticals.''
</P>
<P>
	   Such a reluctance to confront uncomfortable possibilities, or even
present-day political realities, was evident throughout the GOP presidential
debate.
</P>
<P>
	   Steve Forbes, facing persistent questions on why his campaign seems not to
have caught fire in New Hampshire, cited the example of Pat Buchanan, who pulled
a surprise Republican primary victory in the state in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At this point he was in single digits'' in opinion polls, Forbes said. But
that was a touch melodramatic; Buchanan was at 15 percent in a major poll at the
comparable stage of the 1996 campaign -- about three weeks from the New
Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, Alan Keyes asserted that the Constitution address the separation of
church and state.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the phrase does not appear in the Constitution, the First Amendment
opens, ``Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion'' --
words used to build up a body of law that speaks to just such a separation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 2045 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Candidates Debate in N.H.  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DURHAM, N.H. (AP) -- An aggressive George W. Bush pledged in campaign debate
Thursday night to push for ``tax cuts, so help me God'' if elected to the White
House and accused presidential rival John McCain of seeking campaign finance
changes that would hurt the conservative cause.
</P>
<P>
