<HEADLINE> TV Coverage Of SLA Trial Denounced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Prosecutors argued Thursday that television coverage of
the bombing conspiracy trial of an alleged former member of the Symbionese
Liberation Army would endanger public safety by showing how terrorist groups
make bombs.
</P>
<P>
	   Court TV and Cable News Network have asked to televise the trial of Sara
Jane Olson. Her defense team supported the motion, saying her right to a fair
trial will be enhanced by TV coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors Michael Latin and Eleanor Hunter on Thursday opposed the
request.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Much of the testimony in this case will revolve around the making of
terrorist bombs,'' said their court filing. ``Experts will describe in explicit
detail how terrorist groups, like the SLA, make their bombs, how law enforcement
disarms them, and techniques used by law enforcement in tracking those
responsible for domestic terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Detailed gavel to gavel television coverage will hinder law enforcement
and be detrimental to public safety,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
	   Olson, formerly known as Kathleen Ann Soliah, is accused of planting pipe
bombs under two police cars in 1975 as part of a SLA plot to avenge the killings
of six SLA members in a Los Angeles police shootout. The devices did not
explode.
</P>
<P>
	   Superior Court Judge James Ideman did not immediately rule on the television
issue. So far, he has refused to admit TV cameras to hearings in the case. Trial
is set to begin next month.
</P>
<P>
	   Olson remained a fugitive for more than two decades and led an apparently
crime-free life as a doctor's wife and mother of three children until she was
arrested in June near her home in St. Paul, Minn. She has pleaded innocent and
is free on $1 million bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
