<HEADLINE> Lehman Bros. Earnings Jump 307 Pct.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Fourth-quarter earnings at Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc.
surged 307 percent to $301 million, well above analysts' predictions.
</P>
<P>
	   Lehman attributed the strong earnings numbers to record profits in the New
York-based company's investment banking and securities trading businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Lehman earned $2.28 a share, or 31 cents above analysts' expectations of
$1.97 a share, for the three months ended Nov. 30, the company said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   During the fourth quarter of 1998, the firm reported net income of $74
million, or 51 cents a share, as all of Wall Street suffered in the wake of a
global financial crisis brought on by economic strife in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
	   Lehman's shares rose along with most other banking stocks Thursday, rising
$2.93 3/4 to $72.87 1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   Net revenues, which exclude interest expenses, totaled $1.4 billion for the
quarter, or more than double the $665 million in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
	   "This year's record results reflect how far the firm has come since becoming
a public company five years ago. Underscoring our position as a leading global
investment bank, our earnings in 1999 represent a tenfold increase from our
first year's net income level," Richard S. Fuld Jr., chairman and chief
executive of Lehman, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   For the full fiscal year, profits totaled $1.13 billion, a 54 percent
increase from the $736 million in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Full year revenues were $5.3 billion vs. $4.1 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
