<HEADLINE> Rudy Crew Hired at U. of Washington  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- A day after his job ended as head of the nation's largest
school system, Rudy Crew was hired Thursday to lead a new institute at the
University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   Crew will be executive director of the school's fledgling Institute for K-12
Leadership, which has been in development since 1998. The institute aims to
provide training for current and aspiring school leaders. He starts his new
$175,000-a-year job Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   ``With the appointment of Rudy Crew, the UW takes a giant step in bringing
together the necessary resources for making a key contribution to public
education in America,'' said university President Richard McCormick.
</P>
<P>
	   Allen Glenn, dean of the College of Education, told reporters that Crew's
arrival marked the start of ``an exciting roller-coaster ride.''
</P>
<P>
	   Crew replied: ``If it's anything like the one I've been through, I'll
pass.''
</P>
<P>
	   Crew served as chancellor of New York City schools for four years. Last
spring, he clashed with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani over the issue of using
taxpayer-funded vouchers to send public students to private schools. Crew
opposed the idea, which the mayor supported.
</P>
<P>
	   On Christmas Eve, the city's Board of Education voted 4-3 to let him go. New
York schools have 1.1 million students.
</P>
<P>
	   Crew, 49, headed the Tacoma School District for two years before going to
New York. He has two children at the University of Washington and has maintained
a home outside Tacoma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
