<DOCNO> APW20000106.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Jack E. Brown
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHOENIX (AP) -- Jack E. Brown, an attorney noted for groundbreaking
intellectual property and antitrust cases, died Thursday of cancer. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of Brown's landmark cases involved protecting Apple Computer's ``look
and feel'' in a case against Microsoft, and preventing Franklin Computer Corp.
from cloning the Apple II personal computer.
</P>
<P>
	   Brown, a 1952 Harvard Law School graduate, was listed in the National Law
Journal as one of the 100 most influential lawyers in the United States.
Yvonne Duffy
</P>
<P>
	   ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Yvonne Duffy, a columnist on disabilities for the
Detroit Free Press, died Tuesday after her breathing tube became detached at her
home. She was 60.
</P>
<P>
	   Childhood polio had left Ms. Duffy unable to use her legs and one arm.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'd like to educate the non-disabled world about what we are doing and are
capable of doing,'' Ms. Duffy said when she began writing her column. ``And I'd
like to spotlight some interesting folks other than Helen Keller and Stephen
Hawking. You'd think they're the only folks who accomplished anything.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Duffy's column, ``Disabled in America,'' appeared on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
	   She is survived by an uncle, Alex Garvin of Toronto.
Walter Galenson
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Walter Galenson, an economist who made the first serious
Western attempt to measure labor productivity in the former Soviet Union, died
on Dec. 30. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
	   Galenson wrote or edited 28 books, including a 1954 study comparing labor
productivity in the Soviet Union and the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   His latest, published in 1998, was ``The World's Strongest Trade Unions,''
about Scandinavian unions.
Jenny Humbert-Droz
</P>
<P>
	   NEUCHATEL, Switzerland (AP) -- Jenny Humbert-Droz, one of Switzerland's
first feminists and communists, died Tuesday. She was 107.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1916, she married Jules Humbert-Droz, one of the founders of
Switzerland's Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
	   Lenin appointed her husband a secretary of the Moscow-based Communist
International, or Comintern, and in the 1920s Mrs. Humbert-Droz worked for the
organization as a translator.
</P>
<P>
	   The couple returned to Switzerland in 1928 after falling out of favor under
Stalin.
</P>
<P>
	   After the war, they rejoined the mainstream Social Democratic Party, and
Mrs. Humbert-Droz headed a socialist women's group in Zurich.
</P>
<P>
	   After her husband's death in 1971, she edited his memoirs and wrote her own
book, entitled ``One thought, one conscience, one battle.''
Roger Lapham Jr.
</P>
<P>
	   STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Roger Lapham Jr., a founding partner of the Oakland
Raiders, died Sunday of cancer. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
	   Lapham helped organize the Raiders, one of eight charter members of the
American Football League, which began operations in 1960 and eventually was
absorbed by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
	   His father, Roger, was mayor of San Francisco from 1943 to 1948.
Heyward Elliot McDonald
</P>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Heyward Elliott McDonald, a former South Carolina
legislator, died Wednesday of a heart attack. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
	   McDonald served in the South Carolina House of Representatives from 1963-66
and in the Senate from 1977-84.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to his time in the state Legislature, McDonald ran for the U.S.
House in 1970 but lost to Republican Floyd Spence.
John Milner
</P>
<P>
	   EAST POINT, Ga. (AP) -- John Milner, a member of National League
championship teams with the New York Mets and Pittsburgh Pirates, died Tuesday
of cancer. He was 50.
</P>
<P>
	   Milner, a first baseman and outfielder, spent 12 years in the majors, coming
up in 1971 with the Mets and playing with them in the 1973 World Series.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1978, he moved to Pittsburgh and was a member of the Pirates' World
Series champions a year later.
</P>
<P>
	   He split his final two seasons with Pittsburgh and Montreal.
J. Stewart Newlin
</P>
<P>
	   WELLINGTON, Kan. (AP) -- J. Stewart ``Stew'' Newlin, the former publisher of
the Wellington Daily News who was correspondent for The Associated Press in
Topeka from 1946-48, died Jan. 3 in Arizona. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
	   Newlin and his wife, Maggie, published the Daily News from the mid-1950s
until they sold the paper to former University of Kansas football coach Jack
Mitchell in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
	   Newlin was also a former managing editor of The Garden City Telegram before
he went to work for the AP in Kansas City and Topeka.
</P>
<P>
	   Newlin was a former president of the Kansas Press Association, and received
its Distinguished Service Award.
</P>
<P>
	   He is survived by a son, Harve; a daughter, Donna; two stepsons; a brother,
Dick; and a sister, Nancy Ashton.
Ervin J. Nutter
</P>
<P>
	   XENIA, Ohio (AP) -- Ervin J. Nutter, the businessman-philanthropist for whom
buildings at Wright State University and the University of Kentucky are named,
died Wednesday. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
	   Nutter founded Elano Corp., which fabricates metal parts for jet airplanes.
In 1985, he sold his interest in the company.
</P>
<P>
	   He donated more than $1.5 million to build the $34.5 million sports and
entertainment hall at Wright State, which opened in 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   Nutter, a University of Kentucky graduate, is a member of that university's
Hall of Distinguished Alumni. He and his wife, Zoe, donated $1 million to
establish professorships in mechanical engineering and $1 million to help build
the E.J. Nutter Football Training Facility.
</P>
<P>
	   In July, the Nutters donated $1 million to help build a learning and
research center at the National Aviation Hall of Fame in Dayton.
Swami Omkarananda
</P>
<P>
	   WINTERTHUR, Switzerland (AP) -- Swami Omkarananda, a Hindu monk and sect
leader who was imprisoned in Switzerland for attempted murder, died Tuesday of
the flu. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
	   Omkarananda was charged along with other members of the sect for being
behind a bomb attack at the home of Jakob Stucki, a lawmaker and Zurich police
chief.
</P>
<P>
	   He was sentenced to 14 years in prison for attempted murder. He was released
in 1985 and deported to India. A 15-year ban on his return to Switzerland was
due to expire later this year.
Victor Serebriakoff
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Victor Serebriakoff, who helped build Mensa into a worldwide
organization with thousands of members, died Saturday. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
	   Serebriakoff joined Mensa, the society for people with high IQs, in 1950 and
became its leader in 1954. He had an IQ of 161 and was the creator of several
popular IQ tests.
</P>
<P>
	   Under his stewardship, the organization grew to have more than 100,000
members. His posts included international general secretary, international
chairman, editor of the British Mensa magazine and the honorary international
president.
</P>
<P>
	   He wrote numerous books on the society and founded the Mensa Foundation for
Gifted Children.
Adam Yarmolinsky
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Adam Yarmolinsky, an architect of President Kennedy's New
Frontier policy, died Wednesday of leukemia. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
	   Yarmolinsky, who worked for the defense department from 1961 to 1964, helped
form the Kennedy administration's New Frontier, a legislative plan to improve
the nation's defense and bring about changes in health care, civil rights and
housing.
</P>
<P>
	   He also was deputy director of the President's Task Force on the War Against
Poverty in 1964, chief of the U.S. Emergency Relief Mission to the Dominican
Republic in 1965 and principal deputy assistant secretary of defense for
international security affairs from 1965 to 1966.
</P>
<P>
	   Yarmolinsky also served as counselor to the United States Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency from 1977 to 1979.
</P>
</TEXT>
