<HEADLINE> Juvenile Found Dead in Jail Cell  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROSSETT, Ark. (AP) -- A juvenile offender who escaped from a group home was
found dead in his jail cell just hours after being recaptured Thursday,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
	   The death appeared to have been suicide, police Chief Tommy Sturgeon said.
</P>
<P>
	   Christopher Howard, 16, was one of two juvenile offenders who escaped Dec.
28 from Youth Bridge, a group home in Fayetteville that contracts with the state
to house and counsel young offenders.
</P>
<P>
	   He was arrested Thursday morning next door to his mother's home in Crossett,
said Joe Quinn of the state Human Services Department.
</P>
<P>
	   About five hours later, Howard was found hanging in a Crossett jail cell,
police said. Sturgeon said police and paramedics were unable to revive him.
</P>
<P>
	   Arkansas State Police are investigating.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities said Howard and Jonathan Haynie, 16, of Camden, escaped in an
agency van Dec. 28 after overpowering a Youth Bridge employee.
</P>
<P>
	   Howard was committed to state custody Nov. 4 for a second-degree battery
offense. Haynie was committed Nov. 2 for an aggravated robbery offense and
probation revocation. He was arrested Sunday in Camden.
</P>
</TEXT>
