<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Off Welfare Lacking Insurance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A study of mothers leaving welfare found that one-third of
those who took jobs weren't covered by health insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   The number lacking health insurance was even higher among women who left
welfare but didn't work, even though many of them should be eligible for
Medicaid. Nearly half of these unemployed women didn't have insurance a year or
more after leaving welfare, according to the study to be published Monday in the
journal Health Affairs.
</P>
<P>
	   Children previously receiving welfare fared better when it comes to keeping
insurance, the study showed. Forty-seven percent were covered by Medicaid and 29
percent were covered by private insurance after one year. But 29 percent were
uninsured. The numbers add up to more than 100 percent because some children had
multiple sources of health insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   Families that leave welfare can still keep Medicaid if they meet certain
income or medical needs. The study says that many lose their Medicaid coverage
because eligibility rules are more complex and some caseworkers and welfare
recipients don't understand them.
</P>
<P>
	   The study didn't examine the reasons why women who get jobs after leaving
welfare don't have health insurance through their employers. The study's authors
said that other research shows that ex-welfare recipients have low-wage jobs
that don't offer insurance or, if insurance is offered, don't pay enough for
them to afford premiums.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Finding work does not guarantee that a former welfare recipient will also
obtain health care coverage,'' said author Bowen Garrett, a research associate
at the Urban Institute, one of the sponsors of the study of 1,004 women and
1,662 children who left welfare between 1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   The research was part of a project funded by several organizations,
including the Henry J. Kaiser Family.
</P>
<P>
	   The study is the latest evidence that low-income families leaving welfare
are losing insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   Auditors at the Health Care Financing Administration, which runs Medicaid,
found that some states are illegally denying benefits to poor families dropped
from the welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
	   People were losing Medicaid coverage because they were not told they were
eligible, were automatically dropped from computerized Medicaid files when they
got off welfare, or were improperly harassed by caseworkers when they applied
for coverage, auditors said.
</P>
<P>
	   A study last year by Families USA, a liberal consumer group, estimated that
675,000 people lost Medicaid coverage and had no other health insurance in 1997
due to strict new welfare rules.
</P>
<P>
	   Judy Waxman, director of government affairs at the group, said families who
lose insurance are at risk of returning to welfare because parents with sick
children will have to stay home.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If their kids get sick, they can't afford a doctor and the kids get sicker
-- then the parents have to leave work,'' said Waxman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 2244 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
