<HEADLINE> Mexico Official Defends Expulsions  </HEADLINE>
   By MARK STEVENSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A top Mexican official on Thursday defended the
expulsion of 12 U.S. citizens for attending a rebel-sponsored New Year
celebration in troubled-plagued Chiapas state.
</P>
<P>
	   The expulsions came amid complaints by human rights groups of strict limits
on foreign travel to Chiapas, where the leftist Zapatista rebels staged a brief
armed uprising six years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Alejandro Carrillo, the country's top immigration official, said the
expulsions were legal and justified.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Foreigners are not prohibited from attending local celebrations, but if
the celebrations have a political connection, that's interference'' in domestic
politics and grounds for expulsion under Mexican law, Carrillo told a Mexico
City news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   The government has frequently banned foreigners it accuses of being
sympathizers of the Chiapas-based Zapatistas. But human rights group charge that
independent observers have also been the focus of a campaign that has resulted
in hundreds of expulsions in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the 12 was Kerry Appel, a Denver man who built a business buying
coffee direct from Mexican farmers. They were detained at a government
checkpoint after attending the party. Mexico said their presence violated terms
of their visas by becoming involved in domestic political issues.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a tough decision, because I've had very good relations with the
Mexicans over the last 30 years,'' Appel, an outspoken rebel supporter, said in
San Cristobal, Chiapas. ``It appears there is a campaign to get all the
foreigners out of Indian villages'' in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
	   The Zapatista uprising was aimed at demanding greater democracy for Mexico's
Indians. Peace talks between the government and rebels have been held
intermittently and a truce remains in effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
