<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Rejoins Mideast Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- President Clinton plunged back into slow-moving
Mideast peace talks Thursday, meeting with Israel's prime minister and the
Syrian foreign minister after face-to-face negotiations between the two sides
ground to a halt.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. aim is a treaty that would exchange the Golan Heights, a strategic
border territory Israel has held for more than three decades, for diplomatic and
economic relations with Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton met separately for an hour each with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa. He then flew back to
Washington by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
	   A State Department spokesman, Philip Reeker, said Clinton would return
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, called the meetings constructive and
``obviously susbtantive,'' but did not say whether the president made any
headway.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Both the prime minister and the foreign minister are quite engaged,'' he
said. ``There are a lot of things that have to be worked through and it's going
to take more than one afternoon to work on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
	   There was no word on whether the president was able to set up a three-way
meeting or had resolved any of the knotty problems that must be overcome if
Israel is to swap territory for a peace treaty with Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   Syria began Wednesday to outline its offer in a mixed committee under the
supervision of Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk. A committee on new
border security measures met all day, as well.
</P>
<P>
	   But there were no face-to-face negotiations over Syria's key demand: a
specific timetable for Israel to relinquish the Golan Heights, which Syria lost
in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
	   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the talks, in their fourth
day, were still ``chugging along.'' But he said the American hosts were
dissatisfied with the pace and would like to see it accelerated.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton and Barak, along with their advisers, met for about 45 minutes, then
the two leaders spent an additional 20 minutes alone, said Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Sufficiently good and constructive'' was the way Rubin described the
meetings held by Clinton and Albright. Rubin said, however, U.S. officials were
not putting ``a lot of energy'' into getting the committees back together yet.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's intervention Thursday was his third of the week. On his arrival,
Clinton conferred with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on her own
90-minute meeting with al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
	   The president, wearing a leather flight jacket, waved to bystanders as he
alighted from his helicopter and made no statement. Marking the end of Ramadan,
Islam's holiest month, the White House issued a presidential message with a
prayer for peace.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We pray that the new moon will bring a new era of peace between nations --
in the Middle East and all across the world -- so people can emerge from the
shadows of violence and make better lives for their children,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   In Washington, Clinton's assistant for national security, Sandy Berger, told
reporters to ``not underestimate the degree of difficulty'' in the negotiations
being held near this oldest town in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These are very difficult issues that divide the parties,'' Berger said.
``They've been at war three times since the 1940s. There are very strong views
on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
	   In contrast to discontent within the Syrian delegation, Barak and his
delegation appeared pleased that the negotiations were focused on peace terms
and security measures, such as installing an early-warning system at the border
and clearing it of troops.
</P>
<P>
	   Barak found time Wednesday to jog and do calisthenics at a gymnasium in the
hotel the two delegations are sharing behind police barricades.
</P>
<P>
	   An Israel source, insisting on anonymity, said the talks were likely to go
into a second week -- after a weekend break -- and that Barak planned to stay
on.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said that Albright, meanwhile, had directed her assistants to prepare
a ``working document'' detailing negotiations held in 1996 as well as talks last
month in Washington and here this week.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That will enable us at the appropriate time to move forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked if Israel could be secure without retaining the Golan Heights, which
overlooks its northeastern towns that were targets of cross-border attacks
before 1967, Rubin said, ``Israel is going to have to make that decision.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We believe that Israel has legitimate security needs and we believe those
needs can be met,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
