<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norway Train Crash Prompts Boycott  </HEADLINE>
   By NILS MYKLBOST Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RENA, Norway (AP) -- Train engineers vowed to boycott a Norwegian rail line
until safety improves on Thursday, two days after passengers trains hit head-on
in a fiery crash that killed at least 17 people.
</P>
<P>
	   The confirmed death toll rose Thursday when searchers pulled five more
bodies from the scorched wreckage. But three more people were missing and
authorities said they expected the toll to hit at least 20.
</P>
<P>
	   The trains collided Tuesday about 110 miles north of Oslo. A raging fire
prevented rescuers from reaching some of the broken, twisted cars until hours
after the crash.
</P>
<P>
	   It was one of the worst train disasters in Norwegian history. The trains
were traveling at about 55 mph around a corner, and the engineers had no chance
to stop, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Railroad Engineer's Union said the Scandiavian country's 1,100
railroad engineers would boycott that line until safety measures were improved.
</P>
<P>
	   They also demanded that closed stations reopen and restore their staff
instead of relying solely on traffic controllers working from another site.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Station staff offer extra security because they call and ask the next
station whether the track is clear before a train can leave the station,'' Leiv
Helge Olsen, of the union, told newspapers.
</P>
<P>
	   The cause of the wreck was under investigation. But it appears so far that
one of the trains might have run a red stop signal, since no technical faults
had been found on the line.
</P>
<P>
	   The TV-2 television network reported that the train managers monitoring
traffic remotely may not have been able to warn the engineers because of a
mix-up over cellular telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
	   The trains burned for about six hours, making the rescue effort a nightmare
of intense heat amid the bitter cold of Norwegian winter. Some victims burned
alive, just out of reach of rescuers.
</P>
<P>
	   Though the weather improved Thursday, with temperatures rising above
freezing, work was still difficult because bodies had to be cut from the twisted
hulk of melted metal.
</P>
<P>
	   Rescuer Trond Simarud said a major worry was a 100-ton locomotive that was
overturned and feared highly unstable. It was being held in place by a military
tank, a backhoe and wire. The teams hoped to lift the engine out with the crane,
but it was not clear when that job would begin.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 30 passengers and crew known to have been injured, only three
remained hospitalized late Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 2310 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000106.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colleges Get Racist Letter Threats  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- Predominately black colleges in Alabama and
Tennessee have received letters threatening the ``total destruction of your
race'' and bearing the image of the Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
	   Letters postmarked Fayetteville, N.C., were sent to Oakwood College in
Huntsville, Alabama A&AMP;M University in Huntsville, Alabama State University in
Montgomery, and Stillman College in Tuscaloosa. They were also received by Fisk
University and Meharry Medical College in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was terribly distasteful and a racist type of letter,'' said Alabama
State spokeswoman Julie Debardelaben.
</P>
<P>
	   The anonymous messages said, ``Eventually, we'll get rid of you. The year
2000, the war escalates. ... We promise.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The total destruction of your race is our mission in life,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
	   The letters were sent in late December, but some were not received until
this week because of the holidays.
</P>
<P>
	   Security has been tightened at the two Tennessee schools, but not at the
Alabama schools, and police have alerted the FBI. FBI officials would not
comment on whether they were investigating the matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
