<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-06 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panic Spreads Through Ivory Coast  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- Rumors of gunfire spread panic through Ivory
Coast's commercial capital Thursday, less than two weeks after a former army
chief seized power in a largely bloodless coup.
</P>
<P>
	   Stores closed down, and residents fled the central business district as
rumors spread of gunshots in several in other areas. By late afternoon, however,
calm had been restored.
</P>
<P>
	   Western diplomats and military officials confirmed there were gunshots
Wednesday night at one of the main military bases.
</P>
<P>
	   It was unclear, though, what had provoked the shooting, or if there was more
gunfire Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Junta leader Gen. Robert Guei visited a number of bases Thursday to reassure
troops he was committed to addressing their grievances over pay and benefits.
Later, he issued a statement on national radio denying there was any unrest in
the country.
</P>
<P>
	   The military seized power Christmas Eve amid an economic decline in West
African country, which has been one of region's most stable and prosperous
countries.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, Guei named himself president and defense minister in an interim
coalition Cabinet, which will govern until democracy is restored.
</P>
<P>
	   The junta has promised a new constitution and elections to restore
democracy, but has not given a timetable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-06-00 2321 </TRAILER>
